(8, 'cold', 'undefined', 'undefined', 'undefined', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"list": ["temperature"], "text": "Cold is the presence of low temperature, especially in the atmosphere."}, {"list": ["subjective perception"], "text": "In common usage, cold is often a subjective perception."}, {"list": ["absolute zero", "Kelvin scale", "thermodynamic temperature"], "text": "A lower bound to temperature is absolute zero, defined as 0.00K on the Kelvin scale, an absolute thermodynamic temperature scale."}, {"list": ["Celsius scale", "Fahrenheit scale", "Rankine scale"], "text": "This corresponds to on the Celsius scale,  on the Fahrenheit scale, and  on the Rankine scale."}, {"list": ["thermal energy", "kinetic energy"], "text": "Since temperature relates to the thermal energy held by an object or a sample of matter, which is the kinetic energy of the random motion of the particle constituents of matter, an object will have less thermal energy when it is colder and more when it is hotter."}, {"text": "If it were possible to cool a system to absolute zero, all motion of the particles in a sample of matter would cease and they would be at complete rest in this classical sense."}, {"text": "The object would be described as having zero thermal energy."}, {"list": ["quantum mechanics", "zero-point energy", "uncertainty principle"], "text": "Microscopically in the description of quantum mechanics, however, matter still has zero-point energy even at absolute zero, because of the uncertainty principle."}, {"list": ["temperature"], "text": "Cooling refers to the process of becoming cold, or lowering in temperature."}, {"text": "This could be accomplished by removing heat from a system, or exposing the system to an environment with a lower temperature."}, {"list": ["Coolants", "fluids"], "text": "Coolants are fluids used to cool objects, prevent freezing and prevent erosion in machines."}, {"list": ["Air cooling", "air"], "text": "Air cooling is the process of cooling an object by exposing it to air."}, {"list": ["surface area", "mass"], "text": "This will only work if the air is at a lower temperature than the object, and the process can be enhanced by increasing the surface area or decreasing the mass of the object."}, {"list": ["ice", "dry ice", "liquid nitrogen"], "text": "Another common method of cooling is exposing an object to ice, dry ice, or liquid nitrogen."}, {"list": ["convection", "heat"], "text": "This works by convection; the heat is transferred from the relatively warm object to the relatively cold coolant."}, {"list": ["Laser cooling", "magnetic evaporative cooling"], "text": "Laser cooling and magnetic evaporative cooling are techniques used to reach very low temperatures."}, {"text": "In ancient times, ice was not adopted for food preservation but used to cool wine which the Romans had also done."}, {"list": ["Pliny", "Emperor Nero", "Zimri-Lim", "Mari Kingdom", "Euphrates"], "text": "According to Pliny, Emperor Nero invented the ice bucket to chill wines instead of adding it to wine to make it cold as it would dilute it.Some time around 1700 BC Zimri-Lim, king of Mari Kingdom in northwest Iraq had created an \\"icehouse\\" called bit shurpin at a location close to his capital city on the banks of the Euphrates."}, {"text": "In the 7th century BC the Chinese had used icehouses to preserve vegetables and fruits."}, {"list": ["Tang dynastic rule", "Eastern Chou Dynasty"], "text": "During the Tang dynastic rule in China (618 -907 AD) a document refers to the practice of using ice that was in vogue during the Eastern Chou Dynasty (770 -256 BC) by 94 workmen employed for \\"Ice-Service\\" to freeze everything from wine to dead bodies."}, {"list": ["Nintoku"], "text": "Shachtman says that in the 4th century AD, Nintoku, Japanese Emperor was given a gift by his brother of ice from a mountain."}, {"text": "The Emperor was so happy with the gift that he named the first of June as the \\"Day of Ice\\" and ceremoniously gave blocks of ice to his officials."}, {"text": "Even in ancient times, Shachtman says, in Egypt and India, night cooling by evaporation of water and heat radiation, and the ability of salts to lower the freezing temperature of water was practiced."}, {"list": ["carbon dioxide"], "text": "The ancient people of Rome and Greece were aware that boiled water cooled quicker than the ordinary water; the reason for this is that with boiling of water carbon dioxide and other gases, which are deterrents to cooling, are removed; but this fact was not known till the 17th century."}, {"list": ["Tom Shachtman"], "text": "According to Tom Shachtman, till early seventeenth century cold was considered a mystery without source which was linked with death; inexplicable and too fearsome to investigate."}, {"text": "Refrigeration by artificial means was an abhorrent idea as the thinking was for natural refrigeration though lot of consumable goods perished without any effort towards refrigeration."}, {"text": "In the early 1700s nobody tried to improve the efficacy of health, transportation or communications by mastering the knowledge of cold nor was there any effort to improve the comfort level of people by proper adoption of cold."}, {"list": ["snow", "snowflakes"], "text": "The reasons for conversion of snow in the heavens into water, on the earth, reason for formation of snowflakes, its slippery characteristics were not fathomed."}, {"text": "Snow measurements were not known."}, {"list": ["Cornelis Jacobszoon Drebbel"], "text": "Shachtman says it was Cornelis Jacobszoon Drebbel who was appointed in 1608 by James Stuart, King of England who believed in magicians to perform magical tricks such as to produce thunder lightning, lions, birds, trembling leaves and so forth."}, {"text": "It was Drebbel, in 1620, who demonstrated an experiment in the Westminster Abbey to the king and his courtiers on the power of cold."}, {"text": "On a summer day, Shachtman says, Drebbel had created a chill (lowered the temperature by several degrees) in the hall of the Abbey which made the king to shiver and run out of the hall with his entourage."}, {"text": "This was an incredible spectacle, says Shachtman."}, {"list": ["Florence"], "text": "On an earlier occasion several years back Giambattista dells Porta had demonstrated at the Abbey \\"ice fantasy gardens, intricate ice sculptures\\" and also iced drinks for banquets in Florence."}, {"list": ["Francis Bacon"], "text": "The only reference to the artificial freezing created by Drebbel was in a reference by Francis Bacon."}, {"text": "His demonstration was not taken seriously as it was considered as one of his magic tricks, as there was no practical application then."}, {"text": "Drebbel had not revealed his secrets."}, {"list": ["potassium nitrate"], "text": "Lord Chancellor Bacon, says Shachtman, who was advocating experimental science had in the publication Navum Organum published in the later part of 1620s had made an attempt to explain the artificial freezing experiment at Westminster Abbey, though he was not present during the demonstration, as \\"Nitre (or rather its spirit) is very cold, and hence nitre or salt when added to snow or ice intensifies the cold of the latter, the nitre by adding to its own cold, but the salt by supplying activity to the cold snow.\\" This explanation on the cold inducing aspects of nitre (now known as potassium nitrate) and salt was tried then by many scientists."}, {"text": "Shachtman says it was the lack of scientific knowledge in physics and chemistry that had held back progress in use of ice for beneficial purposes till the awakening came in the 17th century, brought about by a drastic change in societal transformation in religious thoughts."}, {"list": ["Robert Boyle"], "text": "The intellectual barrier was broken by Francis Bacon and Robert Boyle who followed him in this quest for knowledge of cold."}, {"text": "Boyle did extensive experimentation during the 17th century in the discipline of cold, and his research which related to pressure and volume, was the forerunner of research in the field of cold during the 19th century."}, {"text": "He explained his approach as \\"Bacon\'s identification of heat and cold as the right and left hands of nature\\"."}, {"list": ["Aristotle"], "text": "Boyle also refuted some of the theories mooted by Aristotle on cold by experimenting on transmission of cold from one material to the other."}, {"text": "He proved that water was the not the only source of cold but gold, silver and crystal, which had no water content, could also change to severe cold condition."}, {"text": "In the United States from about 1850 till end of 19th century export of ice was second only to cotton."}, {"list": ["Maryland"], "text": "The first ice box was developed by Thomas Moore, a farmer from Maryland in 1810 to carry butter in an oval shaped wooden tub."}, {"text": "The tub was provided with a metal lining in its interior and surrounded by a packing of ice."}, {"text": "A rabbit skin was used as insulation."}, {"text": "Moore also developed an ice box for domestic use with the container built over a space of 6 cuft which was filled with ice."}, {"text": "In 1825, ice harvesting by use of a horse drawn ice cutting device was invented by Nathaniel J. Wyeth."}, {"text": "The cut blocks of uniform size ice was a cheap method of food preservation widely practiced in the United States."}, {"text": "Also developed in 1855 was a steam powered device to haul 600 tons of ice per hour."}, {"text": "More innovations ensued."}, {"text": "Devices using compressed air as a refrigerants were invented."}, {"list": ["Iceboxes", "refrigerator"], "text": "Iceboxes were in widespread use from the mid-19th century to the 1930s, when the refrigerator was introduced into the home."}, {"list": ["ice houses"], "text": "Most municipally consumed ice was harvested in winter from snow-packed areas or frozen lakes, stored in ice houses, and delivered domestically as iceboxes became more common."}, {"text": "In 1913, refrigerators for home use were invented."}, {"text": "In 1923 Frigidaire introduced the first self-contained unit."}, {"list": ["Freon"], "text": "The introduction of Freon in the 1920s expanded the refrigerator market during the 1930s."}, {"text": "Home freezers as separate compartments (larger than necessary just for ice cubes) were introduced in 1940."}, {"text": "Frozen foods, previously a luxury item, became commonplace."}, {"list": ["physiological", "pathological", "human body"], "text": "Cold has numerous physiological and pathological effects on the human body, as well as on other organisms."}, {"list": ["psychological"], "text": "Cold environments may promote certain psychological traits, as well as having direct effects on the ability to move."}, {"list": ["Shivering"], "text": "Shivering is one of the first physiological responses to cold."}, {"list": ["frostbite", "sepsis", "hypothermia"], "text": "Extreme cold temperatures may lead to frostbite, sepsis, and hypothermia, which in turn may result in death."}, {"text": "Bibliography"}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d5/Antarctic_iceberg%2C_2001_-2.jpg", "file": "File:Antarctic iceberg, 2001 -2.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Antarctic_iceberg%2C_2001_-2.jpg/300px-Antarctic_iceberg%2C_2001_-2.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/64/Perrault_Leon_Out_In_The_Cold.jpg", "file": "File:Perrault Leon Out In The Cold.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/Perrault_Leon_Out_In_The_Cold.jpg/300px-Perrault_Leon_Out_In_The_Cold.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/Diving_signal_cold.jpg", "file": "File:Diving signal cold.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Diving_signal_cold.jpg/300px-Diving_signal_cold.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/Goose_bumps.jpg", "file": "File:Goose bumps.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Goose_bumps.jpg/300px-Goose_bumps.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bd/AntarcticaDomeCSnow.jpg", "file": "File:AntarcticaDomeCSnow.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/AntarcticaDomeCSnow.jpg/300px-AntarcticaDomeCSnow.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b2/Boomerang_nebula.jpg", "file": "File:Boomerang_nebula.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Boomerang_nebula.jpg/300px-Boomerang_nebula.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a6/Triton_moon_mosaic_Voyager_2_(large).jpg", "file": "File:Triton_moon_mosaic_Voyager_2_(large).jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Triton_moon_mosaic_Voyager_2_(large).jpg/300px-Triton_moon_mosaic_Voyager_2_(large).jpg"}]');
