(19, 'muscle_soreness', 'Delayed%20onset%20muscle%20soreness', '', 'Sports%20medicine', 'null', '{}', '{}', '[{"list": ["pain", "muscles", "exercise"], "text": "Delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS) is the pain and stiffness felt in muscles several hours to days after unaccustomed or strenuous exercise."}, {"text": "The soreness is felt most strongly 24 to 72 hours after the exercise."}, {"list": ["eccentric", "microtrauma", "muscle fibers"], "text": "It is thought to be caused by eccentric (lengthening) exercise, which causes small-scale damage (microtrauma) to the muscle fibers."}, {"text": "After such exercise, the muscle adapts rapidly to prevent muscle damage, and thereby soreness, if the exercise is repeated."}, {"list": ["symptom"], "text": "Delayed onset muscle soreness is one symptom of exercise-induced muscle damage."}, {"list": ["acute muscle soreness"], "text": "The other is acute muscle soreness, which appears during and immediately after exercise."}, {"text": "The soreness is perceived as a dull, aching pain in the affected muscle, often combined with tenderness and stiffness."}, {"text": "The pain is typically felt only when the muscle is stretched, contracted or put under pressure, not when it is at rest."}, {"list": ["hyperalgesia"], "text": "This tenderness, a characteristic symptom of DOMS, is also referred to as \\"muscular mechanical hyperalgesia\\"."}, {"text": "Although there is variance among exercises and individuals, the soreness usually increases in intensity in the first 24 hours after exercise."}, {"text": "It peaks from 24 to 72 hours, then subsides and disappears up to seven days after exercise."}, {"list": ["eccentric"], "text": "The soreness is caused by eccentric exercise, that is, exercise consisting of eccentric (lengthening) contractions of the muscle."}, {"list": ["Isometric", "concentric"], "text": "Isometric (static) exercise causes much less soreness, and concentric (shortening) exercise causes none."}, {"list": ["microtrauma"], "text": "The mechanism of delayed onset muscle soreness is not completely understood, but the pain is ultimately thought to be a result of microtrauma – mechanical damage at a very small scale – to the muscles being exercised."}, {"list": ["Theodore Hough"], "text": "DOMS was first described in 1902 by Theodore Hough, who concluded that this kind of soreness is \\"fundamentally the result of ruptures within the muscle\\"."}, {"list": ["lesions", "sarcomere"], "text": "According to this \\"muscle damage\\" theory of DOMS, these ruptures are microscopic lesions at the Z-line of the muscle sarcomere."}, {"text": "The soreness has been attributed to the increased tension force and muscle lengthening from eccentric exercise."}, {"list": ["actin", "myosin", "motor units"], "text": "This may cause the actin and myosin cross-bridges to separate prior to relaxation, ultimately causing greater tension on the remaining active motor units."}, {"text": "This increases the risk of broadening, smearing, and damage to the sarcomere."}, {"list": ["nociceptors"], "text": "When microtrauma occurs to these structures, nociceptors (pain receptors) within muscle connective tissues are stimulated and cause the sensation of pain."}, {"list": ["enzyme", "efflux"], "text": "Another explanation for the pain associated with DOMS is the \\"enzyme efflux\\" theory."}, {"list": ["calcium", "sarcoplasmic reticulum"], "text": "Following microtrauma, calcium that is normally stored in the sarcoplasmic reticulum accumulates in the damaged muscles."}, {"list": ["ATP"], "text": "Cellular respiration is inhibited and ATP needed to actively transport calcium back into the sarcoplasmic reticulum is also slowed."}, {"list": ["proteases", "phospholipases"], "text": "This accumulation of calcium may activate proteases and phospholipases which in turn break down and degenerate muscle protein."}, {"list": ["inflammation", "histamines", "prostaglandins", "potassium"], "text": "This causes inflammation, and in turn pain due to the accumulation of histamines, prostaglandins, and potassium."}, {"list": ["lactic acid"], "text": "An earlier theory posited that DOMS is connected to the build-up of lactic acid in the blood, which was thought to continue being produced following exercise."}, {"text": "This build-up of lactic acid was thought to be a toxic metabolic waste product that caused the perception of pain at a delayed stage."}, {"text": "This theory has been largely rejected, as concentric contractions which also produce lactic acid have been unable to cause DOMS."}, {"text": "Additionally, lactic acid is known from multiple studies to return to normal levels within one hour of exercise, and therefore cannot cause the pain that occurs much later."}, {"text": "Although delayed onset muscle soreness is a symptom associated with muscle damage, its magnitude does not necessarily reflect the magnitude of muscle damage."}, {"text": "Soreness is one of the temporary changes caused in muscles by unaccustomed eccentric exercise."}, {"text": "Other such changes include decreased muscle strength, reduced range of motion, and muscle swelling."}, {"text": "It has been shown, however, that these changes develop independently in time from one another and that the soreness is therefore not the cause of the reduction in muscle function."}, {"text": "Soreness might conceivably serve as a warning to reduce muscle activity so as to prevent further injury."}, {"text": "However, further activity temporarily alleviates the soreness, even though it causes more pain initially."}, {"text": "Continued light use of the sore muscle also has no adverse effect on recovery from soreness and does not exacerbate muscle damage."}, {"text": "It is therefore unlikely that soreness is in fact a warning sign not to use the affected muscle."}, {"text": "After performing an unaccustomed eccentric exercise and exhibiting severe soreness, the muscle rapidly adapts to reduce further damage from the same exercise."}, {"text": "This is called the \\"repeated-bout effect\\"."}, {"text": "As a result of this effect, not only is the soreness reduced, but other indicators of muscle damage, such as swelling, reduced strength and reduced range of motion, are also more quickly recovered from."}, {"text": "The effect is mostly, but not wholly, specific to the exercised muscle: experiments have shown that some of the protective effect is also conferred on other muscles."}, {"text": "The magnitude of the effect is subject to many variations, depending for instance on the time between bouts, the number and length of eccentric contractions and the exercise mode."}, {"text": "It also varies between people and between indicators of muscle damage."}, {"text": "Generally, though, the protective effect lasts for at least several weeks."}, {"text": "It seems to gradually decrease as time between bouts increases, and is undetectable after about one year."}, {"text": "The first bout does not need to be as intense as the subsequent bouts in order to confer at least some protection against soreness."}, {"text": "For instance, eccentric exercise performed at 40% of maximal strength has been shown to confer a protection of 20 to 60% from muscle damage incurred by a 100% strength exercise two to three weeks later."}, {"text": "Also, the repeated-bout effect appears even after a relatively small number of contractions, possibly as few as two."}, {"text": "In one study, a first bout of 10, 20 or 50 contractions provided equal protection for a second bout of 50 contractions three weeks later."}, {"text": "The reason for the protective effect is not yet understood."}, {"text": "A number of possible mechanisms, which may complement one another, have been proposed."}, {"list": ["protein synthesis"], "text": "These include neural adaptations (improved use and control of the muscle by the nervous system), mechanical adaptations (increased muscle stiffness or muscle support tissue), and cellular adaptations (adaptation to inflammatory response and increased protein synthesis, among others)."}, {"text": "Delayed onset muscle soreness can be reduced or prevented by gradually increasing the intensity of a new exercise program, thereby taking advantage of the repeated-bout effect."}, {"text": "Soreness can theoretically be avoided by limiting exercise to concentric and isometric contractions."}, {"text": "But eccentric contractions in some muscles are normally unavoidable during exercise, especially when muscles are fatigued."}, {"text": "Limiting the length of eccentric muscle extensions during exercise may afford some protection against soreness, but this may also not be practical depending on the mode of exercise."}, {"text": "A study comparing arm muscle training at different starting lengths found that training at the short length reduced muscle damage indicators by about 50% compared to the long length, but this effect was not found in leg muscles."}, {"list": ["Static stretching", "warming up"], "text": "Static stretching or warming up the muscles before or after exercise does not prevent soreness."}, {"text": "Overstretching can by itself cause soreness."}, {"text": "The use of correctly fitted, medical-grade, graduated compression garments such as socks and calf sleeves during the workout can reduce muscle oscillation and thus some of the micro-tears that contribute to DOMS."}, {"list": ["nutrition"], "text": "Proper nutrition to manage electrolytes and glycogen before and after exertion has also been proposed as a way to ease soreness."}, {"text": "Consuming more vitamin C may not prevent soreness,"}, {"list": ["curcumin"], "text": "but oral curcumin (2.5 gram, twice daily) likely reduces it."}, {"text": "The soreness usually disappears within about 72 hours after appearing."}, {"list": ["nerve mobilization", "sauna"], "text": "If treatment is desired, any measure that increases blood flow to the muscle, such as low-intensity activity, massage, nerve mobilization, hot baths, or a sauna visit may help somewhat."}, {"text": "Immersion in cool or icy water, an occasionally recommended remedy, was found to be ineffective in alleviating DOMS in one 2011 study, but effective in another."}, {"list": ["cryotherapy"], "text": "There is also insufficient evidence to determine whether whole-body cryotherapy – compared with passive rest or no whole-body cryotherapy – reduces DOMS, or improves subjective recovery, after exercise."}, {"text": "Counterintuitively, continued exercise may temporarily suppress the soreness."}, {"text": "Exercise increases pain thresholds and pain tolerance."}, {"list": ["exercise-induced analgesia", "endurance training", "resistance training"], "text": "This effect, called exercise-induced analgesia, is known to occur in endurance training (running, cycling, swimming), but little is known about whether it also occurs in resistance training."}, {"text": "There are claims in the literature that exercising sore muscles appears to be the best way to reduce or eliminate the soreness, but this has not yet been systematically investigated."}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[]'),
(20, 'nosebleed', 'Nosebleed', 'A%20three%20year%20old%20with%20a%20minor%20nosebleed%20from%20falling%20and%20hitting%20the%20floor%20with%20his%20face.%20Nosebleeds%20like%20this%20one%20normally%20resolve%20within%20a%20few%20minutes.', '', 'null', '{}', '{}', '[{"list": ["nose"], "text": "A nosebleed, also known as epistaxis, is the common occurrence of bleeding from the nose."}, {"list": ["blood", "nostrils"], "text": "It is usually noticed when the blood drains out through the nostrils."}, {"text": "There are two types: anterior (the most common), and posterior (less common, more likely to require medical attention)."}, {"list": ["nasolacrimal duct"], "text": "Sometimes in more severe cases, the blood can come up the nasolacrimal duct and out from the eye."}, {"list": ["nausea", "vomiting"], "text": "Fresh blood and clotted blood can also flow down into the stomach and cause nausea and vomiting."}, {"text": "Although the sight of large amounts of blood can be alarming and may warrant medical attention, nosebleeds are rarely fatal, accounting for only 4 of the 2.4 million deaths in the U.S. in 1999."}, {"text": "About 60% of people have a nosebleed at some point in their life."}, {"text": "About 10% of nosebleeds are serious."}, {"text": "The causes of nosebleeds can generally be divided into two categories, local and general factors, although a significant number of nosebleeds occur with no obvious cause."}, {"text": "Nosebleeds are due to the rupture of a blood vessel within the richly perfused nasal mucosa."}, {"text": "Rupture may be spontaneous or initiated by trauma."}, {"text": "Nosebleeds are reported in up to 60% of the population with peak incidences in those under the age of ten and over the age of 50 and appear to occur in males more than females."}, {"text": "An increase in blood pressure (e.g. due to general hypertension) tends to increase the duration of spontaneous epistaxis."}, {"list": ["Anticoagulant"], "text": "Anticoagulant medication and disorders of blood clotting can promote and prolong bleeding."}, {"text": "Spontaneous epistaxis is more common in the elderly as the nasal mucosa (lining) becomes dry and thin and blood pressure tends to be higher."}, {"text": "The elderly are also more prone to prolonged nose bleeds as their blood vessels are less able to constrict and control the bleeding."}, {"list": ["anterior"], "text": "The vast majority of nose bleeds occur in the anterior (front) part of the nose from the nasal septum."}, {"list": ["Kiesselbach\'s plexus"], "text": "This area is richly endowed with blood vessels (Kiesselbach\'s plexus)."}, {"list": ["Little\'s area"], "text": "This region is also known as Little\'s area."}, {"text": "Bleeding farther back in the nose is known as a posterior bleed and is usually due to bleeding from Woodruff\'s plexus, a venous plexus situated in the posterior part of inferior meatus."}, {"text": "Posterior bleeds are often prolonged and difficult to control."}, {"text": "They can be associated with bleeding from both nostrils and with a greater flow of blood into the mouth."}, {"text": "Sometimes blood flowing from other sources of bleeding passes through the nasal cavity and exits the nostrils."}, {"text": "It is thus blood coming from the nose but is not a true nosebleed, that is, not truly originating from the nasal cavity."}, {"text": "Such bleeding is called pseudoepistaxis ( + epistaxis)."}, {"list": ["blood coughed up", "airway"], "text": "Examples include blood coughed up through the airway and ending up in the nasal cavity, then dripping out."}, {"list": ["clots", "direct pressure"], "text": "The flow of blood normally stops when the blood clots, which may be encouraged by direct pressure applied by pinching the soft fleshy part of the nose."}, {"list": ["Little\'s area"], "text": "This applies pressure to Little\'s area (Kiesselbach\'s area), the source of the majority of nose bleeds, and promotes clotting."}, {"text": "Pressure should be firm and be applied for at least five minutes and up to 20 minutes; tilting the head forward helps decrease the chance of nausea and airway obstruction."}, {"text": "Swallowing excess blood can irritate the stomach and cause vomiting."}, {"text": "The local application of a vasoconstrictive agent has been shown to reduce the bleeding time in benign cases of epistaxis."}, {"list": ["oxymetazoline", "phenylephrine", "allergic rhinitis"], "text": "The drugs oxymetazoline or phenylephrine are widely available in over-the-counter nasal sprays for the treatment of allergic rhinitis, and they may be used for this purpose."}, {"text": "If these simple measures do not work then medical intervention may be needed to stop bleeding."}, {"list": ["silver nitrate"], "text": "The use of silver nitrate to cauterize bleeding blood vessels is common but not very useful for those with more than mild bleeding."}, {"text": "It is also often painful even when freezing is used."}, {"text": "There are two types of nasal packing, anterior nasal packing and posterior nasal packing."}, {"text": "There are a number of different types of anterior nasal packs."}, {"text": "Some use gauze and others use balloons."}, {"list": ["Foley catheter"], "text": "Posterior packing can be achieved by using a Foley catheter, blowing up the balloon when it is in the back of the throat, and applying traction."}, {"list": ["Merocel packing"], "text": "Ribbon gauze or Merocel packing can also be used."}, {"list": ["surgicel"], "text": "There are also several dissolvable packing materials, such as surgicel that function as a pack but are not removed and dissolve after a few days."}, {"text": "Packing is generally left in for two to five days."}, {"text": "Ongoing bleeding despite good nasal packing is a surgical emergency and can be treated by endoscopic evaluation of the nasal cavity under general anaesthesia to identify an elusive bleeding point or to directly ligate (tie off) the blood vessels supplying the nose."}, {"list": ["sphenopalatine", "ethmoidal"], "text": "These blood vessels include the sphenopalatine, anterior and posterior ethmoidal arteries."}, {"list": ["carotid artery"], "text": "More rarely the maxillary or a branch of the external carotid artery can be ligated."}, {"list": ["embolization"], "text": "The bleeding can also be stopped by intra-arterial embolization using a catheter placed in the groin and threaded up the aorta to the bleeding vessel by an interventional radiologist."}, {"text": "There is no difference in outcomes between embolization and ligation as treatment options, but embolization is considerably more expensive."}, {"text": "Continued bleeding may be an indication of more serious underlying conditions."}, {"text": "The utility of local cooling of the head and neck is controversial."}, {"text": "Some state that applying ice to the nose or forehead is not useful."}, {"text": "Others feel that it may promote vasoconstriction of the nasal blood vessels and thus be useful."}, {"list": ["antibiotic"], "text": "Application of a topical antibiotic ointment to the nasal mucosa has been shown to be an effective treatment for recurrent epistaxis."}, {"text": "One study found it as effective as nasal cautery in the prevention of recurrent epistaxis in people without active bleeding at the time of treatment—both had a success rate of approximately 50 percent."}, {"list": ["manga", "anime"], "text": "In the visual language of Japanese comics (manga) and animation (anime), a sudden, violent nosebleed indicates that the bleeding person is sexually aroused."}, {"list": ["Western fiction"], "text": "Separately in Western fiction, nosebleeds often signify intense mental focus or effort, particularly during the use of psychic powers."}, {"list": ["nosebleed section"], "text": "In American and Canadian usage, \\"nosebleed section\\" or \\"nosebleed seats\\" are common slang for seating at sporting or other spectator events that are the highest up and farthest away from the event."}, {"text": "The reference alludes to the propensity for nasal hemorrhage at high altitudes, usually owing to lower barometric pressure."}, {"list": ["Sioux"], "text": "The oral history of the Native American Sioux tribe includes reference to women who experience nosebleeds as a result of a lover\'s playing of music, implying sexual arousal."}, {"list": ["Finnish language"], "text": "In Finnish language, \\"begging for a nosebleed\\" is commonly used in abstract meaning to describe self-destructive behaviour, for example ignoring safety procedures or deliberately aggravating stronger parties."}, {"list": ["Filipino"], "text": "In Filipino slang, to \\"have a nosebleed\\" is to have serious difficulty conversing in English with a fluent or native English speaker."}, {"list": ["examination", "job interview"], "text": "It can also refer to anxiety brought on by a stressful event such as an examination or a job interview."}, {"list": ["Dutch language"], "text": "In the Dutch language, \\"pretending to have a nosebleed\\" is a saying that means pretending not to know anything about something, when actually being involved somehow."}, {"text": "The word epistaxis () is from epistazo, \\"to bleed from the nose\\" from  epi, \\"above, over\\" and  stazo, \\"to drip [from the nostrils]\\"."}, {"list": ["National Library of Medicine"], "text": "* National Library of Medicine - Describes causes, solutions, and prevention of nosebleeds"}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/db/Boxing_children_-_bloody_nose.jpg", "file": "File:Boxing children - bloody nose.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Boxing_children_-_bloody_nose.jpg/300px-Boxing_children_-_bloody_nose.jpg"}]'),
(21, 'pink_eye', 'Conjunctivitis', 'An%20eye%20with%20viral%20conjunctivitis', 'Ophthalmology', '["Reddish eye", "scratchiness"]', '{"desc": "Based on symptoms, microbial culture", "list": ["microbial culture"]}', '{"desc": "Viral, bacterial, allergies", "list": ["Viral", "bacterial"]}', '[{"list": ["inflammation", "outermost layer of the white part of the eye", "eyelid"], "text": "Conjunctivitis, also known as pink eye, is inflammation of the outermost layer of the white part of the eye and the inner surface of the eyelid."}, {"text": "It makes the eye appear pink or reddish."}, {"text": "There may also be pain, burning, scratchiness, or itchiness."}, {"text": "The affected eye may have increased tears or be \\"stuck shut\\" in the morning."}, {"text": "Swelling of the white part of the eye may also occur."}, {"text": "Itching of the eye is more common in cases due to allergies."}, {"text": "Conjunctivitis can affect one or both eyes."}, {"list": ["viral", "bacterial"], "text": "The most common infectious causes are viral followed by bacterial."}, {"list": ["common cold"], "text": "The viral infection may occur along with other symptoms of a common cold."}, {"text": "Viral and bacterial cases are easily spread between people."}, {"list": ["pollen"], "text": "Allergies to pollen or animal hair is also a common cause."}, {"text": "Diagnosis is often based on signs and symptoms."}, {"list": ["culture"], "text": "Occasionally a sample of the discharge is sent for culture."}, {"list": ["handwashing"], "text": "Prevention is partly by handwashing."}, {"text": "Treatment depends on the underlying cause."}, {"text": "In the majority of viral cases, there is no specific treatment."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Most cases due to a bacterial infection will also resolve without treatment; however, antibiotics can shorten the illness."}, {"list": ["contact lens", "gonorrhea", "chlamydia"], "text": "Those who wear contact lens and those with either gonorrhea or chlamydia as the cause should be treated."}, {"list": ["antihistamine", "mast cell inhibitor"], "text": "Allergic cases can be treated with antihistamine or mast cell inhibitor drops."}, {"text": "About 3 to 6 million people get conjunctivitis each year in the United States."}, {"text": "In adults viral causes are more common, while in children bacterial causes are more common."}, {"text": "Typically people get better in one or two weeks."}, {"list": ["visual loss", "sensitivity to light", "herpes"], "text": "If there is visual loss, significant pain, sensitivity to light, signs of herpes, or a person is not improving after a week, further diagnosis and treatment may be required."}, {"list": ["neonatal conjunctivitis"], "text": "Conjunctivitis in a newborn, known as neonatal conjunctivitis, may also require specific treatment."}, {"list": ["Red eye", "swelling of conjunctiva", "watering"], "text": "Red eye, swelling of conjunctiva and watering of the eyes are symptoms common to all forms of conjunctivitis."}, {"list": ["pupils", "visual acuity"], "text": "However, the pupils should be normally reactive, and the visual acuity normal."}, {"list": ["respiratory tract", "common cold", "sore throat"], "text": "Viral conjunctivitis is often associated with an infection of the upper respiratory tract, a common cold, or a sore throat."}, {"text": "Its symptoms include excessive watering and itching."}, {"text": "The infection usually begins with one eye, but may spread easily to the other."}, {"list": ["conjunctiva", "ciliary", "iritis", "microscopy", "lymphoid follicles", "tarsal", "punctate keratitis"], "text": "Viral conjunctivitis shows a fine, diffuse pinkness of the conjunctiva, which is easily mistaken for the ciliary infection of iris (iritis), but there are usually corroborative signs on microscopy, particularly numerous lymphoid follicles on the tarsal conjunctiva, and sometimes a punctate keratitis."}, {"list": ["Allergic conjunctivitis", "inflammation", "conjunctiva", "membrane", "allergy"], "text": "Allergic conjunctivitis is inflammation of the conjunctiva (the membrane covering the white part of the eye) due to allergy."}, {"list": ["Allergens"], "text": "Allergens differ among patients."}, {"list": ["vasodilation", "blood vessels", "swelling", "conjunctiva", "itching", "lacrimation", "tears"], "text": "Symptoms consist of redness (mainly due to vasodilation of the peripheral small blood vessels), swelling of the conjunctiva, itching, and increased lacrimation (production of tears)."}, {"list": ["rhinitis"], "text": "If this is combined with rhinitis, the condition is termed \\"allergic rhinoconjunctivitis\\"."}, {"list": ["histamine", "mast cells", "nerve endings"], "text": "The symptoms are due to release of histamine and other active substances by mast cells, which stimulate dilation of blood vessels, irritate nerve endings, and increase secretion of tears."}, {"list": ["redness", "eyelid", "mucopurulent discharge"], "text": "Bacterial conjunctivitis causes the rapid onset of conjunctival redness, swelling of the eyelid, and mucopurulent discharge."}, {"text": "Typically, symptoms develop first in one eye, but may spread to the other eye within 2–5 days."}, {"list": ["pyogenic", "bacteria", "mucopurulent discharge"], "text": "Bacterial conjunctivitis due to common pyogenic (pus-producing) bacteria causes marked grittiness/irritation and a stringy, opaque, greyish or yellowish mucopurulent discharge that may cause the lids to stick together, especially after sleep."}, {"text": "Severe crusting of the infected eye and the surrounding skin may also occur."}, {"text": "The gritty and/or scratchy feeling is sometimes localized enough for patients to insist they must have a foreign body in the eye."}, {"list": ["pyogenic"], "text": "The more acute pyogenic infections can be painful."}, {"list": ["Staphylococci", "Streptococci", "Haemophilus sp"], "text": "Common bacteria responsible for non-acute bacterial conjunctivitis are Staphylococci, Streptococci, Haemophilus sp."}, {"list": ["Chlamydia trachomatis"], "text": "Less commonly Chlamydia trachomatis is involved."}, {"list": ["Chlamydia trachomatis\'\'", "Moraxella\'\'", "exudative"], "text": "Bacteria such as Chlamydia trachomatis or Moraxella can cause a non-exudative but persistent conjunctivitis without much redness."}, {"list": ["membranes"], "text": "Bacterial conjunctivitis may cause the production of membranes or pseudomembranes that cover the conjunctiva."}, {"list": ["inflammatory cells"], "text": "Pseudomembranes consist of a combination of inflammatory cells and exudates, and are loosely adherent to the conjunctiva, while true membranes are more tightly adherent and cannot be easily peeled away."}, {"list": ["Neisseria gonorrhoeae", "hemolytic", "streptococci", "C. diphtheriae"], "text": "Cases of bacterial conjunctivitis that involve the production of membranes or pseudomembranes are associated with Neisseria gonorrhoeae, β-hemolytic streptococci, and C. diphtheriae."}, {"list": ["Corynebacterium diphtheriae\'\'"], "text": "Corynebacterium diphtheriae causes membrane formation in conjunctiva of non-immunized children."}, {"list": ["acidic", "alkali"], "text": "Chemical eye injury is due to either an acidic or alkali substance getting in the eye."}, {"text": "Alkalis are typically worse than acidic burns."}, {"list": ["cornea"], "text": "Mild burns will produce conjunctivitis, while more severe burns may cause the cornea to turn white."}, {"list": ["Litmus paper", "pH"], "text": "Litmus paper is an easy way to rule out the diagnosis by verifying that the pH is within the normal range of 7.0—7.2."}, {"list": ["irrigation"], "text": "Large volumes of irrigation is the treatment of choice and should continue until the pH is 6—8."}, {"list": ["Local anaesthetic", "eye drops"], "text": "Local anaesthetic eye drops can be used to decrease the pain."}, {"text": "Irritant or toxic conjunctivitis show primarily marked redness."}, {"text": "If due to splash injury, it is often present in only the lower conjunctival ."}, {"list": ["caustic", "alkalis", "sodium hydroxide", "necrosis", "sloughing", "epithelium"], "text": "With some chemicals, above all with caustic alkalis such as sodium hydroxide, there may be necrosis of the conjunctiva with a deceptively white eye due to vascular closure, followed by sloughing of the dead epithelium."}, {"list": ["anterior uveitis"], "text": "This is likely to be associated with slit-lamp evidence of anterior uveitis."}, {"list": ["Chlamydia trachomatis\'\'", "purulent"], "text": "Inclusion conjunctivitis of the newborn (ICN) is a conjunctivitis that may be caused by the bacteria Chlamydia trachomatis, and may lead to acute, purulent conjunctivitis."}, {"text": "However, it is usually self-healing."}, {"text": "Conjunctivitis is identified by irritation and redness of the conjunctiva."}, {"list": ["pyogenic", "slit lamp"], "text": "Except in obvious pyogenic or toxic/chemical conjunctivitis, a slit lamp (biomicroscope) is needed to have any confidence in the diagnosis."}, {"list": ["bulbar"], "text": "Examination of the tarsal conjunctiva is usually more diagnostic than the bulbar conjunctiva."}, {"text": "Conjunctivitis, when caused by an infection, is most commonly caused by a viral infection."}, {"text": "Bacterial infections, allergies, other irritants, and dryness are also common causes."}, {"list": ["contaminated objects", "water"], "text": "Both bacterial and viral infections are contagious and passed from person to person, but can also spread through contaminated objects or water."}, {"list": ["Adenoviruses", "adenoviral keratoconjunctivitis"], "text": "Adenoviruses is the most common cause of viral conjunctivitis (adenoviral keratoconjunctivitis)."}, {"list": ["Herpetic keratoconjunctivitis", "herpes simplex", "acyclovir"], "text": "Herpetic keratoconjunctivitis (caused by herpes simplex viruses) can be serious and requires treatment with acyclovir."}, {"list": ["enteroviruses", "Coxsackievirus"], "text": "Acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is a highly contagious disease caused by one of two enteroviruses, Enterovirus 70 and Coxsackievirus A24."}, {"list": ["Ghana", "epidemics"], "text": "These were first identified in an outbreak in Ghana in 1969, and have spread worldwide since then, causing several epidemics."}, {"list": ["Staphylococcus aureus\'\'", "Streptococcus pneumoniae\'\'", "Haemophilus influenzae\'\'"], "text": "The most common causes of acute bacterial conjunctivitis are Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and Haemophilus influenzae."}, {"list": ["Neisseria gonorrhoeae\'\'", "N. meningitidis\'\'"], "text": "Though very rare, hyperacute cases are usually caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae or N. meningitidis."}, {"list": ["Staphylococcus aureus\'\'", "Moraxella lacunata\'\'"], "text": "Chronic cases of bacterial conjunctivitis are those lasting longer than 3 weeks, and are typically caused by Staphylococcus aureus, Moraxella lacunata, or gram-negative enteric flora."}, {"list": ["allergens", "pollen", "perfumes", "cosmetics", "smoke", "dust mites", "Balsam of Peru"], "text": "Conjunctivitis may also be caused by allergens such as pollen, perfumes, cosmetics, smoke, dust mites, Balsam of Peru, and eye drops."}, {"list": ["reactive arthritis", "autoimmune"], "text": "Conjunctivitis is part of the triad of reactive arthritis, which is thought to be caused by autoimmune cross-reactivity following certain bacterial infections."}, {"list": ["HLA-B27"], "text": "Reactive arthritis is highly associated with HLA-B27."}, {"list": ["relapsing polychondritis"], "text": "Conjunctivitis is associated with the autoimmune disease relapsing polychondritis."}, {"list": ["Cultures"], "text": "Cultures are not often taken or needed as most cases resolve either with time or typical antibiotics."}, {"list": ["bacterial culture", "antibiotics"], "text": "Swabs for bacterial culture are necessary if the history and signs suggest bacterial conjunctivitis but there is no response to topical antibiotics."}, {"list": ["epidemic"], "text": "Viral culture may be appropriate in epidemic case clusters."}, {"list": ["patch test", "allergen"], "text": "A patch test is used to identify the causative allergen in the case where conjunctivitis is caused by allergy."}, {"list": ["cytology", "chlamydial", "fungal", "allergy", "dysplasia"], "text": "Conjunctival scrapes for cytology can be useful in detecting chlamydial and fungal infections, allergy, and dysplasia, but are rarely done because of the cost and the general lack of laboratory staff experienced in handling ocular specimens."}, {"list": ["biopsy", "granulomatous", "sarcoidosis", "dysplasia"], "text": "Conjunctival incisional biopsy is occasionally done when granulomatous diseases (e.g., sarcoidosis) or dysplasia are suspected."}, {"text": "Classification can be either by cause or by extent of the inflamed area."}, {"list": ["blepharitis", "eyelids"], "text": "Blepharoconjunctivitis is the dual combination of conjunctivitis with blepharitis (inflammation of the eyelids)."}, {"list": ["Keratoconjunctivitis", "keratitis", "corneal"], "text": "Keratoconjunctivitis is the combination of conjunctivitis and keratitis (corneal inflammation)."}, {"text": "Blepharokeratoconjunctivitis is the combination of conjunctivitis with blepharitis and keratitis."}, {"text": "It is clinically defined by changes of the lid margin, meibomian gland dysfunction, redness of the eye, conjunctival chemosis and inflammation of the cornea."}, {"text": "There are more serious conditions that can present with a red eye such as infectious keratitis, angle-closure glaucoma, or iritis."}, {"text": "These conditions require the urgent attention of an ophthalmologist."}, {"text": "Signs of such conditions include decreased vision, significantly increased sensitivity to light, inability to keep eye open, a pupil that does not respond to light, or a severe headache with nausea."}, {"text": "Fluctuating blurring is common, due to tearing and mucoid discharge."}, {"text": "Mild photophobia is common."}, {"list": ["glaucoma", "uveitis", "keratitis", "meningitis", "carotico-cavernous fistula"], "text": "However, if any of these symptoms are prominent, it is important to consider other diseases such as glaucoma, uveitis, keratitis and even meningitis or carotico-cavernous fistula."}, {"text": "A more comprehensive differential diagnosis for the red or painful eye includes:"}, {"text": "The best effective prevention is hygiene and not rubbing the eyes by infected hands."}, {"list": ["adenovirus", "haemophilus influenzae", "pneumococcus", "neisseria meningitidis"], "text": "Vaccination against adenovirus, haemophilus influenzae, pneumococcus, and neisseria meningitidis is also effective."}, {"list": ["conjunctivitis following birth"], "text": "Povidone-iodine eye solution has been found to prevent conjunctivitis following birth."}, {"text": "As it is less expensive it is being more commonly used for this purpose globally."}, {"text": "Conjunctivitis resolves in 65% of cases without treatment, within two to five days."}, {"text": "The prescription of antibiotics is not necessary in most cases."}, {"text": "Viral conjunctivitis usually resolves on its own and does not require any specific treatment."}, {"list": ["Antihistamines", "diphenhydramine", "mast cell stabilizers", "cromolyn"], "text": "Antihistamines (e.g., diphenhydramine) or mast cell stabilizers (e.g., cromolyn) may be used to help with the symptoms."}, {"list": ["Povidone iodine"], "text": "Povidone iodine has been suggested as a treatment, but as of 2008 evidence to support it was poor."}, {"list": ["artificial tears"], "text": "For the allergic type, cool water poured over the face with the head inclined downward constricts capillaries, and artificial tears sometimes relieve discomfort in mild cases."}, {"list": ["nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory medications", "antihistamines"], "text": "In more severe cases, nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory medications and antihistamines may be prescribed."}, {"text": "Persistent allergic conjunctivitis may also require topical steroid drops."}, {"text": "Bacterial conjunctivitis usually resolves without treatment."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Topical antibiotics may be needed only if no improvement is observed after three days."}, {"text": "No serious effects were noted either with or without treatment."}, {"text": "As they do speed healing in bacterial conjunctivitis, their use may be considered."}, {"list": ["immunocompromised", "chlamydia", "gonorrhea"], "text": "In those who wear contact lenses, are immunocompromised, have disease which is thought to be due to chlamydia or gonorrhea, have a fair bit of pain, or who have lots of discharge, antibiotics are recommended."}, {"text": "Gonorrhea or chlamydia infections require both oral and topical antibiotics."}, {"text": "When appropriate, the choice of antibiotic varies, differing based on the cause (if known) or the likely cause of the conjunctivitis."}, {"list": ["Fluoroquinolones", "sodium sulfacetamide", "trimethoprim/polymyxin"], "text": "Fluoroquinolones, sodium sulfacetamide, or trimethoprim/polymyxin may be used, typically for 7–10 days."}, {"list": ["penicillin"], "text": "Cases of meningococcal conjunctivitis can also be treated with systemic penicillin, as long as the strain is sensitive to penicillin."}, {"text": "When investigated as a treatment, Povidone-iodine ophthalmic solution has also been observed to have some effectiveness against bacterial and chlamydial conjunctivitis, with a possible role suggested in locations where topical antibiotics are unavailable or costly."}, {"list": ["irrigation", "Ringer\'s lactate", "saline solution"], "text": "Conjunctivitis due to chemicals is treated via irrigation with Ringer\'s lactate or saline solution."}, {"list": ["alkali"], "text": "Chemical injuries (particularly alkali burns) are medical emergencies, as they can lead to severe scarring and intraocular damage."}, {"text": "People with chemically induced conjunctivitis should not touch their eyes, regardless of whether or not their hands are clean, as they run the risk of spreading the condition to another eye."}, {"text": "Conjunctivitis is the most common eye disease."}, {"list": ["adenovirus"], "text": "An adenovirus was first isolated by Rowe et al. in 1953."}, {"text": "Two years later Jawetz et al. published on epidemic keratoconjunctivitis."}, {"list": ["Chennai"], "text": "\\"Madras eye\\" is a colloquial term that has been used in India for the disease, with one explanation relating to a connection with a former superintendent of the Regional Institute of Ophthalmology in the city of Madras (the present-day Chennai)."}]', '{"list": ["Handwashing"], "conditions": ["Handwashing"]}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ee/An_eye_with_viral_conjunctivitis.jpg", "file": "File:An eye with viral conjunctivitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/An_eye_with_viral_conjunctivitis.jpg/300px-An_eye_with_viral_conjunctivitis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Hemorragicconjunctivitis2.jpg", "file": "File:Hemorragicconjunctivitis2.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Hemorragicconjunctivitis2.jpg/300px-Hemorragicconjunctivitis2.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d7/Allergicconjunctivitis.jpg", "file": "File:Allergicconjunctivitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Allergicconjunctivitis.jpg/300px-Allergicconjunctivitis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/90/Swollen_eye_with_conjunctivitis.jpg", "file": "File:Swollen eye with conjunctivitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Swollen_eye_with_conjunctivitis.jpg/300px-Swollen_eye_with_conjunctivitis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/Membranous_conjunctivitis.jpg", "file": "File:Membranous conjunctivitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Membranous_conjunctivitis.jpg/300px-Membranous_conjunctivitis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b9/Chlamydial-conjunctivitis.jpg", "file": "File:Chlamydial-conjunctivitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Chlamydial-conjunctivitis.jpg/300px-Chlamydial-conjunctivitis.jpg"}]'),
(22, 'poisoning', 'Poisoning', 'The%20symbol%20of%20a%20toxic%20substance', '', 'null', '{}', '{}', '[{"list": ["organism", "chemically", "toxic substance", "venom", "animal"], "text": "Poisoning is a condition or a process in which an organism becomes chemically harmed (poisoned) by a toxic substance or venom of an animal."}, {"list": ["poison"], "text": "Acute poisoning is exposure to a poison on one occasion or during a short period of time."}, {"list": ["close relation to the degree of exposure"], "text": "Symptoms develop in close relation to the degree of exposure."}, {"text": "Absorption of a poison is necessary for systemic poisoning (that is, in the blood throughout the body)."}, {"list": ["lye", "corrosives"], "text": "In contrast, substances that destroy tissue but do not absorb, such as lye, are classified as corrosives rather than poisons."}, {"list": ["skull and crossbones"], "text": "Furthermore, many common household medications are not labeled with skull and crossbones, although they can cause severe illness or even death."}, {"list": ["toxicity"], "text": "In the medical sense, toxicity and poisoning can be caused by less dangerous substances than those legally classified as a poison."}, {"list": ["Toxicology"], "text": "Toxicology is the study and practice of the symptoms, mechanisms, diagnosis, and treatment of poisoning."}, {"text": "Chronic poisoning is long-term repeated or continuous exposure to a poison where symptoms do not occur immediately or after each exposure."}, {"text": "The patient gradually becomes ill, or becomes ill after a long latent period."}, {"list": ["bioaccumulate", "biomagnified", "mercury", "lead"], "text": "Chronic poisoning most commonly occurs following exposure to poisons that bioaccumulate, or are biomagnified, such as mercury, gadolinium, and lead."}, {"text": "Contact or absorption of poisons can cause rapid death or impairment."}, {"list": ["nervous system", "neurotoxins", "nerve gases", "warfare"], "text": "Agents that act on the nervous system can paralyze in seconds or less, and include both biologically derived neurotoxins and so-called nerve gases, which may be synthesized for warfare or industry."}, {"list": ["cyanide", "execution", "gas chambers", "inhibiting", "enzymes", "mitochondria", "ATP"], "text": "Inhaled or ingested cyanide, used as a method of execution in gas chambers, almost instantly starves the body of energy by inhibiting the enzymes in mitochondria that make ATP."}, {"list": ["potassium chloride", "heart", "cell potential", "muscle contraction"], "text": "Intravenous injection of an unnaturally high concentration of potassium chloride, such as in the execution of prisoners in parts of the United States, quickly stops the heart by eliminating the cell potential necessary for muscle contraction."}, {"list": ["pesticides", "secondary poisoning", "humans", "beneficial organisms"], "text": "Most biocides, including pesticides, are created to act as poisons to target organisms, although acute or less observable chronic poisoning can also occur in non-target organisms (secondary poisoning), including the humans who apply the biocides and other beneficial organisms."}, {"list": ["2,4-D"], "text": "For example, the herbicide 2,4-D imitates the action of a plant hormone, which makes its lethal toxicity specific to plants."}, {"text": "Indeed, 2,4-D is not a poison, but classified as \\"harmful\\" (EU)."}, {"list": ["toxication"], "text": "Many substances regarded as poisons are toxic only indirectly, by toxication."}, {"list": ["methanol", "formaldehyde", "formic acid", "liver"], "text": "An example is \\"wood alcohol\\" or methanol, which is not poisonous itself, but is chemically converted to toxic formaldehyde and formic acid in the liver."}, {"list": ["drug", "enzymes"], "text": "Many drug molecules are made toxic in the liver, and the genetic variability of certain liver enzymes makes the toxicity of many compounds differ between individuals."}, {"list": ["radiation poisoning"], "text": "Exposure to radioactive substances can produce radiation poisoning, an unrelated phenomenon."}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/58/GHS-pictogram-skull.svg", "file": "File:GHS-pictogram-skull.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/GHS-pictogram-skull.svg/300px-GHS-pictogram-skull.svg"}]');
