(24, 'shoulder_dislocation', 'Dislocated%20shoulder', 'Anterior%20dislocation%20of%20the%20left%20shoulder.', 'Emergency%20medicine%2C%20orthopedics', 'null', '{"desc": "Based on symptoms, X-rays", "list": ["X-rays"]}', '{"desc": "Fall onto an outstretched arm or the shoulder."}', '[{"list": ["humerus", "shoulder joint"], "text": "A dislocated shoulder is when the head of the humerus is out of the shoulder joint."}, {"text": "Symptoms include shoulder pain and instability."}, {"list": ["Bankart lesion", "Hill-Sachs lesion", "rotator cuff tear", "axillary nerve"], "text": "Complications may include a Bankart lesion, Hill-Sachs lesion, rotator cuff tear, or injury to the axillary nerve."}, {"text": "A shoulder dislocation often occurs as a result of a fall onto an outstretched arm or onto the shoulder."}, {"list": ["X-rays"], "text": "Diagnosis is typically based on symptoms and confirmed by X-rays."}, {"text": "They are classified as anterior, posterior, inferior, and superior with most being anterior."}, {"list": ["shoulder reduction"], "text": "Treatment is by shoulder reduction which may be accomplished by a number of techniques including traction-countertraction, external rotation, scapular manipulation, and the Stimson technique."}, {"text": "After reduction X-rays are recommended for verification."}, {"list": ["sling"], "text": "The arm may than be placed in a sling for a few weeks."}, {"text": "Surgery may be recommended in those with recurrent dislocations."}, {"text": "About 1.7% of people have a shoulder dislocation at one point in time."}, {"text": "In the United States this is about 24 per 100,000 people per year."}, {"list": ["emergency departments"], "text": "They make up about half of major joint dislocations seen in emergency departments."}, {"text": "Males are affected more often than females."}, {"text": "A diagnosis of shoulder dislocation is often suspected based on patient history and physical examination."}, {"text": "Radiographs are made to confirm the diagnosis."}, {"text": "Most dislocations are apparent on radiographs showing incongruence of the glenohumeral joint."}, {"text": "Posterior dislocations may be hard to detect on standard AP radiographs, but are more readily detected on other views."}, {"text": "After reduction, radiographs are usually repeated to confirm successful reduction and to detect bony damage."}, {"list": ["MRI scan"], "text": "After repeated shoulder dislocations, an MRI scan may be used to assess soft tissue damage."}, {"text": "In regards to recurrent dislocations, the apprehension test (anterior instability) and sulcus sign (inferior instability) are useful methods for determining predisposition to future dislocation."}, {"text": "There are three main types of dislocations: anterior, posterior, and inferior."}, {"list": ["shoulder", "anteriorly"], "text": "In over 95% of shoulder dislocations, the humerus is displaced anteriorly."}, {"list": ["coracoid process"], "text": "In most of those, the head of the humerus comes to rest under the coracoid process, referred to as sub-coracoid dislocation."}, {"list": ["glenoid", "clavicular", "intrathoracic", "retroperitoneal"], "text": "Sub-glenoid, subclavicular, and, very rarely, intrathoracic or retroperitoneal dislocations may also occur."}, {"text": "Anterior dislocations are usually caused by a direct blow to, or fall on, an outstretched arm."}, {"list": ["externally rotated", "abducted"], "text": "The patient typically holds his/her arm externally rotated and slightly abducted."}, {"list": ["Hill–Sachs lesion"], "text": "A Hill–Sachs lesion is an impaction of the head of the humerus left by the glenoid rim during dislocation."}, {"text": "Hill-Sachs deformities occur in 35%-40% of anterior dislocations."}, {"text": "They can be seen on a front-facing X-ray when the arm is in internal rotation."}, {"list": ["Bankart lesions"], "text": "Bankart lesions are disruptions of the glenoid labrum with or without an avulsion of bone fragment."}, {"list": ["axillary artery", "axillary nerve"], "text": "Damage to the axillary artery and axillary nerve (C5,C6) may result."}, {"text": "The axillary nerve is injured in 37% making it the most commonly injured structure with this type of injury."}, {"list": ["suprascapular nerve", "radial nerve"], "text": "Other common, associated, nerve injuries include injury to the suprascapular nerve (29%) and the radial nerve (22%)."}, {"list": ["deltoid muscle"], "text": "Axillary nerve damage results in a weakened or paralyzed deltoid muscle and as the deltoid atrophies unilaterally, the normal rounded contour of the shoulder is lost."}, {"list": ["abducting"], "text": "A patient with injury to the axillary nerve will have difficulty in abducting the arm from approximately 15° away from the body."}, {"list": ["supraspinatus muscle", "adducted"], "text": "The supraspinatus muscle initiates abduction from a fully adducted position."}, {"list": ["electric shock"], "text": "Posterior dislocations are uncommon, and are typically due to the muscle contraction from electric shock or seizure."}, {"text": "They may be caused by strength imbalance of the rotator cuff muscles."}, {"text": "Patients typically present holding their arm internally rotated and adducted, and exhibiting flattening of the anterior shoulder with a prominent coracoid process."}, {"list": ["elderly"], "text": "Posterior dislocations may go unrecognized, especially in an elderly patient and in the unconscious trauma patient."}, {"text": "An average interval of 1 year was noted between injury and diagnosis in a series of 40 patients."}, {"text": "Inferior dislocation is the least likely, occurring in less than 1%."}, {"text": "This condition is also called luxatio erecta because the arm appears to be permanently held upward or behind the head."}, {"text": "It is caused by a hyper abduction of the arm that forces the humeral head against the acromion."}, {"list": ["ligament"], "text": "Such injuries have a high complication rate as many vascular, neurological, tendon, and ligament injuries are likely to occur from this mechanism of injury."}, {"text": "Prompt medical treatment should be sought for suspected dislocation."}, {"list": ["splint"], "text": "Usually, the shoulder is kept in its current position by use of a splint or sling."}, {"list": ["arm", "torso"], "text": "A pillow between the arm and torso may provide support and increase comfort."}, {"text": "Strong analgesics are needed to allay the pain of a dislocation and the distress associated with it."}, {"list": ["Shoulder reduction"], "text": "Shoulder reduction may be accomplished with a number of techniques including traction-countertraction, external rotation, scapular manipulation, Stimson technique, Cunningham technique, or Milch technique."}, {"list": ["procedural sedation and analgesia", "lidocaine"], "text": "Pain can be managed during the procedures either by procedural sedation and analgesia or injected lidocaine into the shoulder joint."}, {"text": "Injecting lidocaine into the joint may be less expensive and faster."}, {"text": "If a shoulder cannot be relocated in the emergency room, relocation in the operating room maybe required."}, {"text": "This situation occurs in about 7% of cases."}, {"text": "There does not appear to be any difference in outcomes when the arm is immobilized in internal versus external rotation following an anterior shoulder dislocation."}, {"text": "A 2008 study of 300 people for almost six years found that conventional shoulder immobilisation in a sling offered no benefit."}, {"list": ["shoulder surgery"], "text": "In young adults engaged in highly demanding activities shoulder surgery may be considered."}, {"list": ["Arthroscopic surgery", "glenoidal labrum", "capsular ligaments", "biceps", "SLAP lesion"], "text": "Arthroscopic surgery techniques may be used to repair the glenoidal labrum, capsular ligaments, biceps long head anchor or SLAP lesion or to tighten the shoulder capsule."}, {"list": ["Bankart repair"], "text": "Arthroscopic stabilization surgery has evolved from the Bankart repair, a time-honored surgical treatment for recurrent anterior instability of the shoulder."}, {"list": ["Bankart repair"], "text": "However, the failure rate following Bankart repair has been shown to increase markedly in patients with significant bone loss from the glenoid (socket)."}, {"list": ["Latarjet operation"], "text": "In such cases, improved results have been reported with some form of bone augmentation of the glenoid such as the Latarjet operation."}, {"text": "Although posterior dislocation is much less common, instability following it is no less challenging and, again, some form of bone augmentation may be required to control instability."}, {"text": "There remains those situations characterized by multidirectional instability, which have failed to respond satisfactorily to rehabilitation, falling under the AMBRI classification previously noted."}, {"text": "This is usually due to an overstretched and redundant capsule which no longer offers stability or support."}, {"text": "Traditionally, this has responded well to a \'reefing\' procedure known as inferior capsular shift."}, {"text": "More recently, the procedure has been carried out as an arthroscopic procedure, rather than open surgery, again with comparable results."}, {"text": "Most recently, the procedure has been carried out using radio frequency technology to shrink the redundant shoulder capsule, although the long-term results of this development are currently unproven."}, {"text": "After an anterior shoulder dislocation, the risk of a future dislocation is about 20%.<!"}, {"text": "--> This risk is greater in males than females."}, {"list": ["Shoulder problems"], "text": "*Shoulder problems"}]', '{}', '{"list": ["Bankart lesion", " Hill-Sachs lesion", " rotator cuff tear", " axillary nerve injury"], "conditions": ["Bankart lesion", "Hill-Sachs lesion", "rotator cuff tear", "axillary nerve"]}', '{"desc": "Procedural sedation and analgesia, intraarticular lidocaine", "list": ["Procedural sedation and analgesia", "lidocaine"]}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ef/Dislocated_shoulder_X-ray_10.png", "file": "File:Dislocated shoulder X-ray 10.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Dislocated_shoulder_X-ray_10.png/300px-Dislocated_shoulder_X-ray_10.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/be/Lightbulb_sign_-_posterior_shoulder_dislocation_-_Roe_vor_und_nach_Reposition_001.jpg", "file": "File:Lightbulb sign - posterior shoulder dislocation - Roe vor und nach Reposition 001.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Lightbulb_sign_-_posterior_shoulder_dislocation_-_Roe_vor_und_nach_Reposition_001.jpg/300px-Lightbulb_sign_-_posterior_shoulder_dislocation_-_Roe_vor_und_nach_Reposition_001.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bd/Inferiourdislocation.JPG", "file": "Image:Inferiourdislocation.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Inferiourdislocation.JPG/300px-Inferiourdislocation.JPG"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/64/Cunningham2017.jpg", "file": "File:Cunningham2017.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/Cunningham2017.jpg/300px-Cunningham2017.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/47/Post_Dislocated_shoulder_MRI_01.png", "file": "File:Post Dislocated shoulder MRI 01.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Post_Dislocated_shoulder_MRI_01.png/300px-Post_Dislocated_shoulder_MRI_01.png"}]'),
(25, 'sleep_apnea', 'Sleep%20apnea', 'Obstructive%20sleep%20apnea', 'Otorhinolaryngology%2C%20sleep%20medicine', '["Pauses in breathing or periods of shallow breathing during sleep", "snoring", "tired during the day"]', '{"desc": "Overnight sleep study", "list": ["sleep study"]}', '{"desc": "Obstructive sleep apnea, central sleep apnea, mixed sleep apnea", "list": ["Obstructive sleep apnea", "central sleep apnea"]}', '[{"list": ["sleep disorder", "pauses in breathing", "shallow breathing", "sleep"], "text": "Sleep apnea, also spelled sleep apnoea, is a sleep disorder characterized by pauses in breathing or periods of shallow breathing during sleep."}, {"text": "Each pause can last for a few seconds to a few minutes and they happen many times a night."}, {"list": ["snoring"], "text": "In the most common form, this follows loud snoring."}, {"text": "There may be a choking or snorting sound as breathing resumes."}, {"text": "As it disrupts normal sleep, those affected may experience sleepiness or feel tired during the day."}, {"text": "In children it may cause problems in school, or hyperactivity."}, {"list": ["obstructive", "central"], "text": "There are three forms of sleep apnea: obstructive (OSA), central (CSA), and a combination of the two called mixed."}, {"text": "OSA is the most common form."}, {"list": ["overweight", "allergies", "tonsils"], "text": "Risk factors for OSA include being overweight, a family history of the condition, allergies, a small airway, and enlarged tonsils."}, {"text": "In OSA, breathing is interrupted by a blockage of airflow, while in CSA breathing stops due to a lack of effort to breathe."}, {"text": "People with sleep apnea may not be aware they have it. In many cases it is first observed by a family member."}, {"list": ["sleep study"], "text": "Sleep apnea is often diagnosed with an overnight sleep study."}, {"text": "For a diagnosis of sleep apnea, more than five episodes an hour must occur."}, {"text": "Treatment may include lifestyle changes, mouthpieces, breathing devices, and surgery."}, {"list": ["alcohol"], "text": "Lifestyle changes may include avoiding alcohol, losing weight, stopping smoking, and sleeping on one\'s side."}, {"list": ["CPAP machine"], "text": "Breathing devices include the use of a CPAP machine."}, {"list": ["heart attack", "stroke", "diabetes", "heart failure", "irregular heartbeat", "obesity", "motor vehicle collisions"], "text": "Without treatment sleep apnea may increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, diabetes, heart failure, irregular heartbeat, obesity, and motor vehicle collisions."}, {"text": "OSA affects 1 to 6% of adults and 2% of children."}, {"text": "It affects males about twice as often as females."}, {"text": "While people at any age can be affected it occurs most commonly among those 55 to 60 years old."}, {"text": "Central sleep apnea affects less than 1% of people."}, {"list": ["myth", "Ondine\'s curse"], "text": "A type of central sleep apnea was described in the German myth of Ondine\'s curse where when asleep the person would forget to breathe."}, {"list": ["excessive daytime sleepiness"], "text": "People with sleep apnea have problems with excessive daytime sleepiness (EDS), impaired alertness, and vision problems."}, {"text": "OSA may increase risk for driving accidents and work-related accidents."}, {"text": "If OSA is not treated, people are at increased risk of other health problems, such as diabetes."}, {"text": "Death could occur from untreated OSA due to lack of oxygen to the body."}, {"text": "Moreover, people are examined using \\"standard test batteries\\" to further identify parts of the brain that may be adversely affected by sleep apnea, including those that govern:"}, {"text": "There is evidence that the risk of diabetes among those with moderate or severe sleep apnea is higher."}, {"list": ["steatosis"], "text": "There is increasing evidence that sleep apnea may lead to liver function impairment, particularly fatty liver diseases (see steatosis)."}, {"text": "Finally, because there are many factors that could lead to some of the effects previously listed, some people are not aware that they have sleep apnea and are either misdiagnosed or ignore the symptoms altogether."}, {"text": "Sleep apnea can affect people regardless of sex, race, or age."}, {"text": "However, risk factors include:"}, {"text": "Central sleep apnea is more often associated with any of the following risk factors:"}, {"text": "When breathing is paused, carbon dioxide builds up in the bloodstream."}, {"list": ["Chemoreceptors"], "text": "Chemoreceptors in the blood stream note the high carbon dioxide levels."}, {"text": "The brain is signaled to wake the person sleeping and breathe in air."}, {"text": "Breathing normally will restore oxygen levels and the person will fall asleep again."}, {"list": ["polysomnography"], "text": "Sleep apnea may be diagnosed by the evaluation of symptoms, risk factors and observation, (e.g., excessive daytime sleepiness and fatigue) but the gold standard for diagnosis is a formal sleep study (polysomnography, or sometimes a reduced-channels home-based test)."}, {"list": ["AHI", "RDI"], "text": "A study can establish reliable indices of the disorder, derived from the number and type of event per hour of sleep (Apnea Hypopnea Index (AHI), or Respiratory Disturbance Index (RDI)), associated to a formal threshold, above which a patient is considered as suffering from sleep apnea, and the severity of their sleep apnea can then be quantified."}, {"text": "Mild OSA (Obstructive Sleep Apneas) ranges from 5 to 14.9 events per hour, moderate OSA falls in the range of 15–29.9 events per hour, and severe OSA would be a patient having over 30 events per hour."}, {"text": "Despite this medical consensus, the variety of apneic events (e.g., hypopnea vs apnea, central vs obstructive), the variability of patients\' physiologies, and the inherent shortcomings and variability of equipment and methods, this field is subject to debate."}, {"text": "Within this context, the definition of an event depends on several factors (e.g., patient\'s age) and account for this variability through a multi-criteria decision rule described in several, sometimes conflicting, guidelines."}, {"list": ["EEG", "blood oxygen"], "text": "One example of a commonly adopted definition of an apnea (for an adult) includes a minimum 10-second interval between breaths, with either a neurological arousal (a 3-second or greater shift in EEG frequency, measured at C3, C4, O1, or O2) or a blood oxygen desaturation of 3–4% or greater, or both arousal and desaturation."}, {"list": ["Oximetry", "polysomnography"], "text": "Oximetry, which may be performed over one or several nights in a person\'s home, is a simpler, but less reliable alternative to a polysomnography."}, {"text": "The test is only recommended when requested by a physician and should not be used to test those without symptoms."}, {"list": ["continuous positive airway pressure"], "text": "Home oximetry may be effective in guiding prescription for automatically self-adjusting continuous positive airway pressure."}, {"text": "There are three types of sleep apnea."}, {"text": "OSA accounts for 84%, CSA for 0.4%, and 15% of cases are mixed."}, {"text": "Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) is the most common category of sleep-disordered breathing."}, {"text": "The muscle tone of the body ordinarily relaxes during sleep, and at the level of the throat the human airway is composed of collapsible walls of soft tissue which can obstruct breathing."}, {"list": ["upper respiratory infection", "hypoxemia", "sleep deprivation"], "text": "Mild occasional sleep apnea, such as many people experience during an upper respiratory infection, may not be significant, but chronic severe obstructive sleep apnea requires treatment to prevent low blood oxygen (hypoxemia), sleep deprivation, and other complications."}, {"text": "Individuals with low muscle tone and soft tissue around the airway (e.g., because of obesity) and structural features that give rise to a narrowed airway are at high risk for obstructive sleep apnea."}, {"text": "The elderly are more likely to have OSA than young people."}, {"text": "Men are more likely to suffer sleep apnea than women and children are, though it is not uncommon in the last two population groups."}, {"text": "The risk of OSA rises with increasing body weight, active smoking and age."}, {"text": "In addition, patients with diabetes or \\"borderline\\" diabetes have up to three times the risk of having OSA."}, {"list": ["snoring"], "text": "Common symptoms include loud snoring, restless sleep, and sleepiness during the daytime."}, {"list": ["oximetry", "polysomnography"], "text": "Diagnostic tests include home oximetry or polysomnography in a sleep clinic."}, {"text": "Some treatments involve lifestyle changes, such as avoiding alcohol or muscle relaxants, losing weight, and quitting smoking."}, {"list": ["recliner"], "text": "Many people benefit from sleeping at a 30-degree elevation of the upper body or higher, as if in a recliner."}, {"text": "Doing so helps prevent the gravitational collapse of the airway."}, {"list": ["Lateral positions", "supine positions"], "text": "Lateral positions (sleeping on a side), as opposed to supine positions (sleeping on the back), are also recommended as a treatment for sleep apnea,  largely because the gravitational component is smaller in  the lateral position."}, {"list": ["Mandibular advancement splint"], "text": "Some people benefit from various kinds of oral appliances such as the Mandibular advancement splint to keep the airway open during sleep."}, {"list": ["Continuous positive airway pressure"], "text": "Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) is the most effective treatment for severe obstructive sleep apnea but oral appliances are considered a first line approach equal to CPAP for mild to moderate sleep apnea according to the AASM parameters of care."}, {"text": "There are also surgical procedures to remove and tighten tissue and widen the airway."}, {"text": "Snoring is a common finding in people with this syndrome."}, {"text": "Snoring is the turbulent sound of air moving through the back of the mouth, nose, and throat."}, {"text": "Although not everyone who snores is experiencing difficulty breathing, snoring in combination with other risk factors has been found to be highly predictive of OSA."}, {"text": "The loudness of the snoring is not indicative of the severity of obstruction, however."}, {"text": "If the upper airways are tremendously obstructed, there may not be enough air movement to make much sound."}, {"text": "Even the loudest snoring does not mean that an individual has sleep apnea syndrome."}, {"text": "The sign that is most suggestive of sleep apneas occurs when snoring stops."}, {"list": ["hypersomnolence", "micrognathia"], "text": "Other indicators include (but are not limited to): hypersomnolence, obesity BMI >30, large neck circumference ( in women, in men), enlarged tonsils and large tongue volume, micrognathia, morning headaches, irritability/mood-swings/depression, learning and/or memory difficulties, and sexual dysfunction."}, {"list": ["hypopnea"], "text": "The term \\"sleep-disordered breathing\\" is commonly used in the U.S. to describe the full range of breathing problems during sleep in which not enough air reaches the lungs (hypopnea and apnea)."}, {"list": ["cardiovascular disease", "stroke", "high blood pressure", "arrhythmias", "diabetes", "sleep deprived driving"], "text": "Sleep-disordered breathing is associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, stroke, high blood pressure, arrhythmias, diabetes, and sleep deprived driving accidents."}, {"list": ["essential hypertension"], "text": "When high blood pressure is caused by OSA, it is distinctive in that, unlike most cases of high blood pressure (so-called essential hypertension), the readings do not drop significantly when the individual is sleeping."}, {"list": ["Stroke"], "text": "Stroke is associated with obstructive sleep apnea."}, {"text": "It has been revealed that people with OSA show tissue loss in brain regions that help store memory, thus linking OSA with memory loss."}, {"list": ["magnetic resonance imaging", "mammillary bodies"], "text": "Using magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), the scientists discovered that people with sleep apnea have mammillary bodies that are about 20 percent smaller, particularly on the left side."}, {"text": "One of the key investigators hypothesized that repeated drops in oxygen lead to the brain injury."}, {"list": ["Cheyne–Stokes respiration"], "text": "In pure central sleep apnea or Cheyne–Stokes respiration, the brain\'s respiratory control centers are imbalanced during sleep."}, {"text": "Blood levels of carbon dioxide, and the neurological feedback mechanism that monitors them, do not react quickly enough to maintain an even respiratory rate, with the entire system cycling between apnea and hyperpnea, even during wakefulness."}, {"text": "The sleeper stops breathing and then starts again."}, {"text": "There is no effort made to breathe during the pause in breathing: there are no chest movements and no struggling."}, {"text": "After the episode of apnea, breathing may be faster (hyperpnea) for a period of time, a compensatory mechanism to blow off retained waste gases and absorb more oxygen."}, {"text": "While sleeping, a normal individual is \\"at rest\\" as far as cardiovascular workload is concerned."}, {"text": "Breathing is regular in a healthy person during sleep, and oxygen levels and carbon dioxide levels in the bloodstream stay fairly constant."}, {"text": "Any sudden drop in oxygen or excess of carbon dioxide (even if tiny) strongly stimulates the brain\'s respiratory centers to breathe."}, {"text": "In central sleep apnea, the basic neurological controls for breathing rate malfunction and fail to give the signal to inhale, causing the individual to miss one or more cycles of breathing."}, {"list": ["hypoxaemia", "hypercapnia"], "text": "If the pause in breathing is long enough, the percentage of oxygen in the circulation will drop to a lower than normal level (hypoxaemia) and the concentration of carbon dioxide will build to a higher than normal level (hypercapnia)."}, {"list": ["hypoxia", "hypercapnia"], "text": "In turn, these conditions of hypoxia and hypercapnia will trigger additional effects on the body."}, {"text": "Brain cells need constant oxygen to live, and if the level of blood oxygen goes low enough for long enough, the consequences of brain damage and even death will occur."}, {"text": "However, central sleep apnea is more often a chronic condition that causes much milder effects than sudden death."}, {"text": "The exact effects of the condition will depend on how severe the apnea is and on the individual characteristics of the person having the apnea."}, {"text": "Several examples are discussed below, and more about the nature of the condition is presented in the section on Clinical Details."}, {"text": "In any person, hypoxia and hypercapnia have certain common effects on the body."}, {"text": "The heart rate will increase, unless there are such severe co-existing problems with the heart muscle itself or the autonomic nervous system that makes this compensatory increase impossible."}, {"list": ["cyanosis"], "text": "The more translucent areas of the body will show a bluish or dusky cast from cyanosis, which is the change in hue that occurs owing to lack of oxygen in the blood (\\"turning blue\\")."}, {"text": "Overdoses of drugs that are respiratory depressants (such as heroin, and other opiates) kill by damping the activity of the brain\'s respiratory control centers."}, {"text": "In central sleep apnea, the effects of sleep alone can remove the brain\'s mandate for the body to breathe."}, {"text": "Some people with sleep apnea have a combination of both types; its prevalence ranges from 0.56% to 18%."}, {"text": "The condition is generally detected when obstructive sleep apnea is treated with CPAP and central sleep apnea emerges."}, {"text": "The exact mechanism of the loss of central respiratory drive during sleep in OSA is unknown but is most likely related to incorrect settings of the CPAP treatment and other medical conditions the person has."}, {"text": "The treatment of obstructive sleep apnea is different than that of central sleep apnea."}, {"text": "Treatment often starts with behavioral therapy."}, {"text": "Many people are told to avoid alcohol, sleeping pills, and other sedatives, which can relax throat muscles, contributing to the collapse of the airway at night."}, {"text": "For moderate to severe sleep apnea, the most common treatment is the use of a continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) or automatic positive airway pressure (APAP) device."}, {"text": "These splint the person\'s airway open during sleep by means of pressurized air."}, {"text": "The person typically wears a plastic facial mask, which is connected by a flexible tube to a small bedside CPAP machine."}, {"text": "With proper use, CPAP improves outcomes."}, {"text": "Whether or not it decreases the risk of death or heart disease is controversial with some reviews finding benefit and others not."}, {"text": "This variation across studies might be driven by low rates of compliance—analyses of those who use CPAP for at least four hours a night suggests a decrease in cardiovascular events."}, {"text": "Evidence suggests that CPAP may improve sensitivity to insulin, blood pressure, and sleepiness."}, {"text": "Long term compliance, however, is an issue with more than half of people not appropriately using the device."}, {"text": "Although CPAP therapy is effective in reducing apneas and less expensive than other treatments, some people find it uncomfortable."}, {"text": "Some complain of feeling trapped, having chest discomfort, and skin or nose irritation."}, {"text": "Other side effects may include dry mouth, dry nose, nosebleeds, sore lips and gums."}, {"text": "Excess body weight is thought to be an important cause of sleep apnea."}, {"text": "In weight loss studies of obese and overweight individuals, those who lose weight show reduced apnea frequencies and improved Apnoea–Hypopnoea Index (AHI) compared to controls."}, {"list": ["sleep surgery"], "text": "Several surgical procedures (sleep surgery) are used to treat sleep apnea, although they are normally a third line of treatment for those who reject or are not helped by CPAP treatment or dental appliances."}, {"text": "Surgical treatment for obstructive sleep apnea needs to be individualized to address all anatomical areas of obstruction."}, {"list": ["oropharynx"], "text": "Often, correction of the nasal passages needs to be performed in addition to correction of the oropharynx passage."}, {"list": ["Septoplasty", "turbinate surgery"], "text": "Septoplasty and turbinate surgery may improve the nasal airway."}, {"list": ["uvulopalatopharyngoplasty"], "text": "Tonsillectomy and uvulopalatopharyngoplasty (UPPP or UP3) are available to address pharyngeal obstruction."}, {"text": "The \\"Pillar\\" device is a treatment for snoring and obstructive sleep apnea; it is thin, narrow strips of polyester."}, {"list": ["soft palate"], "text": "Three strips are inserted into the roof of the mouth (the soft palate) using a modified syringe and local anesthetic, in order to stiffen the soft palate."}, {"text": "This procedure addresses one of the most common causes of snoring and sleep apnea — vibration or collapse of the soft palate."}, {"text": "It was approved by the FDA for snoring in 2002 and for obstructive sleep apnea in 2004."}, {"text": "A 2013 meta-analysis found that \\"the Pillar implant has a moderate effect on snoring and mild-to-moderate obstructive sleep apnea\\" and that more studies with high level of evidence were needed to arrive at a definite conclusion; it also found that the polyester strips work their way out of the soft palate in about 10% of the people in whom they are implanted."}, {"list": ["hyoid suspension"], "text": "Base-of-tongue advancement by means of advancing the genial tubercle of the mandible, tongue suspension, or hyoid suspension (aka hyoid myotomy and suspension or hyoid advancement) may help with the lower pharynx."}, {"text": "Other surgery options may attempt to shrink or stiffen excess tissue in the mouth or throat; procedures done at either a doctor\'s office or a hospital."}, {"text": "Small shots or other treatments, sometimes in a series, are used for shrinkage, while the insertion of a small piece of stiff plastic is used in the case of surgery whose goal is to stiffen tissues."}, {"list": ["Maxillomandibular advancement"], "text": "Maxillomandibular advancement (MMA) is considered the most effective surgery for people with sleep apnea, because it increases the posterior airway space (PAS)."}, {"text": "However, health professionals are often unsure as to who should be referred for surgery and when to do so: some factors in referral may include failed use of CPAP or device use; anatomy which favors rather than impedes surgery; or significant craniofacial abnormalities which hinder device use."}, {"text": "Several inpatient and outpatient procedures use sedation."}, {"text": "Many drugs and agents used during surgery to relieve pain and to depress consciousness remain in the body at low amounts for hours or even days afterwards."}, {"text": "In an individual with either central, obstructive or mixed sleep apnea, these low doses may be enough to cause life-threatening irregularities in breathing or collapses in a patient\'s airways."}, {"text": "Use of analgesics and sedatives in these patients postoperatively should therefore be minimized or avoided."}, {"text": "Surgery on the mouth and throat, as well as dental surgery and procedures, can result in postoperative swelling of the lining of the mouth and other areas that affect the airway."}, {"text": "Even when the surgical procedure is designed to improve the airway, such as tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy or tongue reduction, swelling may negate some of the effects in the immediate postoperative period."}, {"text": "Once the swelling resolves and the palate becomes tightened by postoperative scarring, however, the full benefit of the surgery may be noticed."}, {"list": ["anesthetist"], "text": "A person with sleep apnea undergoing any medical treatment must make sure his or her doctor and anesthetist are informed about the sleep apnea."}, {"text": "Alternative and emergency procedures may be necessary to maintain the airway of sleep apnea patients."}, {"list": ["Diaphragm pacing"], "text": "Diaphragm pacing, which involves the rhythmic application of electrical impulses to the diaphragm, has been used to treat central sleep apnea."}, {"text": "In April 2014 the U.S. Food and Drug Administration granted pre-market approval for use of an upper airway stimulation system in people who cannot use a continuous positive airway pressure device."}, {"text": "The Inspire Upper Airway Stimulation system senses respiration and applies mild electrical stimulation during inspiration, which pushes the tongue slightly forward to open the airway."}, {"list": ["acetazolamide", "zolpidem", "triazolam"], "text": "There is limited evidence for medication but acetazolamide \\"may be considered\\" for the treatment of central sleep apnea; it also found that zolpidem and triazolam may be considered for the treatment of central sleep apnea, but \\"only if the patient does not have underlying risk factors for respiratory depression\\"."}, {"text": "Low doses of oxygen are also used as a treatment for hypoxia but are discouraged due to side effects."}, {"list": ["mandibular advancement splint"], "text": "An oral appliance, often referred to as a mandibular advancement splint, is a custom-made mouthpiece that shifts the lower jaw forward and opens the bite slightly, opening up the airway."}, {"text": "These devices can be fabricated by a general dentist."}, {"text": "Oral appliance therapy (OAT) is usually successful in patients with mild to moderate obstructive sleep apnea."}, {"text": "While CPAP is more effective for sleep apnea than oral appliances, oral appliances do improve sleepiness and quality of life and are often better tolerated than CPAP."}, {"list": ["Nasal EPAP"], "text": "Nasal EPAP is a bandage-like device placed over the nostrils that utilizes a person\'s own breathing to create positive airway pressure to prevent obstructed breathing."}, {"list": ["Oral pressure therapy"], "text": "Oral pressure therapy utilizes a device that creates a vacuum in the mouth, pulling the soft palate tissue forward."}, {"text": "It has been found useful in about 25 to 37% of people."}, {"text": "The Wisconsin Sleep Cohort Study estimated in 1993 that roughly one in every 15 Americans was affected by at least moderate sleep apnea."}, {"text": "It also estimated that in middle-age as many as nine percent of women and 24 percent of men were affected, undiagnosed and untreated."}, {"text": "The costs of untreated sleep apnea reach further than just health issues."}, {"text": "It is estimated that in the U.S. the average untreated sleep apnea patient\'s annual health care costs $1,336 more than an individual without sleep apnea."}, {"text": "This may cause $3.4 billion/year in additional medical costs."}, {"text": "Whether medical cost savings occur with treatment of sleep apnea remains to be determined."}, {"text": "The clinical picture of this condition has long been recognized as a character trait, without an understanding of the disease process."}, {"list": ["Pickwickian syndrome", "William Osler", "Charles Dickens"], "text": "The term \\"Pickwickian syndrome\\" that is sometimes used for the syndrome was coined by the famous early 20th century physician, William Osler, who must have been a reader of Charles Dickens."}, {"list": ["The Pickwick Papers\'\'"], "text": "The description of Joe, \\"the fat boy\\" in Dickens\'s novel The Pickwick Papers, is an accurate clinical picture of an adult with obstructive sleep apnea syndrome."}, {"list": ["hypoxemia", "hypercapnia", "congestive heart failure"], "text": "The early reports of obstructive sleep apnea in the medical literature described individuals who were very severely affected, often presenting with severe hypoxemia, hypercapnia and congestive heart failure."}, {"list": ["continuous positive airway pressure", "Sydney", "Australia"], "text": "The management of obstructive sleep apnea was improved with the introduction of continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP), first described in 1981 by Colin Sullivan and associates in Sydney, Australia."}, {"text": "The first models were bulky and noisy, but the design was rapidly improved and by the late 1980s CPAP was widely adopted."}, {"list": ["sleep disorders"], "text": "The availability of an effective treatment stimulated an aggressive search for affected individuals and led to the establishment of hundreds of specialized clinics dedicated to the diagnosis and treatment of sleep disorders."}, {"text": "Though many types of sleep problems are recognized, the vast majority of patients attending these centers have sleep-disordered breathing."}, {"text": "Sleep apnea awareness day is April 18 in recognition of Colin Sullivan."}]', '{}', '{"list": ["Heart attack", " stroke", " diabetes", " heart failure", " irregular heartbeat", " obesity", " motor vehicle collisions"], "conditions": ["Heart attack", "stroke", "diabetes", "heart failure", "irregular heartbeat", "obesity", "motor vehicle collisions"]}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/69/Obstruction_ventilation_apn%C3%A9e_sommeil.svg", "file": "File:Obstruction ventilation apnée sommeil.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Obstruction_ventilation_apn%C3%A9e_sommeil.svg/300px-Obstruction_ventilation_apn%C3%A9e_sommeil.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/05/Sleep_apnea.webm", "file": "File:Sleep apnea.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Sleep_apnea.webm/300px-Sleep_apnea.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a1/ObstructiveApnea.png", "file": "File:ObstructiveApnea.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/ObstructiveApnea.png/300px-ObstructiveApnea.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/24/CentralApnea.png", "file": "File:CentralApnea.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/CentralApnea.png/300px-CentralApnea.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ed/Cpapanwender.jpg", "file": "File:Cpapanwender.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Cpapanwender.jpg/300px-Cpapanwender.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0c/CPAP-machine-resmedS9.jpg", "file": "File:CPAP-machine-resmedS9.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/CPAP-machine-resmedS9.jpg/300px-CPAP-machine-resmedS9.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/66/Caut%C3%A9risation_des_parties_molles_-_apn%C3%A9e_du_sommeil.svg", "file": "File:Cautérisation des parties molles - apnée du sommeil.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/66/Caut%C3%A9risation_des_parties_molles_-_apn%C3%A9e_du_sommeil.svg/300px-Caut%C3%A9risation_des_parties_molles_-_apn%C3%A9e_du_sommeil.svg"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(26, 'stomach_ulcer', 'Peptic%20ulcer%20disease', 'Deep%20gastric%20ulcer', 'Gastroenterology%2C%20general%20surgery', '["Upper abdominal pain", "belching", "vomiting", "weight loss", "poor appetite"]', '{"desc": "Based on symptoms, confirmed by endoscopy or barium swallow", "list": ["endoscopy", "barium swallow"]}', '{"desc": "Helicobacter pylori, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, tobacco smoking, Crohn disease", "list": ["Helicobacter pylori\'\'", "non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs", "tobacco smoking", "Crohn disease"]}', '[{"list": ["stomach", "small intestine", "esophagus"], "text": "Peptic ulcer disease (PUD) is a break in the lining of the stomach, first part of the small intestine or occasionally the lower esophagus."}, {"text": "An ulcer in the stomach is known as a gastric ulcer while that in the first part of the intestines is known as a duodenal ulcer."}, {"list": ["upper abdominal pain"], "text": "The most common symptoms of a duodenal ulcer are waking at night with upper abdominal pain or upper abdominal pain that improves with eating."}, {"text": "With a gastric ulcer the pain may worsen with eating."}, {"list": ["burning"], "text": "The pain is often described as a burning or dull ache."}, {"list": ["belching", "poor appetite"], "text": "Other symptoms include belching, vomiting, weight loss, or poor appetite."}, {"text": "About a third of older people have no symptoms."}, {"list": ["bleeding", "perforation", "blockage of the stomach"], "text": "Complications may include bleeding, perforation and blockage of the stomach."}, {"text": "Bleeding occurs in as many as 15% of people."}, {"list": ["bacteria", "Helicobacter pylori\'\'", "non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs"], "text": "Common causes include the bacteria Helicobacter pylori and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)."}, {"list": ["tobacco smoking", "Behcet disease", "Zollinger-Ellison syndrome", "Crohn disease", "liver cirrhosis"], "text": "Other less common causes include tobacco smoking, stress due to serious illness, Behcet disease, Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, Crohn disease and liver cirrhosis, among others."}, {"text": "Older people are more sensitive to the ulcer-causing effects of NSAIDs."}, {"list": ["endoscopy", "barium swallow"], "text": "The diagnosis is typically suspected due to the presenting symptoms with confirmation by either endoscopy or barium swallow."}, {"list": ["antibodies", "urea breath test", "biopsy"], "text": "H. pylori can be diagnosed by testing the blood for antibodies, a urea breath test, testing the stool for signs of the bacteria, or a biopsy of the stomach."}, {"list": ["stomach cancer", "coronary heart disease", "inflammation of the stomach lining", "gallbladder inflammation"], "text": "Other conditions that produce similar symptoms include stomach cancer, coronary heart disease, and inflammation of the stomach lining or gallbladder inflammation."}, {"list": ["Diet"], "text": "Diet does not play an important role in either causing or preventing ulcers."}, {"list": ["alcohol"], "text": "Treatment includes stopping smoking, stopping NSAIDs, stopping alcohol and giving medications to decrease stomach acid."}, {"list": ["proton pump inhibitor", "H2 blocker"], "text": "The medication used to decrease acid is usually either a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) or an H2 blocker with four weeks of treatment initially recommended."}, {"text": "Ulcers due to \'\'H."}, {"list": ["amoxicillin", "clarithromycin"], "text": "pylori\'\' are treated with a combination of medications such as amoxicillin, clarithromycin and a PPI."}, {"list": ["Antibiotic resistance"], "text": "Antibiotic resistance is increasing and thus treatment may not always be effective."}, {"list": ["endoscopy"], "text": "Bleeding ulcers may be treated by endoscopy, with open surgery typically only used in cases in which it is not successful."}, {"text": "Peptic ulcers are present in around 4% of the population."}, {"text": "New ulcers were found in around 87.4 million people worldwide during 2015."}, {"text": "About 10% of people develop a peptic ulcer at some point in their life."}, {"text": "They resulted in 267,500 deaths in 2015 down from 327,000 deaths in 1990."}, {"list": ["Henrietta of England"], "text": "The first description of a perforated peptic ulcer was in 1670 in Princess Henrietta of England."}, {"list": ["Barry Marshall", "Robin Warren"], "text": "H. pylori was first identified as causing peptic ulcers by Barry Marshall and Robin Warren in the late 20th century, a discovery for which they received the Nobel Prize in 2005."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms of a peptic ulcer can include one or more of the following:"}, {"list": ["esophagogastroduodenoscopy"], "text": "In people over the age of 45 with more than two weeks of the above symptoms, the odds for peptic ulceration are high enough to warrant rapid investigation by esophagogastroduodenoscopy."}, {"list": ["epigastric", "gastric acid"], "text": "The timing of the symptoms in relation to the meal may differentiate between gastric and duodenal ulcers: A gastric ulcer would give epigastric pain during the meal, as gastric acid production is increased as food enters the stomach."}, {"list": ["pyloric sphincter"], "text": "Symptoms of duodenal ulcers would initially be relieved by a meal, as the pyloric sphincter closes to concentrate the stomach contents, therefore acid is not reaching the duodenum."}, {"list": ["duodenum"], "text": "Duodenal ulcer pain would manifest mostly 2–3 hours after the meal, when the stomach begins to release digested food and acid into the duodenum."}, {"text": "Also, the symptoms of peptic ulcers may vary with the location of the ulcer and the person\'s age."}, {"text": "Furthermore, typical ulcers tend to heal and recur and as a result the pain may occur for few days and weeks and then wane or disappear."}, {"list": ["elderly"], "text": "Usually, children and the elderly do not develop any symptoms unless complications have arisen."}, {"text": "Burning or gnawing feeling in the stomach area lasting between 30 minutes and 3 hours commonly accompanies ulcers."}, {"list": ["hunger", "indigestion", "heartburn"], "text": "This pain can be misinterpreted as hunger, indigestion or heartburn."}, {"list": ["stomach acid"], "text": "Pain is usually caused by the ulcer but it may be aggravated by the stomach acid when it comes into contact with the ulcerated area."}, {"list": ["sternum"], "text": "The pain caused by peptic ulcers can be felt anywhere from the navel up to the sternum, it may last from few minutes to several hours and it may be worse when the stomach is empty."}, {"text": "Also, sometimes the pain may flare at night and it can commonly be temporarily relieved by eating foods that buffer stomach acid or by taking anti-acid medication."}, {"text": "However, peptic ulcer disease symptoms may be different for every sufferer."}, {"list": ["inflammation", "Helicobacter pylori\'\'", "colonizes", "antral", "mucosa"], "text": "A major causative factor (60% of gastric and up to 50–75% of duodenal ulcers) is chronic inflammation due to Helicobacter pylori that colonizes the antral mucosa."}, {"text": "The immune system is unable to clear the infection, despite the appearance of antibodies."}, {"list": ["gastritis"], "text": "Thus, the bacterium can cause a chronic active gastritis (type B gastritis)."}, {"list": ["Gastrin", "gastric acid"], "text": "Gastrin stimulates the production of gastric acid by parietal cells."}, {"text": "In \'\'H."}, {"list": ["mucosa"], "text": "pylori\'\' colonization responses to increased gastrin, the increase in acid can contribute to the erosion of the mucosa and therefore ulcer formation."}, {"list": ["NSAIDs", "ibuprofen", "aspirin"], "text": "Another major cause is the use of NSAIDs, such as ibuprofen and aspirin."}, {"list": ["gastric acid", "prostaglandins"], "text": "The gastric mucosa protects itself from gastric acid with a layer of mucus, the secretion of which is stimulated by certain prostaglandins."}, {"list": ["cyclooxygenase"], "text": "NSAIDs block the function of cyclooxygenase 1 (COX-1), which is essential for the production of these prostaglandins."}, {"list": ["celecoxib", "rofecoxib"], "text": "COX-2 selective anti-inflammatories (such as celecoxib or the since withdrawn rofecoxib) preferentially inhibit COX-2, which is less essential in the gastric mucosa, and roughly halve the risk of NSAID-related gastric ulceration."}, {"list": ["stress ulcers"], "text": "Stress due to serious health problems such as those requiring treatment in an intensive care unit is well described as a cause of peptic ulcers, which are termed stress ulcers."}, {"text": "While chronic life stress was once believed to be the main cause of ulcers, this is no longer the case."}, {"text": "It is, however, still occasionally believed to play a role."}, {"text": "This may be by increasing the risk in those with other causes such as \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' or NSAID use."}, {"list": ["Dietary", "spice"], "text": "Dietary factors such as spice consumption, were hypothesized to cause ulcers until late in the 20th century, but have been shown to be of relatively minor importance."}, {"text": "Caffeine and coffee, also commonly thought to cause or exacerbate ulcers, appear to have little effect."}, {"text": "Similarly, while studies have found that alcohol consumption increases risk when associated with \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' infection, it does not seem to independently increase risk."}, {"text": "Even when coupled with \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' infection, the increase is modest in comparison to the primary risk factor."}, {"text": "As of 2017 it is unclear if smoking increases the risk of ulcers."}, {"list": ["Gastrinomas", "Zollinger–Ellison syndrome"], "text": "Gastrinomas (Zollinger–Ellison syndrome), rare gastrin-secreting tumors, also cause multiple and difficult-to-heal ulcers."}, {"text": "The diagnosis is mainly established based on the characteristic symptoms."}, {"text": "Stomach pain is usually the first signal of a peptic ulcer."}, {"text": "In some cases, doctors may treat ulcers without diagnosing them with specific tests and observe whether the symptoms resolve, thus indicating that their primary diagnosis was accurate."}, {"list": ["muscularis mucosae"], "text": "More specifically, peptic ulcers erode the muscularis mucosae, at minimum reaching to the level of the submucosa (contrast with erosions, which do not involve the muscularis mucosae)."}, {"list": ["x-rays"], "text": "Confirmation of the diagnosis is made with the help of tests such as endoscopies or barium contrast x-rays."}, {"list": ["weight loss", "stomach cancer"], "text": "The tests are typically ordered if the symptoms do not resolve after a few weeks of treatment, or when they first appear in a person who is over age 45 or who has other symptoms such as weight loss, because stomach cancer can cause similar symptoms."}, {"list": ["acid"], "text": "Also, when severe ulcers resist treatment, particularly if a person has several ulcers or the ulcers are in unusual places, a doctor may suspect an underlying condition that causes the stomach to overproduce acid."}, {"list": ["esophagogastroduodenoscopy", "endoscopy", "gastroscopy"], "text": "An esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD), a form of endoscopy, also known as a gastroscopy, is carried out on people in whom a peptic ulcer is suspected."}, {"text": "By direct visual identification, the location and severity of an ulcer can be described."}, {"text": "Moreover, if no ulcer is present, EGD can often provide an alternative diagnosis."}, {"list": ["blood tests"], "text": "One of the reasons that blood tests are not reliable for accurate peptic ulcer diagnosis on their own is their inability to differentiate between past exposure to the bacteria and current infection."}, {"list": ["antibiotics", "proton-pump inhibitors"], "text": "Additionally, a false negative result is possible with a blood test if the person has recently been taking certain drugs, such as antibiotics or proton-pump inhibitors."}, {"list": ["Helicobacter pylori\'\'"], "text": "The diagnosis of Helicobacter pylori can be made by:"}, {"list": ["malignancy", "gastric cancer"], "text": "The possibility of other causes of ulcers, notably malignancy (gastric cancer) needs to be kept in mind."}, {"list": ["stomach"], "text": "This is especially true in ulcers of the greater (large) curvature of the stomach; most are also a consequence of chronic \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' infection."}, {"text": "If a peptic ulcer perforates, air will leak from the inside of the gastrointestinal tract (which always contains some air) to the peritoneal cavity (which normally never contains air)."}, {"text": "This leads to \\"free gas\\" within the peritoneal cavity."}, {"text": "If the person stands erect, as when having a chest X-ray, the gas will float to a position underneath the diaphragm."}, {"text": "Therefore, gas in the peritoneal cavity, shown on an erect chest X-ray or supine lateral abdominal X-ray, is an omen of perforated peptic ulcer disease."}, {"text": "Gastric ulcers are most often localized on the lesser curvature of the stomach."}, {"text": "The ulcer is a round to oval parietal defect (\\"hole\\"), 2 to 4 cm diameter, with a smooth base and perpendicular borders."}, {"text": "These borders are not elevated or irregular in the acute form of peptic ulcer, regular but with elevated borders and inflammatory surrounding in the chronic form."}, {"text": "In the ulcerative form of gastric cancer the borders are irregular."}, {"text": "Surrounding mucosa may present radial folds, as a consequence of the parietal scarring."}, {"list": ["muscularis mucosae"], "text": "A gastric peptic ulcer is a mucosal perforation which penetrates the muscularis mucosae and lamina propria, usually produced by acid-pepsin aggression."}, {"text": "Ulcer margins are perpendicular and present chronic gastritis."}, {"text": "During the active phase, the base of the ulcer shows 4 zones: fibrinoid necrosis, inflammatory exudate, granulation tissue and fibrous tissue."}, {"text": "The fibrous base of the ulcer may contain vessels with thickened wall or with thrombosis."}, {"text": "Conditions that may appear similar include:"}, {"list": ["antacids", "H2 antagonists", "endoscopy"], "text": "Younger people with ulcer-like symptoms are often treated with antacids or H2 antagonists before endoscopy is undertaken."}, {"list": ["nonsteroidal anti-inflammatories", "prostaglandin", "analogue", "misoprostol"], "text": "People who are taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatories (NSAIDs) may also be prescribed a prostaglandin analogue (misoprostol) in order to help prevent peptic ulcers."}, {"list": ["H2 antagonists", "proton-pump inhibitors"], "text": "H2 antagonists or proton-pump inhibitors decrease the amount of acid in the stomach, helping with healing of ulcers."}, {"text": "When \'\'H."}, {"list": ["clarithromycin", "amoxicillin", "tetracycline", "metronidazole", "proton-pump inhibitor"], "text": "pylori\'\' infection is present, the most effective treatments are combinations of 2 antibiotics (e.g. clarithromycin, amoxicillin, tetracycline, metronidazole) and a proton-pump inhibitor (PPI), sometimes together with a bismuth compound."}, {"text": "In complicated, treatment-resistant cases, 3 antibiotics (e.g. amoxicillin + clarithromycin + metronidazole) may be used together with a PPI and sometimes with bismuth compound."}, {"list": ["pantoprazole"], "text": "An effective first-line therapy for uncomplicated cases would be amoxicillin + metronidazole + pantoprazole (a PPI)."}, {"list": ["Perforated peptic ulcer"], "text": "Perforated peptic ulcer is a surgical emergency and requires surgical repair of the perforation."}, {"list": ["clipping"], "text": "Most bleeding ulcers require endoscopy urgently to stop bleeding with cautery, injection, or clipping."}, {"list": ["Disability-adjusted life year"], "text": "[[File:peptic ulcer disease world map - DALY - WHO2004.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Disability-adjusted life year for peptic ulcer disease per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004. The lifetime risk for developing a peptic ulcer is approximately 10%. They resulted in 301,000 deaths in 2013 down from 327,000 deaths in 1990. In Western countries the percentage of people with H. pylori infections roughly matches age (i.e., 20% at age 20, 30% at age 30, 80% at age 80 etc.). Prevalence is higher in third world countries where it is estimated at about 70% of the population, whereas developed countries show a maximum of 40% ratio. Overall, H. pylori infections show a worldwide decrease, more so in developed countries. Transmission is by food, contaminated groundwater, and through human saliva (such as from kissing or sharing food utensils). A minority of cases of H. pylori infection will eventually lead to an ulcer and a larger proportion of people will get non-specific discomfort, abdominal pain or gastritis.Peptic ulcer disease had a tremendous effect on morbidity and mortality until the last decades of the 20th century when epidemiological trends started to point to an impressive fall in its incidence. The reason that the rates of peptic ulcer disease decreased is thought to be the development of new effective medication and acid suppressants and the discovery of the cause of the condition, H. pylori.The incidence of duodenal ulcers has dropped significantly during the last 30 years, while the incidence of gastric ulcers has shown a small increase, mainly caused by the widespread use of NSAIDs."}, {"list": ["John Lykoudis", "general practitioner", "Greece", "antibiotics"], "text": "John Lykoudis, a general practitioner in Greece, treated people for peptic ulcer disease with antibiotics, beginning in 1958, long before it was commonly recognized that bacteria were a dominant cause for the disease."}, {"list": ["Helicobacter pylori\'\'", "Australian", "Robin Warren", "Barry J. Marshall"], "text": "Helicobacter pylori was identified in 1982 by two Australian scientists, Robin Warren and Barry J. Marshall as a causative factor for ulcers."}, {"list": ["stress", "spicy food"], "text": "In their original paper, Warren and Marshall contended that most gastric ulcers and gastritis were caused by colonization with this bacterium, not by stress or spicy food as had been assumed before."}, {"text": "The \'\'H."}, {"list": ["self-experimentation", "Petri dish"], "text": "pylori\'\' hypothesis was initially poorly received, so in an act of self-experimentation Marshall drank a Petri dish containing a culture of organisms extracted from a person with an ulcer and five days later developed gastritis."}, {"list": ["halitosis"], "text": "His symptoms disappeared after two weeks, but he took antibiotics to kill the remaining bacteria at the urging of his wife, since halitosis is one of the symptoms of infection."}, {"list": ["Australian Medical Journal"], "text": "This experiment was published in 1984 in the Australian Medical Journal and is among the most cited articles from the journal."}, {"list": ["Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"], "text": "In 1997, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, with other government agencies, academic institutions, and industry, launched a national education campaign to inform health care providers and consumers about the link between \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' and ulcers."}, {"text": "This campaign reinforced the news that ulcers are a curable infection and that health can be greatly improved and money saved by disseminating information about \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\'."}, {"list": ["Karolinska Institute in Stockholm", "Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine", "gastritis"], "text": "In 2005, the Karolinska Institute in Stockholm awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine to Dr. Marshall and his long-time collaborator Dr. Warren \\"for their discovery of the bacterium Helicobacter pylori and its role in gastritis and peptic ulcer disease.\\" Professor Marshall continues research related to \'\'H."}, {"list": ["UWA"], "text": "pylori\'\' and runs a molecular biology lab at UWA in Perth, Western Australia."}, {"list": ["mastic gum"], "text": "Some believed that mastic gum, a tree resin extract, actively eliminates the \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' bacteria."}, {"text": "However, multiple subsequent studies have found no effect of using mastic gum on reducing \'\'H."}, {"text": "pylori\'\' levels."}, {"text": "<references group=\\"nb\\" />"}, {"list": ["Gastric ulcer images"], "text": "* Gastric ulcer images"}]', '{}', '{"list": ["Bleeding", " perforation", " blockage of the stomach"], "conditions": ["Bleeding", "perforation", "blockage of the stomach"]}', '{"desc": "Proton pump inhibitor, H2 blocker, antibiotics", "list": ["Proton pump inhibitor", "H2 blocker", "antibiotics"]}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7d/Deep_gastric_ulcer.png", "file": "File:Deep gastric ulcer.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Deep_gastric_ulcer.png/300px-Deep_gastric_ulcer.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f6/Peptic_Ulcers.webm", "file": "File:Peptic Ulcers.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Peptic_Ulcers.webm/300px-Peptic_Ulcers.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8a/Gastric_Ulcer.png", "file": "File:Gastric Ulcer.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Gastric_Ulcer.png/300px-Gastric_Ulcer.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/41/Duodenal_ulcer01.jpg", "file": "File:Duodenal ulcer01.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Duodenal_ulcer01.jpg/300px-Duodenal_ulcer01.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f2/Gastric_ulcer_3.jpg", "file": "Image:Gastric ulcer 3.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Gastric_ulcer_3.jpg/300px-Gastric_ulcer_3.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Peptic_ulcer.svg", "file": "File:Peptic ulcer.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Peptic_ulcer.svg/300px-Peptic_ulcer.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f1/Benign_gastric_ulcer_1.jpg", "file": "Image:Benign gastric ulcer 1.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Benign_gastric_ulcer_1.jpg/300px-Benign_gastric_ulcer_1.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cb/Erosive_gastric_ulcer.jpg", "file": "File:Erosive gastric ulcer.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Erosive_gastric_ulcer.jpg/300px-Erosive_gastric_ulcer.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1a/Antisectetory_drugs.jpg", "file": "File:Antisectetory drugs.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Antisectetory_drugs.jpg/300px-Antisectetory_drugs.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a5/Peptic_ulcer_disease_world_map-Deaths_per_million_persons-WHO2012.svg", "file": "File:Peptic ulcer disease world map-Deaths per million persons-WHO2012.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Peptic_ulcer_disease_world_map-Deaths_per_million_persons-WHO2012.svg/300px-Peptic_ulcer_disease_world_map-Deaths_per_million_persons-WHO2012.svg"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(27, 'stroke', 'Stroke', 'CT%20scan%20of%20the%20brain%20showing%20a%20right-hemispheric%20ischemic%20stroke.', 'Neurology', '["Inability to move or feel on one side of the body", "problems understanding or speaking", "feeling like the world is spinning", "loss of vision to one side"]', '{"desc": "Based on symptoms and medical imaging", "list": ["medical imaging"]}', '{"desc": "Ischemic and hemorrhagic", "list": ["Ischemic", "hemorrhagic"]}', '[{"list": ["medical", "blood flow", "brain", "cell death"], "text": "Stroke is a medical condition in which poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death."}, {"list": ["ischemic", "hemorrhagic", "bleeding"], "text": "There are two main types of stroke: ischemic, due to lack of blood flow, and hemorrhagic, due to bleeding."}, {"text": "They result in part of the brain not functioning properly."}, {"list": ["inability to move or feel", "problems understanding", "speaking", "feeling like the world is spinning", "loss of vision to one side"], "text": "Signs and symptoms of a stroke may include an inability to move or feel on one side of the body, problems understanding or speaking, feeling like the world is spinning, or loss of vision to one side."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms often appear soon after the stroke has occurred."}, {"list": ["transient ischemic attack"], "text": "If symptoms last less than one or two hours it is known as a transient ischemic attack (TIA) or mini-stroke."}, {"list": ["hemorrhagic stroke", "severe headache"], "text": "A hemorrhagic stroke may also be associated with a severe headache."}, {"text": "The symptoms of a stroke can be permanent."}, {"list": ["pneumonia", "loss of bladder control"], "text": "Long-term complications may include pneumonia or loss of bladder control."}, {"list": ["risk factor", "high blood pressure"], "text": "The main risk factor for stroke is high blood pressure."}, {"list": ["tobacco smoking", "obesity", "high blood cholesterol", "diabetes mellitus", "atrial fibrillation"], "text": "Other risk factors include tobacco smoking, obesity, high blood cholesterol, diabetes mellitus, previous TIA, and atrial fibrillation."}, {"text": "An ischemic stroke is typically caused by blockage of a blood vessel, though there are also less common causes."}, {"list": ["bleeding directly into the brain", "space", "brain\'s membranes"], "text": "A hemorrhagic stroke is caused by either bleeding directly into the brain or into the space between the brain\'s membranes."}, {"list": ["brain aneurysm"], "text": "Bleeding may occur due to a ruptured brain aneurysm."}, {"list": ["medical imaging", "CT scan", "magnetic resonance imaging", "physical exam"], "text": "Diagnosis is typically with medical imaging such as a CT scan or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scan along with a physical exam."}, {"list": ["electrocardiogram", "blood tests"], "text": "Other tests such as an electrocardiogram (ECG) and blood tests are done to determine risk factors and rule out other possible causes."}, {"list": ["Low blood sugar"], "text": "Low blood sugar may cause similar symptoms."}, {"list": ["aspirin", "statins", "surgery to open up the arteries to the brain", "narrowing", "warfarin", "atrial fibrillation"], "text": "Prevention includes decreasing risk factors, as well as possibly aspirin, statins, surgery to open up the arteries to the brain in those with problematic narrowing, and warfarin in those with atrial fibrillation."}, {"text": "A stroke or TIA often requires emergency care."}, {"list": ["medication", "break down the clot"], "text": "An ischemic stroke, if detected within three to four and half hours, may be treatable with a medication that can break down the clot."}, {"text": "Aspirin should be used."}, {"list": ["surgery"], "text": "Some hemorrhagic strokes benefit from surgery."}, {"list": ["stroke rehabilitation", "stroke unit"], "text": "Treatment to try to recover lost function is called stroke rehabilitation and ideally takes place in a stroke unit; however, these are not available in much of the world."}, {"text": "In 2013 approximately 6.9 million people had an ischemic stroke and 3.4 million people had a hemorrhagic stroke."}, {"text": "In 2015 there were about 42.4 million people who had previously had a stroke and were still alive."}, {"list": ["developed world"], "text": "Between 1990 and 2010 the number of strokes which occurred each year decreased by approximately 10% in the developed world and increased by 10% in the developing world."}, {"list": ["coronary artery disease"], "text": "In 2015, stroke was the second most frequent cause of death after coronary artery disease, accounting for 6.3 million deaths (11% of the total)."}, {"text": "About 3.0 million deaths resulted from ischemic stroke while 3.3 million deaths resulted from hemorrhagic stroke."}, {"text": "About half of people who have had a stroke live less than one year."}, {"text": "Overall, two thirds of strokes occurred in those over 65 years old."}, {"list": ["ischemic", "hemorrhagic"], "text": "Strokes can be classified into two major categories: ischemic and hemorrhagic."}, {"list": ["interruption of the blood supply", "blood vessel", "abnormal vascular structure"], "text": "Ischemic strokes are caused by interruption of the blood supply to the brain, while hemorrhagic strokes result from the rupture of a blood vessel or an abnormal vascular structure."}, {"text": "About 87% of strokes are ischemic, the rest being hemorrhagic."}, {"text": "Bleeding can develop inside areas of ischemia, a condition known as \\"hemorrhagic transformation.\\" It is unknown how many hemorrhagic strokes actually start as ischemic strokes."}, {"list": ["World Health Organization"], "text": "In the 1970s the World Health Organization defined stroke as a \\"neurological deficit of cerebrovascular cause that persists beyond 24 hours or is interrupted by death within 24 hours\\", although the word \\"stroke\\" is centuries old."}, {"text": "This definition was supposed to reflect the reversibility of tissue damage and was devised for the purpose, with the time frame of 24 hours being chosen arbitrarily."}, {"list": ["transient ischemic attack"], "text": "The 24-hour limit divides stroke from transient ischemic attack, which is a related syndrome of stroke symptoms that resolve completely within 24 hours."}, {"list": ["heart attack", "acute coronary syndrome"], "text": "With the availability of treatments which can reduce stroke severity when given early, many now prefer alternative terminology, such as brain attack and acute ischemic cerebrovascular syndrome (modeled after heart attack and acute coronary syndrome, respectively), to reflect the urgency of stroke symptoms and the need to act swiftly."}, {"text": "In an ischemic stroke, blood supply to part of the brain is decreased, leading to dysfunction of the brain tissue in that area."}, {"text": "There are four reasons why this might happen:"}, {"text": "There are various classification systems for acute ischemic stroke."}, {"list": ["total anterior circulation infarct", "partial anterior circulation infarct", "lacunar infarct", "posterior circulation infarct"], "text": "The Oxford Community Stroke Project classification (OCSP, also known as the Bamford or Oxford classification) relies primarily on the initial symptoms; based on the extent of the symptoms, the stroke episode is classified as total anterior circulation infarct (TACI), partial anterior circulation infarct (PACI), lacunar infarct (LACI) or posterior circulation infarct (POCI)."}, {"text": "These four entities predict the extent of the stroke, the area of the brain that is affected, the underlying cause, and the prognosis."}, {"text": "Later publications distinguish between \\"syndrome\\" and \\"infarct\\", based on evidence from imaging."}, {"text": "\\"Syndrome\\" may be replaced by \\"hemorrhage\\" if imaging demonstrates a bleed."}, {"list": ["Org 10172", "atherosclerosis", "heart"], "text": "See The TOAST (Trial of Org 10172 in Acute Stroke Treatment) classification is based on clinical symptoms as well as results of further investigations; on this basis, a stroke is classified as being due to (1) thrombosis or embolism due to atherosclerosis of a large artery, (2) an embolism originating in the heart, (3) complete blockage of a small blood vessel, (4) other determined cause, (5) undetermined cause (two possible causes, no cause identified, or incomplete investigation)."}, {"list": ["Users", "stimulants", "cocaine", "methamphetamine"], "text": "Users of stimulants, such as cocaine and methamphetamine are at a high risk for ischemic strokes."}, {"text": "There are two main types of hemorrhagic stroke:"}, {"list": ["cerebral amyloid angiopathy", "cerebral arteriovenous malformation", "intracranial aneurysm"], "text": "Hemorrhagic strokes may occur on the background of alterations to the blood vessels in the brain, such as cerebral amyloid angiopathy, cerebral arteriovenous malformation and an intracranial aneurysm, which can cause intraparenchymal or subarachnoid hemorrhage."}, {"list": ["headache", "thunderclap headache", "head injury"], "text": "In addition to neurological impairment, hemorrhagic strokes usually cause specific symptoms (for instance, subarachnoid hemorrhage classically causes a severe headache known as a thunderclap headache) or reveal evidence of a previous head injury."}, {"text": "Stroke symptoms typically start suddenly, over seconds to minutes, and in most cases do not progress further."}, {"text": "The symptoms depend on the area of the brain affected."}, {"text": "The more extensive the area of the brain affected, the more functions that are likely to be lost."}, {"text": "Some forms of stroke can cause additional symptoms."}, {"text": "For example, in intracranial hemorrhage, the affected area may compress other structures."}, {"list": ["headache"], "text": "Most forms of stroke are not associated with a headache, apart from subarachnoid hemorrhage and cerebral venous thrombosis and occasionally intracerebral hemorrhage."}, {"text": "Various systems have been proposed to increase recognition of stroke."}, {"text": "Different findings are able to predict the presence or absence of stroke to different degrees."}, {"text": "Sudden-onset face weakness, arm drift (i.e., if a person, when asked to raise both arms, involuntarily lets one arm drift downward) and abnormal speech are the findings most likely to lead to the correct identification of a case of stroke increasing the likelihood by 5.5 when at least one of these is present)."}, {"list": ["likelihood ratio"], "text": "Similarly, when all three of these are absent, the likelihood of stroke is significantly decreased (– likelihood ratio of 0.39)."}, {"text": "While these findings are not perfect for diagnosing stroke, the fact that they can be evaluated relatively rapidly and easily make them very valuable in the acute setting."}, {"list": ["FAST", "Department of Health (United Kingdom)", "Stroke Association", "American Stroke Association", "National Stroke Association", "Los Angeles Prehospital Stroke Screen (LAPSS)", "Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale"], "text": "A mnemonic to remember the warning signs of stroke is FAST (facial droop, arm weakness, speech difficulty, and time to call emergency services), as advocated by the Department of Health (United Kingdom) and the Stroke Association, the American Stroke Association, the National Stroke Association (US), the Los Angeles Prehospital Stroke Screen (LAPSS) and the Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale (CPSS)."}, {"text": "Use of these scales is recommended by professional guidelines."}, {"list": ["emergency room"], "text": "For people referred to the emergency room, early recognition of stroke is deemed important as this can expedite diagnostic tests and treatments."}, {"text": "A scoring system called ROSIER (recognition of stroke in the emergency room) is recommended for this purpose; it is based on features from the medical history and physical examination."}, {"list": ["central nervous system pathways", "spinothalamic tract", "corticospinal tract", "posterior column–medial lemniscus pathway"], "text": "If the area of the brain affected contains one of the three prominent central nervous system pathways—the spinothalamic tract, corticospinal tract, and the posterior column–medial lemniscus pathway, symptoms may include:"}, {"list": ["Loss of consciousness", "intracranial pressure"], "text": "Loss of consciousness, headache, and vomiting usually occur more often in hemorrhagic stroke than in thrombosis because of the increased intracranial pressure from the leaking blood compressing the brain."}, {"text": "If symptoms are maximal at onset, the cause is more likely to be a subarachnoid hemorrhage or an embolic stroke."}, {"list": ["atherosclerotic"], "text": "In thrombotic stroke, a thrombus (blood clot) usually forms around atherosclerotic plaques."}, {"text": "Since blockage of the artery is gradual, onset of symptomatic thrombotic strokes is slower than that of a hemorrhagic stroke."}, {"list": ["embolus"], "text": "A thrombus itself (even if it does not completely block the blood vessel) can lead to an embolic stroke (see below) if the thrombus breaks off and travels in the bloodstream, at which point it is called an embolus."}, {"text": "Two types of thrombosis can cause stroke:"}, {"list": ["arterial embolism", "embolus"], "text": "An embolic stroke refers to an arterial embolism (a blockage of an artery) by an embolus, a traveling particle or debris in the arterial bloodstream originating from elsewhere."}, {"list": ["fat", "bone marrow", "broken bone", "cancer", "bacteria", "endocarditis"], "text": "An embolus is most frequently a thrombus, but it can also be a number of other substances including fat (e.g., from bone marrow in a broken bone), air, cancer cells or clumps of bacteria (usually from infectious endocarditis)."}, {"text": "Because an embolus arises from elsewhere, local therapy solves the problem only temporarily."}, {"text": "Thus, the source of the embolus must be identified."}, {"text": "Because the embolic blockage is sudden in onset, symptoms usually are maximal at the start."}, {"text": "Also, symptoms may be transient as the embolus is partially resorbed and moves to a different location or dissipates altogether."}, {"list": ["heart", "atrial fibrillation"], "text": "Emboli most commonly arise from the heart (especially in atrial fibrillation) but may originate from elsewhere in the arterial tree."}, {"list": ["paradoxical embolism", "deep vein thrombosis", "atrial", "ventricular septal defect"], "text": "In paradoxical embolism, a deep vein thrombosis embolizes through an atrial or ventricular septal defect in the heart into the brain."}, {"text": "Causes of stroke related to the heart can be distinguished between high and low-risk:"}, {"list": ["Cerebral hypoperfusion"], "text": "Cerebral hypoperfusion is the reduction of blood flow to all parts of the brain."}, {"text": "The reduction could be to a particular part of the brain depending on the cause."}, {"list": ["heart failure", "cardiac arrest", "cardiac output", "myocardial infarction", "pulmonary embolism", "pericardial effusion"], "text": "It is most commonly due to heart failure from cardiac arrest or arrhythmias, or from reduced cardiac output as a result of myocardial infarction, pulmonary embolism, pericardial effusion, or bleeding."}, {"list": ["Hypoxemia"], "text": "Hypoxemia (low blood oxygen content) may precipitate the hypoperfusion."}, {"text": "Because the reduction in blood flow is global, all parts of the brain may be affected, especially vulnerable \\"watershed\\" areas - border zone regions supplied by the major cerebral arteries."}, {"list": ["watershed stroke"], "text": "A watershed stroke refers to the condition when the blood supply to these areas is compromised."}, {"text": "Blood flow to these areas does not necessarily stop, but instead it may lessen to the point where brain damage can occur."}, {"list": ["Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis"], "text": "Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis leads to stroke due to locally increased venous pressure, which exceeds the pressure generated by the arteries."}, {"text": "Infarcts are more likely to undergo hemorrhagic transformation (leaking of blood into the damaged area) than other types of ischemic stroke."}, {"list": ["cavernous angiomas", "arteriovenous malformations", "amyloid angiopathy"], "text": "It generally occurs in small arteries or arterioles and is commonly due to hypertension, intracranial vascular malformations (including cavernous angiomas or arteriovenous malformations), cerebral amyloid angiopathy, or infarcts into which secondary hemorrhage has occurred."}, {"list": ["bleeding disorders", "amyloid angiopathy", "illicit drug use", "cocaine"], "text": "Other potential causes are trauma, bleeding disorders, amyloid angiopathy, illicit drug use (e.g., amphetamines or cocaine)."}, {"list": ["ventricular system", "CSF"], "text": "The hematoma enlarges until pressure from surrounding tissue limits its growth, or until it decompresses by emptying into the ventricular system, CSF or the pial surface."}, {"text": "A third of intracerebral bleed is into the brain\'s ventricles."}, {"list": ["mortality rate", "subarachnoid hemorrhage"], "text": "ICH has a mortality rate of 44 percent after 30 days, higher than ischemic stroke or subarachnoid hemorrhage (which technically may also be classified as a type of stroke )."}, {"text": "Other causes may include spasm of an artery."}, {"list": ["cocaine"], "text": "This may occur due to cocaine."}, {"list": ["silent stroke"], "text": "A silent stroke is a stroke that does not have any outward symptoms, and the patients are typically unaware they have had a stroke."}, {"list": ["transient ischemic attack"], "text": "Despite not causing identifiable symptoms, a silent stroke still damages the brain, and places the patient at increased risk for both transient ischemic attack and major stroke in the future."}, {"text": "Conversely, those who have had a major stroke are also at risk of having silent strokes."}, {"text": "In a broad study in 1998, more than 11 million people were estimated to have experienced a stroke in the United States."}, {"list": ["hemorrhages"], "text": "Approximately 770,000 of these strokes were symptomatic and 11 million were first-ever silent MRI infarcts or hemorrhages."}, {"list": ["lesions", "MRI"], "text": "Silent strokes typically cause lesions which are detected via the use of neuroimaging such as MRI."}, {"text": "Silent strokes are estimated to occur at five times the rate of symptomatic strokes."}, {"list": ["anemia"], "text": "The risk of silent stroke increases with age, but may also affect younger adults and children, especially those with acute anemia."}, {"list": ["ischemic cascade"], "text": "Ischemic stroke occurs because of a loss of blood supply to part of the brain, initiating the ischemic cascade."}, {"list": ["infarction"], "text": "Brain tissue ceases to function if deprived of oxygen for more than 60 to 90 seconds, and after approximately three hours will suffer irreversible injury possibly leading to the death of the tissue, i.e., infarction."}, {"list": ["alteplase", "emboli"], "text": "(This is why fibrinolytics such as alteplase are given only until three hours since the onset of the stroke.) Atherosclerosis may disrupt the blood supply by narrowing the lumen of blood vessels leading to a reduction of blood flow, by causing the formation of blood clots within the vessel, or by releasing showers of small emboli through the disintegration of atherosclerotic plaques."}, {"text": "Embolic infarction occurs when emboli formed elsewhere in the circulatory system, typically in the heart as a consequence of atrial fibrillation, or in the carotid arteries, break off, enter the cerebral circulation, then lodge in and block brain blood vessels."}, {"list": ["anaerobic metabolism"], "text": "Since blood vessels in the brain are now blocked, the brain becomes low in energy, and thus it resorts into using anaerobic metabolism within the region of brain tissue affected by ischemia."}, {"list": ["adenosine triphosphate", "lactic acid"], "text": "Anaerobic metabolism produces less adenosine triphosphate (ATP) but releases a by-product called lactic acid."}, {"text": "Lactic acid is an irritant which could potentially destroy cells since it is an acid and disrupts the normal acid-base balance in the brain."}, {"list": ["penumbra"], "text": "The ischemia area is referred to as the \\"ischemic penumbra\\"."}, {"list": ["high energy phosphate"], "text": "As oxygen or glucose becomes depleted in ischemic brain tissue, the production of high energy phosphate compounds such as adenosine triphosphate (ATP) fails, leading to failure of energy-dependent processes (such as ion pumping) necessary for tissue cell survival."}, {"text": "This sets off a series of interrelated events that result in cellular injury and death."}, {"text": "A major cause of neuronal injury is the release of the excitatory neurotransmitter glutamate."}, {"text": "The concentration of glutamate outside the cells of the nervous system is normally kept low by so-called uptake carriers, which are powered by the concentration gradients of ions (mainly Na + ) across the cell membrane."}, {"text": "However, stroke cuts off the supply of oxygen and glucose which powers the ion pumps maintaining these gradients."}, {"text": "As a result, the transmembrane ion gradients run down, and glutamate transporters reverse their direction, releasing glutamate into the extracellular space."}, {"text": "Glutamate acts on receptors in nerve cells (especially NMDA receptors), producing an influx of calcium which activates enzymes that digest the cells\' proteins, lipids, and nuclear material."}, {"list": ["mitochondria", "programmed cell death"], "text": "Calcium influx can also lead to the failure of mitochondria, which can lead further toward energy depletion and may trigger cell death due to programmed cell death."}, {"list": ["oxygen free radicals", "reactive oxygen species"], "text": "Ischemia also induces production of oxygen free radicals and other reactive oxygen species."}, {"text": "These react with and damage a number of cellular and extracellular elements."}, {"text": "Damage to the blood vessel lining or endothelium is particularly important."}, {"list": ["uric acid", "NXY-059"], "text": "In fact, many antioxidant neuroprotectants such as uric acid and NXY-059 work at the level of the endothelium and not in the brain per se."}, {"list": ["redox signaling"], "text": "Free radicals also directly initiate elements of the programmed cell death cascade by means of redox signaling."}, {"text": "These processes are the same for any type of ischemic tissue and are referred to collectively as the ischemic cascade."}, {"list": ["aerobic metabolism"], "text": "However, brain tissue is especially vulnerable to ischemia since it has a little respiratory reserve and is completely dependent on aerobic metabolism, unlike most other organs."}, {"list": ["hyaluronic acid", "connective tissue"], "text": "In addition to damaging effects on brain cells, ischemia and infarction can result in loss of structural integrity of brain tissue and blood vessels, partly through the release of matrix metalloproteases, which are zinc- and calcium-dependent enzymes that break down collagen, hyaluronic acid, and other elements of connective tissue."}, {"text": "Other proteases also contribute to this process."}, {"list": ["blood brain barrier", "cerebral edema"], "text": "The loss of vascular structural integrity results in a breakdown of the protective blood brain barrier that contributes to cerebral edema, which can cause secondary progression of the brain injury."}, {"text": "Hemorrhagic strokes are classified based on their underlying pathology."}, {"list": ["hypertensive hemorrhage", "aneurysm", "AV fistula", "bleeding"], "text": "Some causes of hemorrhagic stroke are hypertensive hemorrhage, ruptured aneurysm, ruptured AV fistula, transformation of prior ischemic infarction, and drug induced bleeding."}, {"text": "They result in tissue injury by causing compression of tissue from an expanding hematoma or hematomas."}, {"text": "In addition, the pressure may lead to a loss of blood supply to affected tissue with resulting infarction, and the blood released by brain hemorrhage appears to have direct toxic effects on brain tissue and vasculature."}, {"text": "Inflammation contributes to the secondary brain injury after hemorrhage."}, {"list": ["NIHSS", "MRI scans", "Doppler ultrasound", "arteriography"], "text": "Stroke is diagnosed through several techniques: a neurological examination (such as the NIHSS), CT scans (most often without contrast enhancements) or MRI scans, Doppler ultrasound, and arteriography."}, {"text": "The diagnosis of stroke itself is clinical, with assistance from the imaging techniques."}, {"text": "Imaging techniques also assist in determining the subtypes and cause of stroke."}, {"list": ["blood test"], "text": "There is yet no commonly used blood test for the stroke diagnosis itself, though blood tests may be of help in finding out the likely cause of stroke."}, {"list": ["physical examination", "medical history"], "text": "A physical examination, including taking a medical history of the symptoms and a neurological status, helps giving an evaluation of the location and severity of a stroke."}, {"list": ["NIH stroke scale"], "text": "It can give a standard score on e.g., the NIH stroke scale."}, {"text": "For diagnosing ischemic stroke in the emergency setting:"}, {"text": "For the assessment of stable stroke, nuclear medicine scans SPECT and PET/CT may be helpful."}, {"text": "SPECT documents cerebral blood flow and PET with FDG isotope the metabolic activity of the neurons."}, {"text": "When a stroke has been diagnosed, various other studies may be performed to determine the underlying cause."}, {"text": "With the current treatment and diagnosis options available, it is of particular importance to determine whether there is a peripheral source of emboli."}, {"list": ["comorbidity"], "text": "Test selection may vary since the cause of stroke varies with age, comorbidity and the clinical presentation."}, {"text": "The following are commonly used techniques:"}, {"list": ["prevention", "public health"], "text": "Given the disease burden of strokes, prevention is an important public health concern."}, {"list": ["Primary prevention", "number needed to treat"], "text": "Primary prevention is less effective than secondary prevention (as judged by the number needed to treat to prevent one stroke per year)."}, {"text": "Recent guidelines detail the evidence for primary prevention in stroke."}, {"text": "In those who are otherwise healthy, aspirin does not appear beneficial and thus is not recommended."}, {"text": "In people who have had a myocardial infarction or those with a high cardiovascular risk, it provides some protection against a first stroke."}, {"list": ["aspirin", "clopidogrel", "dipyridamole"], "text": "In those who have previously had a stroke, treatment with medications such as aspirin, clopidogrel, and dipyridamole may be beneficial."}, {"list": ["U.S. Preventive Services Task Force", "screening", "carotid artery stenosis"], "text": "The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends against screening for carotid artery stenosis in those without symptoms."}, {"text": "The most important modifiable risk factors for stroke are high blood pressure and atrial fibrillation although the size of the effect is small with 833 people have to be treated for 1 year to prevent one stroke."}, {"list": ["alcohol", "physical activity", "obesity", "red meat"], "text": "Other modifiable risk factors include high blood cholesterol levels, diabetes mellitus, cigarette smoking (active and passive), heavy alcohol consumption, drug use, lack of physical activity, obesity, processed red meat consumption, and unhealthy diet."}, {"text": "Smoking just one cigarette per day increases the risk more than 30%."}, {"list": ["thrombocytosis", "platelet aggregation", "clotting"], "text": "Alcohol use could predispose to ischemic stroke, and intracerebral and subarachnoid hemorrhage via multiple mechanisms (for example via hypertension, atrial fibrillation, rebound thrombocytosis and platelet aggregation and clotting disturbances)."}, {"text": "Drugs, most commonly amphetamines and cocaine, can induce stroke through damage to the blood vessels in the brain and acute hypertension."}, {"list": ["Migraine", "aura"], "text": "Migraine with aura doubles a person\'s risk for ischemic stroke."}, {"list": ["celiac disease"], "text": "Untreated, celiac disease can be an underlying cause of stroke, both in children and adults."}, {"text": "High levels of physical activity reduce the risk of stroke by about 26%."}, {"text": "There is a lack of high quality studies looking at promotional efforts to improve lifestyle factors."}, {"text": "Nonetheless, given the large body of circumstantial evidence, best medical management for stroke includes advice on diet, exercise, smoking and alcohol use."}, {"list": ["carotid endarterectomy"], "text": "Medication is the most common method of stroke prevention; carotid endarterectomy can be a useful surgical method of preventing stroke."}, {"list": ["High blood pressure"], "text": "High blood pressure accounts for 35–50% of stroke risk."}, {"text": "Blood pressure reduction of 10 mmHg systolic or 5 mmHg diastolic reduces the risk of stroke by ~40%."}, {"text": "Lowering blood pressure has been conclusively shown to prevent both ischemic and hemorrhagic strokes."}, {"text": "It is equally important in secondary prevention."}, {"list": ["isolated systolic hypertension"], "text": "Even patients older than 80 years and those with isolated systolic hypertension benefit from antihypertensive therapy."}, {"text": "The available evidence does not show large differences in stroke prevention between antihypertensive drugs —therefore, other factors such as protection against other forms of cardiovascular disease and cost should be considered."}, {"list": ["beta-blockers"], "text": "The routine use of beta-blockers following a stroke or TIA has not been shown to result in benefits."}, {"text": "High cholesterol levels have been inconsistently associated with (ischemic) stroke."}, {"list": ["Statins"], "text": "Statins have been shown to reduce the risk of stroke by about 15%."}, {"list": ["lipid-lowering drugs"], "text": "Since earlier meta-analyses of other lipid-lowering drugs did not show a decreased risk, statins might exert their effect through mechanisms other than their lipid-lowering effects."}, {"list": ["Diabetes mellitus"], "text": "Diabetes mellitus increases the risk of stroke by 2 to 3 times."}, {"list": ["kidney damage", "damage to the retina of the eye"], "text": "While intensive blood sugar control has been shown to reduce small blood vessel complications such as kidney damage and damage to the retina of the eye it has not been shown to reduce large blood vessel complications such as stroke."}, {"list": ["warfarin"], "text": "Oral anticoagulants such as warfarin have been the mainstay of stroke prevention for over 50 years."}, {"list": ["antiplatelets", "secondary prevention"], "text": "However, several studies have shown that aspirin and other antiplatelets are highly effective in secondary prevention after a stroke or transient ischemic attack."}, {"text": "Low doses of aspirin (for example 75–150 mg) are as effective as high doses but have fewer side effects; the lowest effective dose remains unknown."}, {"list": ["Thienopyridines", "clopidogrel", "ticlopidine", "gastrointestinal bleeding"], "text": "Thienopyridines (clopidogrel, ticlopidine) might be slightly more effective than aspirin and have a decreased risk of gastrointestinal bleeding, but are more expensive."}, {"text": "Clopidogrel has less side effects than ticlopidine."}, {"list": ["Dipyridamole"], "text": "Dipyridamole can be added to aspirin therapy to provide a small additional benefit, even though headache is a common side effect."}, {"text": "Low-dose aspirin is also effective for stroke prevention after having a myocardial infarction."}, {"list": ["atrial fibrillation"], "text": "Those with atrial fibrillation have a 5% a year risk of stroke, and this risk is higher in those with valvular atrial fibrillation."}, {"list": ["warfarin", "oral anticoagulants"], "text": "Depending on the stroke risk, anticoagulation with medications such as warfarin or aspirin is useful for prevention.<ref name=\\"AFib-guidelines\\"> Except in people with atrial fibrillation, oral anticoagulants are not advised for stroke prevention —any benefit is offset by bleeding risk."}, {"text": "In primary prevention however, antiplatelet drugs did not reduce the risk of ischemic stroke but increased the risk of major bleeding."}, {"text": "Further studies are needed to investigate a possible protective effect of aspirin against ischemic stroke in women."}, {"list": ["Carotid endarterectomy", "angioplasty", "carotid artery"], "text": "Carotid endarterectomy or carotid angioplasty can be used to remove atherosclerotic narrowing of the carotid artery."}, {"text": "There is evidence supporting this procedure in selected cases."}, {"text": "Endarterectomy for a significant stenosis has been shown to be useful in preventing further strokes in those who have already had one."}, {"text": "Carotid artery stenting has not been shown to be equally useful."}, {"text": "People are selected for surgery based on age, gender, degree of stenosis, time since symptoms and the person\'s preferences."}, {"text": "Surgery is most efficient when not delayed too long —the risk of recurrent stroke in a patient who has a 50% or greater stenosis is up to 20% after 5 years, but endarterectomy reduces this risk to around 5%. The number of procedures needed to cure one patient was 5 for early surgery (within two weeks after the initial stroke), but 125 if delayed longer than 12 weeks."}, {"list": ["Screening"], "text": "Screening for carotid artery narrowing has not been shown to be a useful test in the general population."}, {"text": "Studies of surgical intervention for carotid artery stenosis without symptoms have shown only a small decrease in the risk of stroke."}, {"text": "To be beneficial, the complication rate of the surgery should be kept below 4%. Even then, for 100 surgeries, 5 patients will benefit by avoiding stroke, 3 will develop stroke despite surgery, 3 will develop stroke or die due to the surgery itself, and 89 will remain stroke-free but would also have done so without intervention."}, {"list": ["Mediterranean-style diet"], "text": "Nutrition, specifically the Mediterranean-style diet, has the potential for decreasing the risk of having a stroke by more than half."}, {"list": ["homocysteine", "folic acid"], "text": "It does not appear that lowering levels of homocysteine with folic acid affects the risk of stroke."}, {"text": "A number of specific recommendations have been made for women including taking aspirin after the 11th week of pregnancy if there is a history of previous chronic high blood pressure and taking blood pressure medications during pregnancy if the blood pressure is greater than 150 mmHg systolic or greater than 100 mmHg diastolic.<!"}, {"list": ["preeclampsia"], "text": "--> In those who have previously had preeclampsia other risk factors should be treated more aggressively."}, {"text": "Keeping blood pressure below 140/90 mmHg is recommended."}, {"text": "Anticoagulation can prevent recurrent ischemic strokes."}, {"text": "Among people with nonvalvular atrial fibrillation, anticoagulation can reduce stroke by 60% while antiplatelet agents can reduce stroke by 20%."}, {"text": "However, a recent meta-analysis suggests harm from anticoagulation started early after an embolic stroke."}, {"list": ["CHA2DS2–VASc score"], "text": "Stroke prevention treatment for atrial fibrillation is determined according to the CHA2DS2–VASc score."}, {"list": ["warfarin", "dabigatran", "prothrombin time"], "text": "The most widely used anticoagulant to prevent thromboembolic stroke in patients with nonvalvular atrial fibrillation is the oral agent warfarin while a number of newer agents including dabigatran are alternatives which do not require prothrombin time monitoring."}, {"text": "Anticoagulants, when used following stroke, should not be stopped for dental procedures."}, {"text": "If studies show carotid artery stenosis, and the person has a degree of residual function on the affected side, carotid endarterectomy (surgical removal of the stenosis) may decrease the risk of recurrence if performed rapidly after stroke."}, {"list": ["thrombolysis", "thrombectomy"], "text": "Aspirin reduces the overall risk of recurrence by 13% with greater benefit early on. Definitive therapy within the first few hours is aimed at removing the blockage by breaking the clot down (thrombolysis), or by removing it mechanically (thrombectomy)."}, {"text": "The philosophical premise underlying the importance of rapid stroke intervention was summed up as Time is Brain! in the early 1990s."}, {"text": "Years later, that same idea, that rapid cerebral blood flow restoration results in fewer brain cells dying, has been proved and quantified."}, {"text": "Tight blood sugar control in the first few hours does not improve outcomes and may cause harm."}, {"text": "High blood pressure is also not typically lowered as this has not been found to be helpful."}, {"list": ["Cerebrolysin"], "text": "Cerebrolysin, a mix of pig brain tissue used to treat acute ischemic stroke in many Asian and European countries, does not improve outcomes and may increase the risk of severe adverse events."}, {"list": ["Thrombolysis", "recombinant tissue plasminogen activator"], "text": "Thrombolysis, such as with recombinant tissue plasminogen activator (rtPA), in acute ischemic stroke, when given within three hours of symptom onset results in an overall benefit of 10% with respect to living without disability."}, {"text": "<ref name=\\"Lancet2014\\"> It does not, however, improve chances of survival."}, {"text": "Benefit is greater the earlier it is used."}, {"text": "Between three and four and a half hours the effects are less clear."}, {"text": "A 2014 review found a 5% increase in the number of people living without disability at three to six months; however, there was a 2% increased risk of death in the short term."}, {"text": "After four and a half hours thrombolysis worsens outcomes."}, {"text": "These benefits or lack of benefits occurred regardless of the age of the person treated."}, {"text": "There is no reliable way to determine who will have an intracranial bleed post-treatment versus who will not."}, {"list": ["American Heart Association", "American Academy of Neurology"], "text": "Its use is endorsed by the American Heart Association and the American Academy of Neurology as the recommended treatment for acute stroke within three hours of onset of symptoms as long as there are not other contraindications (such as abnormal lab values, high blood pressure, or recent surgery)."}, {"text": "This position for tPA is based upon the findings of two studies by one group of investigators which showed that tPA improves the chances for a good neurological outcome."}, {"text": "When administered within the first three hours thrombolysis improves functional outcome without affecting mortality."}, {"text": "6.4% of people with large strokes developed substantial brain bleeding as a complication from being given tPA thus part of the reason for increased short term mortality."}, {"list": ["American Academy of Emergency Medicine", "standard of care"], "text": "Additionally, the American Academy of Emergency Medicine states that objective evidence regarding the efficacy, safety, and applicability of tPA for acute ischemic stroke is insufficient to warrant its classification as standard of care."}, {"list": ["Intra-arterial fibrinolysis"], "text": "Intra-arterial fibrinolysis, where a catheter is passed up an artery into the brain and the medication is injected at the site of thrombosis, has been found to improve outcomes in people with acute ischemic stroke."}, {"list": ["Surgical removal of the blood clot"], "text": "Surgical removal of the blood clot causing the ischemic stroke may improve outcomes if done within 7 hours of the start of symptoms in those with an anterior circulation large artery clot."}, {"text": "It however does not change the risk of death."}, {"text": "Significant complications occur in about 7%. Intravenous thrombolysis is generally used in eligible people even if they are being considered for mechanical thrombectomy."}, {"text": "Certain cases may benefit from thrombectomy up to 24 hours after the onset of symptoms."}, {"text": "Strokes affecting large portions of the brain can cause significant brain swelling with secondary brain injury in surrounding tissue."}, {"text": "This phenomenon is mainly encountered in strokes affecting brain tissue dependent upon the middle cerebral artery for blood supply and is also called \\"malignant cerebral infarction\\" because it carries a dismal prognosis."}, {"list": ["hemicraniectomy"], "text": "Relief of the pressure may be attempted with medication, but some require hemicraniectomy, the temporary surgical removal of the skull on one side of the head."}, {"text": "This decreases the risk of death, although some more people survive with disability who would otherwise have died."}, {"list": ["intracerebral hemorrhage"], "text": "People with intracerebral hemorrhage require supportive care, including blood pressure control if required."}, {"text": "People are monitored for changes in the level of consciousness, and their blood sugar and oxygenation are kept at optimum levels."}, {"text": "Anticoagulants and antithrombotics can make bleeding worse and are generally discontinued (and reversed if possible)."}, {"list": ["neurosurgical"], "text": "A proportion may benefit from neurosurgical intervention to remove the blood and treat the underlying cause, but this depends on the location and the size of the hemorrhage as well as patient-related factors, and ongoing research is being conducted into the question as to which people with intracerebral hemorrhage may benefit."}, {"text": "In subarachnoid hemorrhage, early treatment for underlying cerebral aneurysms may reduce the risk of further hemorrhages."}, {"list": ["surgery that involves opening the skull"], "text": "Depending on the site of the aneurysm this may be by surgery that involves opening the skull or endovascularly (through the blood vessels)."}, {"text": "Ideally, people who have had a stroke are admitted to a \\"stroke unit\\", a ward or dedicated area in a hospital staffed by nurses and therapists with experience in stroke treatment."}, {"text": "It has been shown that people admitted to a stroke unit have a higher chance of surviving than those admitted elsewhere in hospital, even if they are being cared for by doctors without experience in stroke."}, {"list": ["Stroke rehabilitation"], "text": "Stroke rehabilitation is the process by which those with disabling strokes undergo treatment to help them return to normal life as much as possible by regaining and relearning the skills of everyday living."}, {"text": "It also aims to help the survivor understand and adapt to difficulties, prevent secondary complications and educate family members to play a supporting role."}, {"text": "A rehabilitation team is usually multidisciplinary as it involves staff with different skills working together to help the patient."}, {"list": ["clinical pharmacists", "physiotherapists", "occupational therapists", "speech and language therapists", "orthotists"], "text": "These include physicians trained in rehabilitation medicine, clinical pharmacists, nursing staff, physiotherapists, occupational therapists, speech and language therapists, and orthotists."}, {"list": ["psychologists", "social workers", "post stroke depression"], "text": "Some teams may also include psychologists and social workers, since at least one-third of affected people manifests post stroke depression."}, {"list": ["Barthel scale"], "text": "Validated instruments such as the Barthel scale may be used to assess the likelihood of a stroke patient being able to manage at home with or without support subsequent to discharge from a hospital."}, {"list": ["nursing care", "skin care", "vital signs"], "text": "Good nursing care is fundamental in maintaining skin care, feeding, hydration, positioning, and monitoring vital signs such as temperature, pulse, and blood pressure."}, {"text": "Stroke rehabilitation begins almost immediately."}, {"list": ["physical therapy", "occupational therapy", "speech-language pathology"], "text": "For most people with stroke, physical therapy (PT), occupational therapy (OT) and speech-language pathology (SLP) are the cornerstones of the rehabilitation process."}, {"list": ["assistive technology", "wheelchairs"], "text": "Often, assistive technology such as wheelchairs, walkers and canes may be beneficial."}, {"list": ["ankle foot orthoses"], "text": "Many mobility problems can be improved by the use of ankle foot orthoses."}, {"text": "PT and OT have overlapping areas of expertise; however, PT focuses on joint range of motion and strength by performing exercises and relearning functional tasks such as bed mobility, transferring, walking and other gross motor functions."}, {"list": ["hemiplegic"], "text": "Physiotherapists can also work with patients to improve awareness and use of the hemiplegic side."}, {"text": "Rehabilitation involves working on the ability to produce strong movements or the ability to perform tasks using normal patterns."}, {"text": "Emphasis is often concentrated on functional tasks and patient’s goals."}, {"list": ["motor learning", "constraint-induced movement therapy"], "text": "One example physiotherapists employ to promote motor learning involves constraint-induced movement therapy."}, {"text": "Through continuous practice the patient relearns to use and adapt the hemiplegic limb during functional activities to create lasting permanent changes."}, {"list": ["activities of daily living", "reading", "writing"], "text": "OT is involved in training to help relearn everyday activities known as the activities of daily living (ADLs) such as eating, drinking, dressing, bathing, cooking, reading and writing, and toileting."}, {"list": ["Speech and language therapy", "dysarthria", "apraxia of speech", "aphasia", "problems with swallowing"], "text": "Speech and language therapy is appropriate for people with the speech production disorders: dysarthria and apraxia of speech, aphasia, cognitive-communication impairments, and problems with swallowing."}, {"list": ["dysphagia", "aspiration pneumonia"], "text": "Patients may have particular problems, such as dysphagia, which can cause swallowed material to pass into the lungs and cause aspiration pneumonia."}, {"list": ["nasogastric tube"], "text": "The condition may improve with time, but in the interim, a nasogastric tube may be inserted, enabling liquid food to be given directly into the stomach."}, {"list": ["percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy"], "text": "If swallowing is still deemed unsafe, then a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG) tube is passed and this can remain indefinitely."}, {"text": "Treatment of spasticity related to stroke often involves early mobilizations, commonly performed by a physiotherapist, combined with elongation of spastic muscles and sustained stretching through various positionings."}, {"text": "Gaining initial improvement in range of motion is often achieved through rhythmic rotational patterns associated with the affected limb."}, {"text": "After full range has been achieved by the therapist, the limb should be positioned in the lengthened positions to prevent against further contractures, skin breakdown, and disuse of the limb with the use of splints or other tools to stabilize the joint."}, {"text": "Cold in the form of ice wraps or ice packs have been proven to briefly reduce spasticity by temporarily dampening neural firing rates."}, {"list": ["Electrical stimulation"], "text": "Electrical stimulation to the antagonist muscles or vibrations has also been used with some success."}, {"list": ["Stroke rehabilitation"], "text": "Stroke rehabilitation should be started as quickly as possible and can last anywhere from a few days to over a year."}, {"list": ["U.S. state"], "text": "Most return of function is seen in the first few months, and then improvement falls off with the \\"window\\" considered officially by U.S. state rehabilitation units and others to be closed after six months, with little chance of further improvement."}, {"text": "However, patients have been known to continue to improve for years, regaining and strengthening abilities like writing, walking, running, and talking."}, {"text": "Daily rehabilitation exercises should continue to be part of the stroke patient\'s routine."}, {"text": "Complete recovery is unusual but not impossible and most patients will improve to some extent: proper diet and exercise are known to help the brain to recover."}, {"list": ["virtual reality"], "text": "Some current and future therapy methods include the use of virtual reality and video games for rehabilitation."}, {"text": "These forms of rehabilitation offer potential for motivating patients to perform specific therapy tasks that many other forms do not."}, {"text": "Many clinics and hospitals are adopting the use of these off-the-shelf devices for exercise, social interaction, and rehabilitation because they are affordable, accessible and can be used within the clinic and home."}, {"list": ["Mirror therapy"], "text": "Mirror therapy is associated with improved motor function of the upper extremity in patients with stroke."}, {"list": ["transcranial magnetic stimulation", "transcranial direct-current stimulation"], "text": "Other non-invasive rehabilitation methods used to augment physical therapy of motor function in stroke patients include transcranial magnetic stimulation and transcranial direct-current stimulation."}, {"list": ["robotic therapies"], "text": "and robotic therapies."}, {"text": "A stroke can also reduce people\'s general fitness."}, {"text": "Reduced fitness can reduce capacity for rehabilitation as well as general health."}, {"text": "Physical exercises as part of a rehabilitation program following a stroke appear safe."}, {"text": "Cardiorespiratory fitness training that involves walking in rehabilitation can improve speed, tolerance and independence during walking, and may improve balance."}, {"text": "There are inadequate long-term data about the effects of exercise and training on death, dependence and disability after a stroke."}, {"text": "The future areas of research may concentrate on the optimal exercise prescription and long term health benefits of exercise."}, {"text": "The effect of physical training on cognition also may be studied further."}, {"text": "The ability to walk independently in their community, indoors or outdoors, is important following stroke."}, {"text": "Although no negative effects have been reported, it is unclear if outcomes can improve with these walking programs when compared to usual treatment."}, {"text": "A stroke can affect the ability to live independently and with quality.<!-- --> Self-management programs are a special training that educates stroke survivors about stroke and its consequences, helps them acquire skills to cope with their challenges, and helps them set and meet their own goals during their recovery process.<!-- --> These programs are tailored to the target audience, and lead by someone trained and expert in stroke and its consequences (most commonly professionals, but also stroke survivors and peers).<!-- --> A 2016 review reported that these programs improve the quality of life after stroke, without negative effects.<!-- --> People with stroke felt more empowered, happy and satisfied with life after participating in this training."}, {"text": "Disability affects 75% of stroke survivors enough to decrease their employability."}, {"text": "Stroke can affect people physically, mentally, emotionally, or a combination of the three."}, {"text": "The results of stroke vary widely depending on size and location of the lesion."}, {"text": "Dysfunctions correspond to areas in the brain that have been damaged."}, {"list": ["pressure sores", "pneumonia", "incontinence", "apraxia", "daily activities", "speech loss", "vision loss", "pain"], "text": "Some of the physical disabilities that can result from stroke include muscle weakness, numbness, pressure sores, pneumonia, incontinence, apraxia (inability to perform learned movements), difficulties carrying out daily activities, appetite loss, speech loss, vision loss and pain."}, {"list": ["coma"], "text": "If the stroke is severe enough, or in a certain location such as parts of the brainstem, coma or death can result."}, {"text": "Emotional problems following a stroke can be due to direct damage to emotional centers in the brain or from frustration and difficulty adapting to new limitations."}, {"list": ["anxiety", "panic attacks", "flat affect", "mania", "apathy", "psychosis"], "text": "Post-stroke emotional difficulties include anxiety, panic attacks, flat affect (failure to express emotions), mania, apathy and psychosis."}, {"text": "Other difficulties may include a decreased ability to communicate emotions through facial expression, body language and voice."}, {"text": "Disruption in self-identity, relationships with others, and emotional well-being can lead to social consequences after stroke due to the lack of ability to communicate."}, {"text": "Many people who experience communication impairments after a stroke find it more difficult to cope with the social issues rather than physical impairments."}, {"text": "Broader aspects of care must address the emotional impact speech impairment has on those who experience difficulties with speech after a stroke."}, {"list": ["paralysis"], "text": "Those who experience a stroke are at risk of paralysis which could result in a self disturbed body image which may also lead to other social issues."}, {"list": ["sleep disturbances", "self-esteem"], "text": "30 to 50% of stroke survivors suffer post-stroke depression, which is characterized by lethargy, irritability, sleep disturbances, lowered self-esteem and withdrawal."}, {"list": ["Depression", "antidepressants"], "text": "Depression can reduce motivation and worsen outcome, but can be treated with social and family support, psychotherapy and, in severe cases, antidepressants."}, {"list": ["Emotional lability"], "text": "Emotional lability, another consequence of stroke, causes the person to switch quickly between emotional highs and lows and to express emotions inappropriately, for instance with an excess of laughing or crying with little or no provocation."}, {"text": "While these expressions of emotion usually correspond to the person\'s actual emotions, a more severe form of emotional lability causes the affected person to laugh and cry pathologically, without regard to context or emotion."}, {"text": "Some people show the opposite of what they feel, for example crying when they are happy."}, {"text": "Emotional lability occurs in about 20% of those who have had a stroke."}, {"text": "Those with a right hemisphere stroke are more likely to have an empathy problems which can make communication harder."}, {"list": ["aphasia", "dementia"], "text": "Cognitive deficits resulting from stroke include perceptual disorders, aphasia, dementia, and problems with attention and memory."}, {"list": ["anosognosia"], "text": "A stroke sufferer may be unaware of his or her own disabilities, a condition called anosognosia."}, {"list": ["hemispatial neglect"], "text": "In a condition called hemispatial neglect, the affected person is unable to attend to anything on the side of space opposite to the damaged hemisphere."}, {"text": "Cognitive and psychological outcome after a stroke can be affected by the age at which the stroke happened, pre-stroke baseline intellectual functioning, psychiatric history and whether there is pre-existing brain pathology."}, {"list": ["seizures"], "text": "Up to 10% of people following a stroke develop seizures, most commonly in the week subsequent to the event; the severity of the stroke increases the likelihood of a seizure."}, {"list": ["Disability-adjusted life year", "stroke belt", "southeastern United States", "increases exponentially", "Von Willebrand factor", "blood type", "menopause", "HRT"], "text": "Stroke world map-Deaths per million persons-WHO2012.svg from 30 years of age, and the cause varies by age. Advanced age is one of the most significant stroke risk factors. 95% of strokes occur in people age 45 and older, and two-thirds of strokes occur in those over the age of 65. A person\'s risk of dying if he or she does have a stroke also increases with age. However, stroke can occur at any age, including in childhood.Family members may have a genetic tendency for stroke or share a lifestyle that contributes to stroke. Higher levels of Von Willebrand factor are more common amongst people who have had ischemic stroke for the first time. The results of this study found that the only significant genetic factor was the person\'s blood type. Having had a stroke in the past greatly increases one\'s risk of future strokes.Men are 25% more likely to suffer strokes than women, yet 60% of deaths from stroke occur in women. Since women live longer, they are older on average when they have their strokes and thus more often killed. Some risk factors for stroke apply only to women. Primary among these are pregnancy, childbirth, menopause, and the treatment thereof (HRT)."}, {"text": "Episodes of stroke and familial stroke have been reported from the 2nd millennium BC onward in ancient Mesopotamia and Persia."}, {"list": ["Hippocrates", "paralysis", "ischemia"], "text": "Hippocrates (460 to 370 BC) was first to describe the phenomenon of sudden paralysis that is often associated with ischemia."}, {"list": ["Apoplexy", "Greek"], "text": "Apoplexy, from the Greek word meaning \\"struck down with violence\\", first appeared in Hippocratic writings to describe this phenomenon."}, {"list": ["seizure"], "text": "The word stroke was used as a synonym for apoplectic seizure as early as 1599, and is a fairly literal translation of the Greek term."}, {"list": ["Johann Jacob Wepfer", "hemorrhagic", "died"], "text": "In 1658, in his Apoplexia, Johann Jacob Wepfer (1620–1695) identified the cause of hemorrhagic stroke when he suggested that people who had died of apoplexy had bleeding in their brains."}, {"list": ["arteries", "vertebral", "carotid", "ischemic", "cerebral infarction", "apoplexy"], "text": "Wepfer also identified the main arteries supplying the brain, the vertebral and carotid arteries, and identified the cause of a type of ischemic stroke known as a cerebral infarction when he suggested that apoplexy might be caused by a blockage to those vessels."}, {"list": ["Rudolf Virchow", "thromboembolism"], "text": "Rudolf Virchow first described the mechanism of thromboembolism as a major factor."}, {"text": "The term cerebrovascular accident was introduced in 1927, reflecting a \\"growing awareness and acceptance of vascular theories and (...) recognition of the consequences of a sudden disruption in the vascular supply of the brain\\"."}, {"text": "Its use is now discouraged by a number of neurology textbooks, reasoning that the connotation of fortuitousness carried by the word accident insufficiently highlights the modifiability of the underlying risk factors."}, {"text": "Cerebrovascular insult may be used interchangeably."}, {"list": ["American Stroke Association"], "text": "The term brain attack was introduced for use to underline the acute nature of stroke according to the American Stroke Association, who since 1990 have used the term, and is used colloquially to refer to both ischemic as well as hemorrhagic stroke."}, {"list": ["Angioplasty", "stenting"], "text": "Angioplasty and stenting have begun to be looked at as possible viable options in treatment of acute ischemic stroke."}, {"text": "Intra-cranial stenting in symptomatic intracranial arterial stenosis, the rate of technical success (reduction to stenosis of <50%) ranged from 90-98%, and the rate of major peri-procedural complications ranged from 4-10%."}, {"text": "The rates of restenosis and stroke following the treatment were also favorable."}, {"list": ["randomized controlled trial"], "text": "This data suggests that a randomized controlled trial is needed to more completely evaluate the possible therapeutic advantage of this preventative measure."}, {"list": ["Neuroprotective", "antioxidants", "reactive oxygen species", "programmed cell death", "excitatory neurotransmitters", "tissue injury"], "text": "Neuroprotective agents including antioxidants which combat reactive oxygen species, or inhibit programmed cell death, or inhibit excitatory neurotransmitters have been shown experimentally to reduce tissue injury caused by ischemia."}, {"list": ["clinical trials", "barbiturate-induced coma"], "text": "Until recently, human clinical trials with neuroprotective agents have failed, with the probable exception of deep barbiturate-induced coma."}, {"list": ["Disufenton sodium"], "text": "Disufenton sodium, the disulfonyl derivative of the radical-scavenging phenylbutylnitrone, was reported to be neuroprotective."}, {"list": ["blood vessel lining"], "text": "This agent is thought to work at the level of the blood vessel lining."}, {"text": "However the favourable results evidenced from one large-scale trial were not reproduced in a second trial."}, {"text": "So that the benefit of disufenton sodium is questionable."}, {"list": ["Hyperbaric oxygen therapy"], "text": "Hyperbaric oxygen therapy has been studied as a possible protective measure, but as of 2014, while the benefits of this have not been ruled out, further research is said to be needed."}, {"text": "Modulating microglial activation and polarization might mitigate hemorrhagic stroke injury and improve brain repair."}]', '{}', '{"list": ["Persistent vegetative state"], "conditions": ["Persistent vegetative state"]}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/49/MCA_Territory_Infarct.svg", "file": "File:MCA Territory Infarct.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/MCA_Territory_Infarct.svg/300px-MCA_Territory_Infarct.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/36/MCA-Stroke-Brain-Human-2.JPG", "file": "File:MCA-Stroke-Brain-Human-2.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/MCA-Stroke-Brain-Human-2.JPG/300px-MCA-Stroke-Brain-Human-2.JPG"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/32/Parachemableedwithedema.png", "file": "File:Parachemableedwithedema.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Parachemableedwithedema.png/300px-Parachemableedwithedema.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b4/Blausen_0836_Stroke.png", "file": "File:Blausen 0836 Stroke.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Blausen_0836_Stroke.png/300px-Blausen_0836_Stroke.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/92/StrokeMCA_overlay.png", "file": "File:StrokeMCA overlay.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/StrokeMCA_overlay.png/300px-StrokeMCA_overlay.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/03/Dens_media_sign_mit_Mediainfarkt_-_CCT_001.jpg", "file": "File:Dens media sign mit Mediainfarkt - CCT 001.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Dens_media_sign_mit_Mediainfarkt_-_CCT_001.jpg/300px-Dens_media_sign_mit_Mediainfarkt_-_CCT_001.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/71/Left_MCA_Stroke.png", "file": "File:Left MCA Stroke.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Left_MCA_Stroke.png/300px-Left_MCA_Stroke.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7c/Hippocrates.jpg", "file": "File:Hippocrates.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Hippocrates.jpg/300px-Hippocrates.jpg"}]');
