(30, 'sunburn', 'Sunburn', 'A%20sunburnt%20back%20that%20was%20partially%20protected%20by%20a%20bathing%20suit%20top.', 'Dermatology', 'null', '{}', '{}', '[{"list": ["radiation burn", "skin", "ultraviolet", "sun"], "text": "Sunburn is a form of radiation burn that affects living tissue, such as skin, that results from an overexposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation, commonly from the sun."}, {"list": ["red or reddish skin", "pain"], "text": "Common symptoms in humans and other animals include red or reddish skin that is hot to the touch, pain, general fatigue, and mild dizziness."}, {"text": "An excess of UV radiation can be life-threatening in extreme cases."}, {"list": ["suntan"], "text": "Exposure of the skin to lesser amounts of UV radiation will often produce a suntan."}, {"list": ["tumors"], "text": "Excessive UV radiation is the leading cause of primarily non-malignant skin tumors."}, {"list": ["Sunscreen", "skin cancer"], "text": "Sunscreen is widely agreed to prevent sunburn and some types of skin cancer."}, {"text": "Clothing, including hats, is considered the preferred skin protection method."}, {"list": ["melanin", "photoprotective", "pigment"], "text": "Moderate sun tanning without burning can also prevent subsequent sunburn, as it increases the amount of melanin, a photoprotective pigment that is the skin\'s natural defense against overexposure."}, {"list": ["direct DNA damage"], "text": "Importantly, both sunburn and the increase in melanin production are triggered by direct DNA damage."}, {"list": ["type I cell-death"], "text": "When the skin cells\' DNA is overly damaged by UV radiation, type I cell-death is triggered and the skin is replaced."}, {"text": "Typically, there is initial redness (erythema), followed by varying degrees of pain, proportional in severity to both the duration and intensity of exposure."}, {"list": ["edema", "itching", "peeling skin", "rash", "nausea", "fever", "chills", "syncope"], "text": "Other symptoms can include edema, itching, peeling skin, rash, nausea, fever, chills, and syncope."}, {"text": "Also, a small amount of heat is given off from the burn, caused by the concentration of blood in the healing process, giving a warm feeling to the affected area."}, {"list": ["burns"], "text": "Sunburns may be classified as superficial, or partial thickness burns."}, {"text": "Minor sunburns typically cause nothing more than slight redness and tenderness to the affected areas."}, {"text": "In more serious cases, blistering can occur."}, {"text": "Extreme sunburns can be painful to the point of debilitation and may require hospital care."}, {"text": "Sunburn can occur in less than 15 minutes, and in seconds when exposed to non-shielded welding arcs or other sources of intense ultraviolet light."}, {"text": "Nevertheless, the inflicted harm is often not immediately obvious."}, {"text": "After the exposure, skin may turn red in as little as 30 minutes but most often takes 2 to 6 hours."}, {"text": "Pain is usually most extreme 6 to 48 hours after exposure."}, {"text": "The burn continues to develop for 1 to 3 days, occasionally followed by peeling skin in 3 to 8 days."}, {"text": "Some peeling and itching may continue for several weeks."}, {"list": ["melanoma", "basal-cell carcinoma", "squamous-cell carcinoma"], "text": "Ultraviolet radiation causes sunburns and increases the risk of three types of skin cancer: melanoma, basal-cell carcinoma and squamous-cell carcinoma."}, {"text": "Of greatest concern is that the melanoma risk increases in a dose-dependent manner with the number of a person\'s lifetime cumulative episodes of sunburn."}, {"list": ["tanning lamps", "welding", "ultraviolet germicidal irradiation"], "text": "Sunburn is caused by UV radiation, either from the sun or from artificial sources, such as tanning lamps, welding arcs, or ultraviolet germicidal irradiation."}, {"list": ["direct DNA damage"], "text": "It is a reaction of the body to direct DNA damage from UVB light."}, {"list": ["thymine dimer"], "text": "This damage is mainly the formation of a thymine dimer."}, {"list": ["apoptosis"], "text": "The damage is recognized by the body, which then triggers several defense mechanisms, including DNA repair to revert the damage, apoptosis and peeling to remove irreparably damaged skin cells, and increased melanin production to prevent future damage."}, {"text": "Melanin readily absorbs UV wavelength light, acting as a photoprotectant."}, {"list": ["free radicals", "indirect DNA damage"], "text": "By preventing UV photons from disrupting chemical bonds, melanin inhibits both the direct alteration of DNA and the generation of free radicals, thus indirect DNA damage."}, {"list": ["inflammation", "prostanoids", "bradykinin"], "text": "Sunburn causes an inflammation process, including production of prostanoids and bradykinin."}, {"list": ["TRPV1", "CXCL5"], "text": "These chemical compounds increase sensitivity to heat by reducing the threshold of heat receptor (TRPV1) activation from 109 °F to 85 °F. The pain may be caused by overproduction of a protein called CXCL5, which activates nerve fibres."}, {"list": ["Skin type"], "text": "Skin type determines the ease of sunburn."}, {"text": "In general, people with lighter skin tone and limited capacity to develop a tan after UVR exposure have a greater risk of sunburn."}, {"text": "The Fitzpatrick\'s Skin phototypes classification describes the normal variations of skin responses to UVR."}, {"text": "Persons with type I skin have the greatest capacity to sunburn and type VI have the least capacity to burn after exposure to UVR."}, {"text": "However, all skin types can develop sunburn."}, {"text": "Fitzpatrick\'s skin phototypes:"}, {"list": ["pharmaceutical"], "text": "The risk of a sunburn can be increased by pharmaceutical products that sensitize users to UV radiation."}, {"list": ["antibiotics", "contraceptives", "tranquillizers"], "text": "Certain antibiotics, oral contraceptives, and tranquillizers have this effect."}, {"list": ["UV Index"], "text": "The UV Index indicates the risk of getting a sunburn at a given time and location."}, {"text": "Contributing factors include:"}, {"list": ["tropic latitudes"], "text": "Because of variations in the intensity of UV radiation passing through the atmosphere, the risk of sunburn increases with proximity to the tropic latitudes, located between 23.5° north and south latitude."}, {"list": ["cloud", "ozone layer", "terrain", "polar regions"], "text": "All else being equal (e.g., cloud cover, ozone layer, terrain, etc.), over the course of a full year, each location within the tropic or polar regions receives approximately the same amount of UV radiation."}, {"list": ["temperate zones"], "text": "In the temperate zones between 23.5° and 66.5°, UV radiation varies substantially by latitude and season."}, {"text": "The higher the latitude, the lower the intensity of the UV rays."}, {"text": "Intensity in the northern hemisphere is greatest during the months of May, June and July — and in the southern hemisphere, November, December and January."}, {"text": "On a minute-by-minute basis, the amount of UV radiation is dependent on the angle of the sun."}, {"list": ["ratio", "shadow"], "text": "This is easily determined by the height ratio of any object to the size of its shadow."}, {"list": ["solar noon"], "text": "The greatest risk is at solar noon, when shadows are at their minimum and the sun\'s radiation passes most directly through the atmosphere."}, {"text": "Regardless of one\'s latitude (assuming no other variables), equal shadow lengths mean equal amounts of UV radiation."}, {"text": "The skin and eyes are most sensitive to damage by UV at 265–275 nm wavelength, which is in the lower UVC band that is almost never encountered except from artificial sources like welding arcs."}, {"text": "Most sunburn is caused by longer wavelengths, simply because those are more prevalent in sunlight at ground level."}, {"text": "In recent decades, the incidence and severity of sunburn has increased worldwide, partly because of chemical damage to the atmosphere\'s ozone layer."}, {"text": "Between the 1970s and the 2000s, average stratospheric ozone decreased by approximately 4%, contributing an approximate 4% increase to the average UV intensity at the earth\'s surface."}, {"list": ["Ozone depletion"], "text": "Ozone depletion and the seasonal \\"ozone hole\\" have led to much larger changes in some locations, especially in the southern hemisphere."}, {"list": ["Suntans"], "text": "Suntans, which naturally develop in some individuals as a protective mechanism against the sun, are viewed by most in the Western world as desirable."}, {"list": ["tanning lamps"], "text": "This has led to an overall increase in exposure to UV radiation from both the natural sun and tanning lamps."}, {"list": ["sun protection factor"], "text": "Suntans can provide a modest sun protection factor (SPF) of 3, meaning that tanned skin would tolerate up to three times the UV exposure as pale skin."}, {"text": "The differential diagnosis of sunburn includes other skin pathology induced by UV radiation including photoallergic reactions, phototoxic reactions to topical or systemic medications, and other dermatologic disorders that are aggravated by exposure to sunlight."}, {"text": "Considerations for diagnosis include duration and intensity of UV exposure, use of topical or systemic medications, history of dermatologic disease, and nutritional status."}, {"text": "The most effective way to prevent sunburn is to reduce the amount of UV radiation reaching the skin."}, {"list": ["UV Index"], "text": "The strength of sunlight is published in many locations as a UV Index."}, {"list": ["World Health Organization", "sunscreen"], "text": "The World Health Organization recommends to limit time in midday summer sun (between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m.), to watch the UV Index, to seek shade, to wear protective clothing (including a wide-brim hat), and to use sunscreen."}, {"text": "Sunlight is generally strongest when the sun is close to the highest point in the sky."}, {"text": "Due to time zones and daylight saving time, this is not necessarily at 12 noon, but often one to two hours later."}, {"text": "Commercial preparations are available that block UV light, known as sunscreens or sunblocks."}, {"text": "They have a sun protection factor (SPF) rating, based on the sunblock\'s ability to suppress sunburn: The higher the SPF rating, the lower the amount of direct DNA damage."}, {"list": ["μL"], "text": "The stated protection factors are correct only if 2 μL of sunscreen is applied per square cm of exposed skin."}, {"text": "This translates into about 28 mL (1 oz) to cover the whole body of an adult male, which is much more than many people use in practice."}, {"text": "Broad-spectrum sunscreens contain filters that protect against UVA radiation as well as UVB."}, {"list": ["skin aging"], "text": "Although UVA radiation does not primarily cause sunburn, it does contribute to skin aging and an increased risk of skin cancer."}, {"text": "Research has shown that the best sunscreen protection is achieved by application 15 to 30 minutes before exposure, followed by one reapplication 15 to 30 minutes after exposure begins."}, {"text": "Further reapplication is necessary only after activities such as swimming, sweating, and rubbing."}, {"text": "This varies based on the indications and protection shown on the label — from as little as 80 minutes in water to a few hours, depending on the product selected."}, {"text": "Sunscreen is effective and thus recommended for preventing melanoma and squamous cell carcinoma."}, {"text": "There is little evidence that it is effective in preventing basal cell carcinoma."}, {"text": "Other advice to reduce rates of skin cancer includes: avoiding sunburning, wearing protective clothing, sunglasses and hats, and attempting to avoid sun exposure or periods of peak exposure."}, {"list": ["U.S. Preventive Services Task Force"], "text": "The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommends that people between 9 and 25 years of age be advised to avoid ultraviolet light."}, {"list": ["vitamin D deficiency"], "text": "Typical use of sunscreen does not usually result in vitamin D deficiency, but extensive usage may."}, {"text": "When one is exposed to any artificial source of occupational UV, special protective clothing (for example, welding helmets/shields) should be worn."}, {"text": "Such sources can produce UVC, an extremely carcinogenic wavelength of UV which ordinarily is not present in normal sunlight, having been filtered out by the atmosphere."}, {"list": ["snow blindness"], "text": "The eyes are also sensitive to sun exposure at about the same UV wavelengths as skin; snow blindness is essentially sunburn of the cornea."}, {"list": ["sunglasses", "glasses"], "text": "Wrap-around sunglasses or the use by spectacle-wearers of glasses that block UV light reduce the harmful radiation."}, {"list": ["macular degeneration", "pterygium", "cataract"], "text": "UV light has been implicated in the development of age-related macular degeneration, pterygium and cataract."}, {"list": ["freckles"], "text": "Concentrated clusters of melanin, commonly known as freckles, are often found within the iris."}, {"text": "Dietary factors influence susceptibility to sunburn, recovery from sunburn, and risk of secondary complications from sunburn."}, {"list": ["antioxidants"], "text": "Several dietary antioxidants, including essential vitamins, have been shown to have some effectiveness for protecting against sunburn and skin damage associated with ultraviolet radiation, in both human and animal studies."}, {"list": ["Vitamin C", "Vitamin E"], "text": "Supplementation with Vitamin C and Vitamin E was shown in one study to reduce the amount of sunburn after a controlled amount of UV exposure."}, {"list": ["beta carotene"], "text": "A review of scientific literature through 2007 found that beta carotene (Vitamin A) supplementation had a protective effect against sunburn, but that the effects were only evident in the long-term, with studies of supplementation for periods less than 10 weeks in duration failing to show any effects."}, {"text": "There is also evidence that common foods may have some protective ability against sunburn if taken for a period before the exposure."}, {"list": ["exposure to the sun"], "text": "The primary measure is avoiding further exposure to the sun."}, {"text": "The best treatment for most sunburns is time."}, {"text": "Most sunburns heal completely within a few weeks."}, {"list": ["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs", "ibuprofen", "naproxen", "aspirin"], "text": "Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (such as ibuprofen or naproxen), and aspirin may decrease redness and pain."}, {"list": ["benzocaine"], "text": "Local anesthetics such as benzocaine, however, are contraindicated."}, {"list": ["hydrocortisone cream", "American Academy of Dermatology"], "text": "Schwellnus et al. states that topical steroids (such as hydrocortisone cream) do not help with sunburns, although the American Academy of Dermatology says they can be used on especially sore areas."}, {"list": ["lidocaine"], "text": "While lidocaine cream is often used as a sunburn treatment, there is little evidence for the effectiveness of such use."}, {"text": "Home treatments that may help the discomfort include using cool and wet cloths on the sunburned areas."}, {"list": ["aloe vera"], "text": "Applying soothing lotions that contain aloe vera to the sunburn areas was supported by one review."}, {"text": "Others have found aloe vera to have no effect."}, {"text": "Aloe vera has no ability to protect people from sunburns."}, {"list": ["soy"], "text": "Another treatment includes using a moisturizer that contains soy."}, {"text": "A sunburn draws fluid to the skin’s surface and away from the rest of the body."}, {"text": "Drinking extra water when you are sunburned helps prevent dehydration."}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d9/Sunburnt_woman.jpeg", "file": "File:Sunburnt woman.jpeg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Sunburnt_woman.jpeg/300px-Sunburnt_woman.jpeg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/04/Sun_Blisters.jpg", "file": "File:Sun Blisters.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Sun_Blisters.jpg/300px-Sun_Blisters.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3b/Direct_DNA_damage.png", "file": "File:direct DNA damage.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Direct_DNA_damage.png/300px-Direct_DNA_damage.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1b/Erythemal_action_spectrum.svg", "file": "File:Erythemal action spectrum.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Erythemal_action_spectrum.svg/300px-Erythemal_action_spectrum.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c8/Sun_burn.JPG", "file": "File:Sun burn.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Sun_burn.JPG/300px-Sun_burn.JPG"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(31, 'syphilis', 'Syphilis', 'Electron%20micrograph%20of%20Treponema%20pallidum', 'Infectious%20disease', '["Firm", "painless", "non-itchy skin ulcer"]', '{"desc": "Blood tests", "list": ["Blood tests"]}', '{"desc": "Treponema pallidum usually spread by sex"}', '[{"list": ["sexually transmitted infection", "bacterium", "Treponema pallidum\'\'"], "text": "Syphilis is a sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum subspecies pallidum."}, {"text": "The signs and symptoms of syphilis vary depending in which of the four stages it presents (primary, secondary, latent, and tertiary)."}, {"list": ["chancre", "skin ulceration"], "text": "The primary stage classically presents with a single chancre (a firm, painless, non-itchy skin ulceration) but there may be multiple sores."}, {"text": "In secondary syphilis a diffuse rash occurs, which frequently involves the palms of the hands and soles of the feet."}, {"text": "There may also be sores in the mouth or vagina."}, {"text": "In latent syphilis, which can last for years, there are few or no symptoms."}, {"list": ["gummas"], "text": "In tertiary syphilis there are gummas (soft non-cancerous growths), neurological, or heart symptoms."}, {"list": ["the great imitator"], "text": "Syphilis has been known as \\"the great imitator\\" as it may cause symptoms similar to many other diseases."}, {"list": ["sexual activity"], "text": "Syphilis is most commonly spread through sexual activity."}, {"list": ["congenital syphilis"], "text": "It may also be transmitted from mother to baby during pregnancy or at birth, resulting in congenital syphilis."}, {"list": ["yaws", "pinta", "bejel"], "text": "Other human diseases caused by related Treponema pallidum subspecies include yaws (subspecies pertenue), pinta (subspecies carateum), and bejel (subspecies endemicum)."}, {"list": ["blood tests", "dark field microscopy"], "text": "Diagnosis is usually made by using blood tests; the bacteria can also be detected using dark field microscopy."}, {"list": ["Center for Disease Control"], "text": "The Center for Disease Control recommends all pregnant women be tested."}, {"list": ["latex condom"], "text": "The risk of sexual transmission of syphilis can be reduced by using a latex condom."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Syphilis can be effectively treated with antibiotics."}, {"list": ["benzathine benzylpenicillin", "injected into a muscle"], "text": "The preferred antibiotic for most cases is benzathine benzylpenicillin injected into a muscle."}, {"list": ["penicillin allergy", "doxycycline", "tetracycline"], "text": "In those who have a severe penicillin allergy, doxycycline or tetracycline may be used."}, {"list": ["neurosyphilis", "intravenous", "benzylpenicillin", "ceftriaxone"], "text": "In those with neurosyphilis, intravenous benzylpenicillin or ceftriaxone is recommended."}, {"list": ["muscle pains", "Jarisch-Herxheimer"], "text": "During treatment people may develop fever, headache, and muscle pains, a reaction known as Jarisch-Herxheimer."}, {"text": "In 2015, about 45.4 million people were infected with syphilis, with 6 million new cases."}, {"text": "During 2015, it caused about 107,000 deaths, down from 202,000 in 1990."}, {"list": ["human immunodeficiency virus"], "text": "After decreasing dramatically with the availability of penicillin in the 1940s, rates of infection have increased since the turn of the millennium in many countries, often in combination with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)."}, {"list": ["promiscuity", "prostitution", "men who have sex with men"], "text": "This is believed to be partly due to increased promiscuity, prostitution, decreasing use of condoms, and unsafe sexual practices among men who have sex with men."}, {"list": ["Cuba"], "text": "In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eliminate mother-to-child transmission of syphilis."}, {"list": ["congenitally"], "text": "Syphilis can present in one of four different stages: primary, secondary, latent, and tertiary, and may also occur congenitally."}, {"list": ["Sir William Osler"], "text": "It was referred to as \\"the great imitator\\" by Sir William Osler due to its varied presentations."}, {"text": "Primary syphilis is typically acquired by direct sexual contact with the infectious lesions of another person."}, {"list": ["chancre"], "text": "Approximately 3 to 90 days after the initial exposure (average 21 days) a skin lesion, called a chancre, appears at the point of contact.<!-- --> This is classically (40% of the time) a single, firm, painless, non-itchy skin ulceration with a clean base and sharp borders 0.3–3.0 cm in size."}, {"list": ["macule", "papule", "erosion", "ulcer"], "text": "The lesion may take on almost any form.<!-- --> In the classic form, it evolves from a macule to a papule and finally to an erosion or ulcer."}, {"text": "Occasionally, multiple lesions may be present (~40%), with multiple lesions more common when coinfected with HIV."}, {"text": "Lesions may be painful or tender (30%), and they may occur in places other than the genitals (2–7%)."}, {"list": ["cervix", "penis", "anally", "rectally", "men who have sex with men"], "text": "The most common location in women is the cervix (44%), the penis in heterosexual men (99%), and anally and rectally relatively commonly in men who have sex with men (34%)."}, {"list": ["Lymph node"], "text": "Lymph node enlargement frequently (80%) occurs around the area of infection, occurring seven to 10 days after chancre formation."}, {"list": ["lesion"], "text": "The lesion may persist for three to six weeks without treatment."}, {"text": "Secondary syphilis occurs approximately four to ten weeks after the primary infection."}, {"list": ["mucous membranes", "lymph nodes"], "text": "While secondary disease is known for the many different ways it can manifest, symptoms most commonly involve the skin, mucous membranes, and lymph nodes."}, {"text": "There may be a symmetrical, reddish-pink, non-itchy rash on the trunk and extremities, including the palms and soles."}, {"list": ["maculopapular", "pustular"], "text": "The rash may become maculopapular or pustular."}, {"list": ["condyloma latum", "mucous membranes"], "text": "It may form flat, broad, whitish, wart-like lesions known as condyloma latum on mucous membranes."}, {"text": "All of these lesions harbor bacteria and are infectious."}, {"list": ["fever", "sore throat", "malaise", "weight loss", "hair loss", "headache"], "text": "Other symptoms may include fever, sore throat, malaise, weight loss, hair loss, and headache."}, {"list": ["liver inflammation", "kidney", "joint inflammation", "periostitis", "inflammation of the optic nerve", "uveitis", "interstitial keratitis"], "text": "Rare manifestations include liver inflammation, kidney disease, joint inflammation, periostitis, inflammation of the optic nerve, uveitis, and interstitial keratitis."}, {"text": "The acute symptoms usually resolve after three to six weeks; about 25% of people may present with a recurrence of secondary symptoms."}, {"text": "Many people who present with secondary syphilis (40–85% of women, 20–65% of men) do not report previously having had the classic chancre of primary syphilis."}, {"list": ["serologic"], "text": "Latent syphilis is defined as having serologic proof of infection without symptoms of disease."}, {"text": "It is further described as either early (less than 1 year after secondary syphilis) or late (more than 1 year after secondary syphilis) in the United States."}, {"text": "The United Kingdom uses a cut-off of two years for early and late latent syphilis."}, {"text": "Early latent syphilis may have a relapse of symptoms."}, {"list": ["asymptomatic"], "text": "Late latent syphilis is asymptomatic, and not as contagious as early latent syphilis."}, {"list": ["neurosyphilis"], "text": "Tertiary syphilis may occur approximately 3 to 15 years after the initial infection, and may be divided into three different forms: gummatous syphilis (15%), late neurosyphilis (6.5%), and cardiovascular syphilis (10%)."}, {"text": "Without treatment, a third of infected people develop tertiary disease."}, {"text": "People with tertiary syphilis are not infectious."}, {"list": ["benign"], "text": "Gummatous syphilis or late benign syphilis usually occurs 1 to 46 years after the initial infection, with an average of 15 years."}, {"list": ["gummas"], "text": "This stage is characterized by the formation of chronic gummas, which are soft, tumor-like balls of inflammation which may vary considerably in size."}, {"text": "They typically affect the skin, bone, and liver, but can occur anywhere."}, {"list": ["Neurosyphilis", "central nervous system"], "text": "Neurosyphilis refers to an infection involving the central nervous system."}, {"list": ["meningitis", "general paresis", "tabes dorsalis"], "text": "It may occur early, being either asymptomatic or in the form of syphilitic meningitis, or late as meningovascular syphilis, general paresis, or tabes dorsalis, which is associated with poor balance and lightning pains in the lower extremities."}, {"text": "Late neurosyphilis typically occurs 4 to 25 years after the initial infection."}, {"list": ["seizure", "dementia", "tabes dorsalis"], "text": "Meningovascular syphilis typically presents with apathy and seizure, and general paresis with dementia and tabes dorsalis."}, {"list": ["Argyll Robertson pupils"], "text": "Also, there may be Argyll Robertson pupils, which are bilateral small pupils that constrict when the person focuses on near objects but do not constrict when exposed to bright light."}, {"text": "Cardiovascular syphilis usually occurs 10–30 years after the initial infection."}, {"list": ["syphilitic aortitis", "aneurysm"], "text": "The most common complication is syphilitic aortitis, which may result in aneurysm formation."}, {"list": ["Congenital syphilis"], "text": "Congenital syphilis is that which is transmitted during pregnancy or during birth."}, {"text": "Two-thirds of syphilitic infants are born without symptoms."}, {"list": ["enlargement of the liver and spleen", "lung inflammation"], "text": "Common symptoms that develop over the first couple of years of life include enlargement of the liver and spleen (70%), rash (70%), fever (40%), neurosyphilis (20%), and lung inflammation (20%)."}, {"list": ["late congenital syphilis", "saddle nose", "Higoumenakis sign", "saber shin", "Clutton\'s joints"], "text": "If untreated, late congenital syphilis may occur in 40%, including saddle nose deformation, Higoumenakis sign, saber shin, or Clutton\'s joints among others."}, {"list": ["miscarriage"], "text": "Infection during pregnancy is also associated with miscarriage."}, {"list": ["Gram-negative"], "text": "Treponema pallidum subspecies pallidum is a spiral-shaped, Gram-negative, highly mobile bacterium."}, {"list": ["yaws", "pinta", "bejel"], "text": "Three other human diseases are caused by related Treponema pallidum subspecies, including yaws (subspecies pertenue), pinta (subspecies carateum) and bejel (subspecies endemicum)."}, {"text": "Unlike subtype pallidum, they do not cause neurological disease."}, {"list": ["natural reservoir"], "text": "Humans are the only known natural reservoir for subspecies pallidum."}, {"text": "It is unable to survive more than a few days without a host."}, {"list": ["Mbp"], "text": "This is due to its small genome (1.14 Mbp) failing to encode the metabolic pathways necessary to make most of its macronutrients."}, {"text": "It has a slow doubling time of greater than 30 hours."}, {"list": ["pregnancy", "fetus"], "text": "Syphilis is transmitted primarily by sexual contact or during pregnancy from a mother to her fetus; the spirochete is able to pass through intact mucous membranes or compromised skin."}, {"list": ["kissing"], "text": "It is thus transmissible by kissing near a lesion, as well as oral, vaginal, and anal sex."}, {"text": "Approximately 30% to 60% of those exposed to primary or secondary syphilis will get the disease."}, {"text": "Its infectivity is exemplified by the fact that an individual inoculated with only 57 organisms has a 50% chance of being infected."}, {"text": "Most (60%) of new cases in the United States occur in men who have sex with men."}, {"list": ["blood products"], "text": "Syphilis can be transmitted by blood products, but the risk is low due to blood testing in many countries."}, {"list": ["sharing needles"], "text": "The risk of transmission from sharing needles appears limited."}, {"text": "It is not generally possible to contract syphilis through toilet seats, daily activities, hot tubs, or sharing eating utensils or clothing."}, {"list": ["objects"], "text": "This is mainly because the bacteria die very quickly outside of the body, making transmission by objects extremely difficult."}, {"text": "Syphilis is difficult to diagnose clinically early in its presentation."}, {"list": ["blood tests", "microscopy"], "text": "Confirmation is either via blood tests or direct visual inspection using microscopy."}, {"text": "Blood tests are more commonly used, as they are easier to perform."}, {"text": "Diagnostic tests are unable to distinguish between the stages of the disease."}, {"list": ["nontreponemal"], "text": "Blood tests are divided into nontreponemal and treponemal tests."}, {"list": ["venereal disease research laboratory", "rapid plasma reagin"], "text": "Nontreponemal tests are used initially, and include venereal disease research laboratory (VDRL) and rapid plasma reagin (RPR) tests."}, {"list": ["False positives", "varicella", "measles"], "text": "False positives on the nontreponemal tests can occur with some viral infections, such as varicella (chickenpox) and measles."}, {"list": ["lymphoma", "tuberculosis", "malaria", "endocarditis", "connective tissue disease", "pregnancy"], "text": "False positives can also occur with lymphoma, tuberculosis, malaria, endocarditis, connective tissue disease, and pregnancy."}, {"list": ["treponemal pallidum particle agglutination", "fluorescent treponemal antibody absorption test"], "text": "Because of the possibility of false positives with nontreponemal tests, confirmation is required with a treponemal test, such as treponemal pallidum particle agglutination (TPHA) or fluorescent treponemal antibody absorption test (FTA-Abs)."}, {"text": "Treponemal antibody tests usually become positive two to five weeks after the initial infection."}, {"list": ["leukocytes", "lymphocytes", "cerebrospinal fluid"], "text": "Neurosyphilis is diagnosed by finding high numbers of leukocytes (predominately lymphocytes) and high protein levels in the cerebrospinal fluid in the setting of a known syphilis infection."}, {"list": ["Dark ground microscopy", "serous fluid"], "text": "Dark ground microscopy of serous fluid from a chancre may be used to make an immediate diagnosis."}, {"text": "Hospitals do not always have equipment or experienced staff members, and testing must be done within 10 minutes of acquiring the sample."}, {"list": ["Sensitivity"], "text": "Sensitivity has been reported to be nearly 80%; therefore the test can only be used to confirm a diagnosis, but not to rule one out."}, {"list": ["direct fluorescent antibody", "nucleic acid amplification"], "text": "Two other tests can be carried out on a sample from the chancre: direct fluorescent antibody testing and nucleic acid amplification tests."}, {"list": ["antibodies", "fluorescein", "polymerase chain reaction"], "text": "Direct fluorescent testing uses antibodies tagged with fluorescein, which attach to specific syphilis proteins, while nucleic acid amplification uses techniques, such as the polymerase chain reaction, to detect the presence of specific syphilis genes."}, {"text": "These tests are not as time-sensitive, as they do not require living bacteria to make the diagnosis."}, {"text": ", there is no vaccine effective for prevention."}, {"text": "Several vaccines based on treponemal proteins reduce lesion development in an animal model and research continues."}, {"list": ["Condom"], "text": "Condom use reduces the likelihood of transmission during sex, but does not completely eliminate the risk."}, {"list": ["Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"], "text": "The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) states, \\"Correct and consistent use of latex condoms can reduce the risk of syphilis only when the infected area or site of potential exposure is protected. However, a syphilis sore outside of the area covered by a latex condom can still allow transmission, so caution should be exercised even when using a condom.\\""}, {"text": "Abstinence from intimate physical contact with an infected person is effective at reducing the transmission of syphilis."}, {"text": "The CDC states, \\"The surest way to avoid transmission of sexually transmitted diseases, including syphilis, is to abstain from sexual contact or to be in a long-term mutually monogamous relationship with a partner who has been tested and is known to be uninfected.\\""}, {"text": "Congenital syphilis in the newborn can be prevented by screening mothers during early pregnancy and treating those who are infected."}, {"list": ["United States Preventive Services Task Force", "World Health Organization", "third trimester"], "text": "The United States Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) strongly recommends universal screening of all pregnant women, while the World Health Organization recommends all women be tested at their first antenatal visit and again in the third trimester.<!-- --> If they are positive, it is recommend their partners also be treated."}, {"list": ["antenatal care"], "text": "Congenital syphilis is still common in the developing world, as many women do not receive antenatal care at all, and the antenatal care others receive does not include screening.<!-- --> It still occasionally occurs in the developed world, as those most likely to acquire syphilis (through drug use, etc.) are least likely to receive care during pregnancy."}, {"text": "Several measures to increase access to testing appear effective at reducing rates of congenital syphilis in low- to middle-income countries."}, {"text": "Point-of-care testing to detect syphilis appeared to be good although more research is needed to assess its effectiveness and into improving outcomes in mothers and babies."}, {"text": "The CDC recommends that sexually active men who have sex with men be tested at least yearly."}, {"list": ["USPSTF"], "text": "The USPSTF also recommends screening among those at high risk."}, {"list": ["notifiable disease", "European Union"], "text": "Syphilis is a notifiable disease in many countries, including Canada the European Union, and the United States."}, {"list": ["public health", "partner notification"], "text": "This means health care providers are required to notify public health authorities, which will then ideally provide partner notification to the person\'s partners."}, {"text": "Physicians may also encourage patients to send their partners to seek care."}, {"list": ["STI"], "text": "Several strategies have been found to improve follow-up for STI testing, including email and text messaging as reminders of appointments."}, {"list": ["benzathine benzylpenicillin"], "text": "The first-choice treatment for uncomplicated syphilis remains a single dose of intramuscular benzathine benzylpenicillin."}, {"list": ["Doxycycline", "tetracycline"], "text": "Doxycycline and tetracycline are alternative choices for those allergic to penicillin; due to the risk of birth defects, these are not recommended for pregnant women."}, {"list": ["Resistance", "macrolides", "rifampicin", "clindamycin"], "text": "Resistance to macrolides, rifampicin, and clindamycin is often present."}, {"list": ["Ceftriaxone", "cephalosporin", "antibiotic"], "text": "Ceftriaxone, a third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic, may be as effective as penicillin-based treatment."}, {"text": "It is recommended that a treated person avoid sex until the sores are healed."}, {"list": ["central nervous system"], "text": "For neurosyphilis, due to the poor penetration of benzylpenicillin into the central nervous system, those affected are recommended to be given large doses of intravenous penicillin for a minimum of 10 days."}, {"text": "If a person is allergic, ceftriaxone may be used or penicillin desensitization attempted."}, {"text": "Other late presentations may be treated with once-weekly intramuscular benzylpenicillin for three weeks."}, {"text": "If allergic, as in the case of early disease, doxycycline or tetracycline may be used, albeit for a longer duration."}, {"text": "Treatment at this stage limits further progression but has only slight effect on damage which has already occurred."}, {"list": ["Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction"], "text": "One of the potential side effects of treatment is the Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction."}, {"list": ["fast heart rate"], "text": "It frequently starts within one hour and lasts for 24 hours, with symptoms of fever, muscle pains, headache, and a fast heart rate."}, {"list": ["cytokines"], "text": "It is caused by cytokines released by the immune system in response to lipoproteins released from rupturing syphilis bacteria."}, {"text": "Penicillin is an effective treatment for syphilis in pregnancy but there is no agreement on which dose or way of giving it is most effective."}, {"text": "More research is needed into how much antibiotic to give and when to give it."}, {"list": ["Age-standardized", "disability adjusted life years", "developing world", "spontaneous abortions", "stillbirths", "sub-Saharan Africa", "perinatal deaths", "intravenous drug users", "HIV", "African Americans", "antibiotics", "virulence"], "text": "Syphilis world map-Deaths per million persons-WHO2012.svg disability adjusted life years from syphilis per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004 In 2012, about 0.5% of adults were infected with syphilis, with 6 million new cases. In 1999 it is believed to have infected 12 million additional people, with greater than 90% of cases in the developing world. It affects between 700,000 and 1.6 million pregnancies a year, resulting in spontaneous abortions, stillbirths, and congenital syphilis. During 2010, it caused about 113,000 deaths, down from 202,000 in 1990. In sub-Saharan Africa, syphilis contributes to approximately 20% of perinatal deaths. Rates are proportionally higher among intravenous drug users, those who are infected with HIV, and men who have sex with men.  In the United States, rates of syphilis as of 2007 were six times greater in men than women; they were nearly equal in 1997. African Americans accounted for almost half of all cases in 2010. As of 2014, syphilis infections continue to increase in the United States. Syphilis was very common in Europe during the 18th and 19th centuries. Flaubert found it universal among nineteenth-century Egyptian prostitutes. In the developed world during the early 20th century, infections declined rapidly with the widespread use of antibiotics, until the 1980s and 1990s. Since 2000, rates of syphilis have been increasing in the USA, Canada, the UK, Australia and Europe, primarily among men who have sex with men. Rates of syphilis among American women have remained stable during this time, while rates among UK women have increased, but at a rate less than that of men. Increased rates among heterosexuals have occurred in China and Russia since the 1990s. This has been attributed to unsafe sexual practices, such as sexual promiscuity, prostitution, and decreasing use of barrier protection.  Untreated, it has a mortality rate of 8% to 58%, with a greater death rate in males. The symptoms of syphilis have become less severe over the 19th and 20th centuries, in part due to widespread availability of effective treatment, and partly due to virulence of the spirochaete. With early treatment, few complications result. Syphilis increases the risk of HIV transmission by two to five times, and coinfection is common (30–60% in some urban centers).  In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother to child transmission of syphilis."}, {"text": "The exact origin of syphilis is disputed."}, {"list": ["Christopher Columbus\'s", "Americas"], "text": "Syphilis was definitely present in the Americas before European contact, and it may have been carried from the Americas to Europe by the returning crewmen from Christopher Columbus\'s voyage to the Americas; or it may have existed in Europe previously, but went unrecognized until shortly after Columbus returned."}, {"text": "These are referred to as the Columbian and pre-Columbian hypotheses, respectively."}, {"text": "The Columbian hypothesis is best supported by the available evidence."}, {"list": ["Naples, Italy", "Italian War of 1494–98"], "text": "The first written records of an outbreak of syphilis in Europe occurred in 1494 or 1495 in Naples, Italy, during a French invasion (Italian War of 1494–98)."}, {"text": "As it was claimed to have been spread by French troops, it was initially known as the \\"French disease\\" by the people of Naples."}, {"list": ["Girolamo Fracastoro", "Latin", "dactylic hexameter"], "text": "In 1530, the pastoral name \\"syphilis\\" (the name of a character) was first used by the Italian physician and poet Girolamo Fracastoro as the title of his Latin poem in dactylic hexameter describing the ravages of the disease in Italy."}, {"text": "It was also known historically as the \\"Great Pox\\"."}, {"list": ["Fritz Schaudinn", "Erich Hoffmann"], "text": "The causative organism, Treponema pallidum, was first identified by Fritz Schaudinn and Erich Hoffmann in 1905."}, {"list": ["Salvarsan", "Paul Ehrlich"], "text": "The first effective treatment for syphilis was Salvarsan, developed in 1910 by Paul Ehrlich."}, {"list": ["penicillin"], "text": "The effectiveness of treatment with penicillin was confirmed in trials in 1943."}, {"list": ["mercury"], "text": "Before the discovery and use of antibiotics in the mid-twentieth century, mercury and isolation were commonly used, with treatments often worse than the disease."}, {"list": ["Franz Schubert", "Arthur Schopenhauer", "Édouard Manet", "Charles Baudelaire", "Guy de Maupassant"], "text": "Many famous historical figures, including Franz Schubert, Arthur Schopenhauer, Édouard Manet, Charles Baudelaire, and Guy de Maupassant are believed to have had the disease."}, {"list": ["Friedrich Nietzsche", "tertiary syphilis"], "text": "Friedrich Nietzsche was long believed to have gone mad as a result of tertiary syphilis, but that diagnosis has recently come into question."}, {"list": ["Albrecht Dürer\'s", "Landsknecht", "mercenary"], "text": "The earliest known depiction of an individual with syphilis is Albrecht Dürer\'s Syphilitic Man, a woodcut believed to represent a Landsknecht, a Northern European mercenary."}, {"list": ["femme fatale\'\'", "John Keats\'", "La Belle Dame sans Merci\'\'"], "text": "The myth of the femme fatale or \\"poison women\\" of the 19th century is believed to be partly derived from the devastation of syphilis, with classic examples in literature including John Keats\' La Belle Dame sans Merci."}, {"list": ["Jan van der Straet", "guaiacum"], "text": "The artist Jan van der Straet painted a scene of a wealthy man receiving treatment for syphilis with the tropical wood guaiacum sometime around 1580."}, {"text": "The title of the work is \\"Preparation and Use of Guayaco for Treating Syphilis\\"."}, {"text": "That the artist chose to include this image in a series of works celebrating the New World indicates how important a treatment, however ineffective, for syphilis was to the European elite at that time."}, {"text": "The richly colored and detailed work depicts four servants preparing the concoction while a physician looks on, hiding something behind his back while the hapless patient drinks."}, {"list": ["medical ethics", "Tuskegee syphilis study"], "text": "One of the most infamous United States cases of questionable medical ethics in the 20th century was the Tuskegee syphilis study."}, {"list": ["Tuskegee, Alabama", "U.S. Public Health Service", "Tuskegee Institute"], "text": "The study took place in Tuskegee, Alabama, and was supported by the U.S. Public Health Service (PHS) in partnership with the Tuskegee Institute."}, {"text": "The study began in 1932, when syphilis was a widespread problem and there was no safe and effective treatment."}, {"text": "The study was designed to measure the progression of untreated syphilis."}, {"text": "By 1947, penicillin had been shown to be an effective cure for early syphilis and was becoming widely used to treat the disease."}, {"text": "Its use in later syphilis was still unclear."}, {"text": "Study directors continued the study and did not offer the participants treatment with penicillin."}, {"text": "This is debated, and some have found that penicillin was given to many of the subjects."}, {"list": ["Peter Buxtun"], "text": "In the 1960s, Peter Buxtun sent a letter to the CDC, who controlled the study, expressing concern about the ethics of letting hundreds of black men die of a disease that could be cured."}, {"text": "The CDC asserted that it needed to continue the study until all of the men had died."}, {"text": "In 1972, Buxton went to the mainstream press, causing a public outcry."}, {"text": "As a result, the program was terminated, the U.S. Government settled a class action lawsuit on behalf of study participants and their descendants in the amount of $10 million ($ in ) and agreed to provide free medical treatment to surviving participants and to surviving family members infected as a consequence of the study, and Congress created a commission empowered to write regulations to deter such abuses from occurring in the future."}, {"text": "On 16 May 1997, thanks to the efforts of the Tuskegee Syphilis Study Legacy Committee formed in 1994, survivors of the study were invited to the White House to be present when President Bill Clinton apologized on behalf of the United States government for the study."}, {"list": ["Guatemala"], "text": "Syphilis experiments were also carried out in Guatemala from 1946 to 1948."}, {"list": ["United States", "human experiments", "Juan José Arévalo"], "text": "They were United States-sponsored human experiments, conducted during the government of Juan José Arévalo with the cooperation of some Guatemalan health ministries and officials."}, {"list": ["mental patients", "sexually transmitted diseases", "informed consent", "antibiotics"], "text": "Doctors infected soldiers, prisoners, and mental patients with syphilis and other sexually transmitted diseases, without the informed consent of the subjects, and then treated them with antibiotics."}, {"text": "In October 2010, the U.S. formally apologized to Guatemala for conducting these experiments."}]', '{"list": ["Condoms", " not having sex"], "conditions": ["Condoms"]}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/29/Treponema_pallidum.jpg", "file": "File:Treponema pallidum.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Treponema_pallidum.jpg/300px-Treponema_pallidum.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/36/Syphilis.webm", "file": "File:Syphilis.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Syphilis.webm/300px-Syphilis.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/06/Chancres_on_the_penile_shaft_due_to_a_primary_syphilitic_infection_caused_by_Treponema_pallidum_6803_lores.jpg", "file": "Image:Chancres on the penile shaft due to a primary syphilitic infection caused by Treponema pallidum 6803 lores.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Chancres_on_the_penile_shaft_due_to_a_primary_syphilitic_infection_caused_by_Treponema_pallidum_6803_lores.jpg/300px-Chancres_on_the_penile_shaft_due_to_a_primary_syphilitic_infection_caused_by_Treponema_pallidum_6803_lores.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bd/Secondary_Syphilis_on_palms_CDC_6809_lores.rsh.jpg", "file": "Image:Secondary Syphilis on palms CDC 6809 lores.rsh.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Secondary_Syphilis_on_palms_CDC_6809_lores.rsh.jpg/300px-Secondary_Syphilis_on_palms_CDC_6809_lores.rsh.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/eb/2ndsyphil2.jpg", "file": "image:2ndsyphil2.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/2ndsyphil2.jpg/300px-2ndsyphil2.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/73/Tertiary_syphilis_head.JPG", "file": "File:Tertiary syphilis head.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Tertiary_syphilis_head.JPG/300px-Tertiary_syphilis_head.JPG"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/91/Treponema_pallidum_01.png", "file": "File:Treponema pallidum 01.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Treponema_pallidum_01.png/300px-Treponema_pallidum_01.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5b/Syphilis_false_shame_and_fear_may_destroy_your_future.png", "file": "File:Syphilis false shame and fear may destroy your future.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Syphilis_false_shame_and_fear_may_destroy_your_future.png/300px-Syphilis_false_shame_and_fear_may_destroy_your_future.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f6/Portrait_of_Mr._J._Kay%2C_afflicted_with_a_rodent_disease._Unknown_artist%2C_c._1820_CE._The_Wellcome_Collection%2C_London.jpg", "file": "File:Portrait of Mr. J. Kay, afflicted with a rodent disease. Unknown artist, c. 1820 CE. The Wellcome Collection, London.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Portrait_of_Mr._J._Kay%2C_afflicted_with_a_rodent_disease._Unknown_artist%2C_c._1820_CE._The_Wellcome_Collection%2C_London.jpg/300px-Portrait_of_Mr._J._Kay%2C_afflicted_with_a_rodent_disease._Unknown_artist%2C_c._1820_CE._The_Wellcome_Collection%2C_London.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/42/Rembrandt_Harmensz._van_Rijn_095.jpg", "file": "Image:Rembrandt Harmensz. van Rijn 095.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Rembrandt_Harmensz._van_Rijn_095.jpg/300px-Rembrandt_Harmensz._van_Rijn_095.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b1/400Behandlung_der_Syphilis.jpg", "file": "File:400Behandlung der Syphilis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/400Behandlung_der_Syphilis.jpg/300px-400Behandlung_der_Syphilis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/82/Stop_syphilis_LCCN98509573.jpg", "file": "File:Stop syphilis LCCN98509573.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Stop_syphilis_LCCN98509573.jpg/300px-Stop_syphilis_LCCN98509573.jpg"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(32, 'tuberculosis', 'Tuberculosis', 'Chest%20X-ray%20of%20a%20person%20with%20advanced%20tuberculosis%3A%20Infection%20in%20both%20lungs%20is%20marked%20by%20white%20arrow-heads%2C%20and%20the%20formation%20of%20a%20cavity%20is%20marked%20by%20black%20arrows.', 'Infectious%20disease%2C%20pulmonology', '["Chronic cough", "fever", "blood in the sputum", "weight loss"]', '{"desc": "CXR, culture, tuberculin skin test", "list": ["CXR", "culture", "tuberculin skin test"]}', '{"desc": "Mycobacterium tuberculosis", "list": ["Mycobacterium tuberculosis\'\'"]}', '[{"list": ["infectious disease", "Mycobacterium tuberculosis\'\'"], "text": "Tuberculosis (TB) is an infectious disease usually caused by the bacterium Mycobacterium tuberculosis (MTB)."}, {"list": ["lungs"], "text": "Tuberculosis generally affects the lungs, but can also affect other parts of the body."}, {"list": ["latent tuberculosis"], "text": "Most infections do not have symptoms, in which case it is known as latent tuberculosis."}, {"text": "About 10% of latent infections progress to active disease which, if left untreated, kills about half of those infected."}, {"list": ["cough", "blood-containing", "sputum", "fever", "night sweats", "weight loss"], "text": "The classic symptoms of active TB are a chronic cough with blood-containing sputum, fever, night sweats, and weight loss."}, {"text": "The historical term \\"consumption\\" came about due to the weight loss."}, {"list": ["Infection"], "text": "Infection of other organs can cause a wide range of symptoms."}, {"list": ["spread through the air", "cough", "sneeze"], "text": "Tuberculosis is spread through the air when people who have active TB in their lungs cough, spit, speak, or sneeze."}, {"text": "People with latent TB do not spread the disease."}, {"list": ["HIV/AIDS", "smoke"], "text": "Active infection occurs more often in people with HIV/AIDS and in those who smoke."}, {"list": ["Diagnosis", "chest X-rays", "microscopic", "culture"], "text": "Diagnosis of active TB is based on chest X-rays, as well as microscopic examination and culture of body fluids."}, {"list": ["tuberculin skin test"], "text": "Diagnosis of latent TB relies on the tuberculin skin test (TST) or blood tests."}, {"list": ["vaccination", "bacillus Calmette-Guérin"], "text": "Prevention of TB involves screening those at high risk, early detection and treatment of cases, and vaccination with the bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG) vaccine."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Those at high risk include household, workplace, and social contacts of people with active TB. Treatment requires the use of multiple antibiotics over a long period of time."}, {"list": ["Antibiotic resistance", "multiple drug-resistant tuberculosis", "extensively drug-resistant tuberculosis"], "text": "Antibiotic resistance is a growing problem with increasing rates of multiple drug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB) and extensively drug-resistant tuberculosis (XDR-TB)."}, {"text": "One-third of the world\'s population is thought to be infected with TB. New infections occur in about 1% of the population each year."}, {"text": "In 2016, there were more than 10 million cases of active TB which resulted in 1.3 million deaths."}, {"text": "This makes it the number one cause of death from an infectious disease."}, {"list": ["developing countries"], "text": "More than 95% of deaths occurred in developing countries, and more than 50% in India, China, Indonesia, Pakistan, and the Philippines."}, {"text": "The number of new cases each year has decreased since 2000."}, {"text": "About 80% of people in many Asian and African countries test positive while 5–10% of people in the United States population test positive by the tuberculin test."}, {"list": ["ancient times"], "text": "Tuberculosis has been present in humans since ancient times."}, {"list": ["lungs"], "text": "Tuberculosis may infect any part of the body, but most commonly occurs in the lungs (known as pulmonary tuberculosis)."}, {"list": ["fever", "chills", "night sweats", "loss of appetite", "weight loss", "fatigue"], "text": "Extrapulmonary TB occurs when tuberculosis develops outside of the lungs, although extrapulmonary TB may coexist with pulmonary TB. General signs and symptoms include fever, chills, night sweats, loss of appetite, weight loss, and fatigue."}, {"list": ["nail clubbing"], "text": "Significant nail clubbing may also occur."}, {"text": "If a tuberculosis infection does become active, it most commonly involves the lungs (in about 90% of cases)."}, {"list": ["chest pain"], "text": "Symptoms may include chest pain and a prolonged cough producing sputum.<!"}, {"text": "--> About 25% of people may not have any symptoms (i.e. they remain \\"asymptomatic\\")."}, {"list": ["cough up blood", "pulmonary artery", "Rasmussen\'s aneurysm"], "text": "Occasionally, people may cough up blood in small amounts, and in very rare cases, the infection may erode into the pulmonary artery or a Rasmussen\'s aneurysm, resulting in massive bleeding."}, {"text": "Tuberculosis may become a chronic illness and cause extensive scarring in the upper lobes of the lungs.<!-- --> The upper lung lobes are more frequently affected by tuberculosis than the lower ones."}, {"text": "The reason for this difference is not clear."}, {"list": ["lymph"], "text": "It may be due to either better air flow, or poor lymph drainage within the upper lungs."}, {"text": "In 15–20% of active cases, the infection spreads outside the lungs, causing other kinds of TB. These are collectively denoted as \\"extrapulmonary tuberculosis\\"."}, {"list": ["weakened immune system"], "text": "Extrapulmonary TB occurs more commonly in people with a weakened immune system and young children."}, {"text": "In those with HIV, this occurs in more than 50% of cases."}, {"list": ["pleura", "central nervous system", "meningitis", "lymphatic system", "scrofula", "genitourinary system", "urogenital tuberculosis", "Pott disease"], "text": "Notable extrapulmonary infection sites include the pleura (in tuberculous pleurisy), the central nervous system (in tuberculous meningitis), the lymphatic system (in scrofula of the neck), the genitourinary system (in urogenital tuberculosis), and the bones and joints (in Pott disease of the spine), among others."}, {"list": ["miliary tuberculosis"], "text": "A potentially more serious, widespread form of TB is called \\"disseminated tuberculosis\\", also known as miliary tuberculosis."}, {"text": "Miliary TB currently makes up about 10% of extrapulmonary cases."}, {"list": ["Mycobacterium tuberculosis\'\'", "aerobic", "bacillus"], "text": "The main cause of TB is Mycobacterium tuberculosis (MTB), a small, aerobic, nonmotile bacillus."}, {"list": ["lipid", "pathogen"], "text": "The high lipid content of this pathogen accounts for many of its unique clinical characteristics."}, {"list": ["divides"], "text": "It divides every 16 to 20 hours, which is an extremely slow rate compared with other bacteria, which usually divide in less than an hour."}, {"list": ["outer membrane"], "text": "Mycobacteria have an outer membrane lipid bilayer."}, {"list": ["Gram stain", "mycolic acid"], "text": "If a Gram stain is performed, MTB either stains very weakly \\"Gram-positive\\" or does not retain dye as a result of the high lipid and mycolic acid content of its cell wall."}, {"list": ["disinfectants", "dry state"], "text": "MTB can withstand weak disinfectants and survive in a dry state for weeks."}, {"list": ["host"], "text": "In nature, the bacterium can grow only within the cells of a host organism, but \'\'M."}, {"list": ["in the laboratory"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\' can be cultured in the laboratory."}, {"list": ["histological", "expectorated", "phlegm"], "text": "Using histological stains on expectorated samples from phlegm (also called \\"sputum\\"), scientists can identify MTB under a microscope."}, {"list": ["acid-fast bacillus"], "text": "Since MTB retains certain stains even after being treated with acidic solution, it is classified as an acid-fast bacillus."}, {"list": ["Ziehl–Neelsen stain", "Kinyoun stain"], "text": "The most common acid-fast staining techniques are the Ziehl–Neelsen stain and the Kinyoun stain, which dye acid-fast bacilli a bright red that stands out against a blue background."}, {"list": ["Auramine-rhodamine staining", "fluorescence microscopy"], "text": "Auramine-rhodamine staining and fluorescence microscopy are also used."}, {"list": ["\'\'M. tuberculosis\'\' complex", "mycobacteria", "M. bovis\'\'", "M. africanum\'\'", "M. canetti\'\'", "M. microti\'\'"], "text": "The M. tuberculosis complex (MTBC) includes four other TB-causing mycobacteria: M. bovis, M. africanum, M. canetti, and M. microti."}, {"text": "M. africanum is not widespread, but it is a significant cause of tuberculosis in parts of Africa."}, {"list": ["pasteurized milk"], "text": "M. bovis was once a common cause of tuberculosis, but the introduction of pasteurized milk has almost completely eliminated this as a public health problem in developed countries."}, {"list": ["Horn of Africa"], "text": "M. canetti is rare and seems to be limited to the Horn of Africa, although a few cases have been seen in African emigrants."}, {"list": ["prevalence"], "text": "M. microti is also rare and is seen almost only in immunodeficient people, although its prevalence may be significantly underestimated."}, {"list": ["M. leprae\'\'", "M. avium\'\'", "M. kansasii\'\'"], "text": "Other known pathogenic mycobacteria include M. leprae, M. avium, and M. kansasii."}, {"list": ["nontuberculous mycobacteria"], "text": "The latter two species are classified as \\"nontuberculous mycobacteria\\" (NTM)."}, {"list": ["leprosy"], "text": "NTM cause neither TB nor leprosy, but they do cause lung diseases that resemble TB."}, {"text": "A number of factors make people more susceptible to TB infections."}, {"text": "The most important risk factor globally is HIV; 13% of all people with TB are infected by the virus."}, {"list": ["sub-Saharan Africa"], "text": "This is a particular problem in sub-Saharan Africa, where rates of HIV are high."}, {"text": "Of people without HIV who are infected with tuberculosis, about 5–10% develop active disease during their lifetimes; in contrast, 30% of those coinfected with HIV develop the active disease."}, {"list": ["malnutrition", "diseases of poverty"], "text": "Tuberculosis is closely linked to both overcrowding and malnutrition, making it one of the principal diseases of poverty."}, {"text": "Those at high risk thus include: people who inject illicit drugs, inhabitants and employees of locales where vulnerable people gather (e.g. prisons and homeless shelters), medically underprivileged and resource-poor communities, high-risk ethnic minorities, children in close contact with high-risk category patients, and health-care providers serving these patients."}, {"text": "Chronic lung disease is another significant risk factor."}, {"list": ["Silicosis"], "text": "Silicosis increases the risk about 30-fold."}, {"list": ["cigarettes"], "text": "Those who smoke cigarettes have nearly twice the risk of TB compared to nonsmokers."}, {"text": "Other disease states can also increase the risk of developing tuberculosis."}, {"list": ["alcoholism", "diabetes mellitus"], "text": "These include alcoholism and diabetes mellitus (three-fold increase)."}, {"list": ["corticosteroids", "infliximab", "developed world"], "text": "Certain medications, such as corticosteroids and infliximab (an anti-αTNF monoclonal antibody), are becoming increasingly important risk factors, especially in the developed world."}, {"list": ["Genetic susceptibility"], "text": "Genetic susceptibility also exists, for which the overall importance remains undefined."}, {"list": ["aerosol", "µm"], "text": "When people with active pulmonary TB cough, sneeze, speak, sing, or spit, they expel infectious aerosol droplets 0.5 to 5.0 µm in diameter."}, {"text": "A single sneeze can release up to 40,000 droplets."}, {"text": "Each one of these droplets may transmit the disease, since the infectious dose of tuberculosis is very small (the inhalation of fewer than 10 bacteria may cause an infection)."}, {"text": "People with prolonged, frequent, or close contact with people with TB are at particularly high risk of becoming infected, with an estimated 22% infection rate."}, {"text": "A person with active but untreated tuberculosis may infect 10–15 (or more) other people per year."}, {"text": "Transmission should occur from only people with active TB – those with latent infection are not thought to be contagious."}, {"list": ["virulence"], "text": "The probability of transmission from one person to another depends upon several factors, including the number of infectious droplets expelled by the carrier, the effectiveness of ventilation, the duration of exposure, the virulence of the \'\'M."}, {"list": ["strain"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\' strain, the level of immunity in the uninfected person, and others."}, {"text": "The cascade of person-to-person spread can be circumvented by segregating those with active (\\"overt\\") TB and putting them on anti-TB drug regimens."}, {"list": ["nonresistant"], "text": "After about two weeks of effective treatment, subjects with nonresistant active infections generally do not remain contagious to others."}, {"text": "If someone does become infected, it typically takes three to four weeks before the newly infected person becomes infectious enough to transmit the disease to others."}, {"text": "About 90% of those infected with \'\'M."}, {"list": ["asymptomatic"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\' have asymptomatic, latent TB infections (sometimes called LTBI), with only a 10% lifetime chance that the latent infection will progress to overt, active tuberculous disease."}, {"text": "In those with HIV, the risk of developing active TB increases to nearly 10% a year."}, {"text": "If effective treatment is not given, the death rate for active TB cases is up to 66%."}, {"list": ["alveolar air sacs", "endosomes", "macrophages"], "text": "TB infection begins when the mycobacteria reach the alveolar air sacs of the lungs, where they invade and replicate within endosomes of alveolar macrophages."}, {"list": ["phagocytosis"], "text": "Macrophages identify the bacterium as foreign and attempt to eliminate it by phagocytosis."}, {"text": "During this process, the bacterium is enveloped by the macrophage and stored temporarily in a membrane-bound vesicle called a phagosome."}, {"text": "The phagosome then combines with a lysosome to create a phagolysosome."}, {"list": ["reactive oxygen species"], "text": "In the phagolysosome, the cell attempts to use reactive oxygen species and acid to kill the bacterium."}, {"text": "However, \'\'M."}, {"list": ["mycolic acid"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\' has a thick, waxy mycolic acid capsule that protects it from these toxic substances."}, {"text": "M. tuberculosis is able to reproduce inside the macrophage and will eventually kill the immune cell."}, {"list": ["Ghon focus", "upper lobe"], "text": "The primary site of infection in the lungs, known as the \\"Ghon focus\\", is generally located in either the upper part of the lower lobe, or the lower part of the upper lobe."}, {"text": "Tuberculosis of the lungs may also occur via infection from the blood stream."}, {"list": ["Simon focus"], "text": "This is known as a Simon focus and is typically found in the top of the lung."}, {"text": "This hematogenous transmission can also spread infection to more distant sites, such as peripheral lymph nodes, the kidneys, the brain, and the bones."}, {"list": ["heart", "skeletal muscles", "pancreas", "thyroid"], "text": "All parts of the body can be affected by the disease, though for unknown reasons it rarely affects the heart, skeletal muscles, pancreas, or thyroid."}, {"list": ["granulomatous"], "text": "Tuberculosis is classified as one of the granulomatous inflammatory diseases."}, {"list": ["Macrophages", "T lymphocytes", "B lymphocytes", "fibroblasts", "granulomas", "lymphocytes"], "text": "Macrophages, T lymphocytes, B lymphocytes, and fibroblasts aggregate to form granulomas, with lymphocytes surrounding the infected macrophages."}, {"text": "When other macrophages attack the infected macrophage, they fuse together to form a giant multinucleated cell in the alveolar lumen."}, {"text": "The granuloma may prevent dissemination of the mycobacteria and provide a local environment for interaction of cells of the immune system."}, {"text": "However, more recent evidence suggests that the bacteria use the granulomas to avoid destruction by the host\'s immune system."}, {"list": ["dendritic cells"], "text": "Macrophages and dendritic cells in the granulomas are unable to present antigen to lymphocytes; thus the immune response is suppressed."}, {"text": "Bacteria inside the granuloma can become dormant, resulting in latent infection."}, {"list": ["necrosis", "tubercles"], "text": "Another feature of the granulomas is the development of abnormal cell death (necrosis) in the center of tubercles."}, {"list": ["caseous necrosis"], "text": "To the naked eye, this has the texture of soft, white cheese and is termed caseous necrosis."}, {"text": "If TB bacteria gain entry to the blood stream from an area of damaged tissue, they can spread throughout the body and set up many foci of infection, all appearing as tiny, white tubercles in the tissues."}, {"text": "This severe form of TB disease, most common in young children and those with HIV, is called miliary tuberculosis."}, {"text": "People with this disseminated TB have a high fatality rate even with treatment (about 30%)."}, {"text": "In many people, the infection waxes and wanes."}, {"list": ["fibrosis"], "text": "Tissue destruction and necrosis are often balanced by healing and fibrosis."}, {"text": "Affected tissue is replaced by scarring and cavities filled with caseous necrotic material."}, {"list": ["bronchi"], "text": "During active disease, some of these cavities are joined to the air passages (bronchi) and this material can be coughed up. It contains living bacteria, and thus can spread the infection."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Treatment with appropriate antibiotics kills bacteria and allows healing to take place."}, {"text": "Upon cure, affected areas are eventually replaced by scar tissue."}, {"text": "Diagnosing active tuberculosis based only on signs and symptoms is difficult, as is diagnosing the disease in those who have a weakened immune system."}, {"list": ["constitutional symptoms"], "text": "A diagnosis of TB should, however, be considered in those with signs of lung disease or constitutional symptoms lasting longer than two weeks."}, {"list": ["chest X-ray", "sputum cultures", "acid-fast bacilli"], "text": "A chest X-ray and multiple sputum cultures for acid-fast bacilli are typically part of the initial evaluation."}, {"text": "Interferon-γ release assays and tuberculin skin tests are of little use in the developing world."}, {"list": ["Interferon gamma release assays"], "text": "Interferon gamma release assays (IGRA) have similar limitations in those with HIV."}, {"text": "A definitive diagnosis of TB is made by identifying \'\'M."}, {"list": ["pus", "tissue", "biopsy"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\' in a clinical sample (e.g., sputum, pus, or a tissue biopsy)."}, {"text": "However, the difficult culture process for this slow-growing organism can take two to six weeks for blood or sputum culture."}, {"text": "Thus, treatment is often begun before cultures are confirmed."}, {"list": ["Nucleic acid amplification tests", "adenosine deaminase"], "text": "Nucleic acid amplification tests and adenosine deaminase testing may allow rapid diagnosis of TB. These tests, however, are not routinely recommended, as they rarely alter how a person is treated."}, {"list": ["specific or sensitive"], "text": "Blood tests to detect antibodies are not specific or sensitive, so they are not recommended."}, {"list": ["Mantoux tuberculin skin test"], "text": "The Mantoux tuberculin skin test is often used to screen people at high risk for TB. Those who have been previously immunized with the Bacille Calmette-Guerin vaccine may have a false-positive test result."}, {"list": ["sarcoidosis", "Hodgkin\'s lymphoma", "malnutrition"], "text": "The test may be falsely negative in those with sarcoidosis, Hodgkin\'s lymphoma, malnutrition, and most notably, active tuberculosis."}, {"text": "Interferon gamma release assays, on a blood sample, are recommended in those who are positive to the Mantoux test."}, {"list": ["environmental mycobacteria", "false-positive"], "text": "These are not affected by immunization or most environmental mycobacteria, so they generate fewer false-positive results."}, {"text": "However, they are affected by \'\'M."}, {"text": "szulgai, M."}, {"text": "marinum, and M."}, {"text": "kansasii\'\'."}, {"text": "IGRAs may increase sensitivity when used in addition to the skin test, but may be less sensitive than the skin test when used alone."}, {"text": "Tuberculosis prevention and control efforts rely primarily on the vaccination of infants and the detection and appropriate treatment of active cases."}, {"list": ["World Health Organization"], "text": "The World Health Organization has achieved some success with improved treatment regimens, and a small decrease in case numbers."}, {"list": ["US Preventive Services Task Force"], "text": "The US Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends screening people who are at high risk for latent tuberculosis with either tuberculin skin tests or interferon-gamma release assays."}, {"list": ["vaccine", "Bacillus Calmette-Guérin"], "text": "The only available vaccine as of 2011 is Bacillus Calmette-Guérin (BCG)."}, {"text": "In children it decreases the risk of getting the infection by 20% and the risk of infection turning into active disease by nearly 60%."}, {"list": ["vaccinated"], "text": "It is the most widely used vaccine worldwide, with more than 90% of all children being vaccinated."}, {"text": "The immunity it induces decreases after about ten years."}, {"text": "As tuberculosis is uncommon in most of Canada, the United Kingdom, and the United States, BCG is administered to only those people at high risk."}, {"list": ["tuberculin skin test"], "text": "Part of the reasoning against the use of the vaccine is that it makes the tuberculin skin test falsely positive, reducing the test\'s usefulness as a screening tool."}, {"text": "A number of new vaccines are currently in development."}, {"list": ["Global Plan to Stop Tuberculosis"], "text": "The World Health Organization declared TB a \\"global health emergency\\" in 1993, and in 2006, the Stop TB Partnership developed a Global Plan to Stop Tuberculosis that aimed to save 14 million lives between its launch and 2015."}, {"text": "A number of targets they set were not achieved by 2015, mostly due to the increase in HIV-associated tuberculosis and the emergence of multiple drug-resistant tuberculosis."}, {"list": ["tuberculosis classification", "American Thoracic Society"], "text": "A tuberculosis classification system developed by the American Thoracic Society is used primarily in public health programs."}, {"text": "Treatment of TB uses antibiotics to kill the bacteria."}, {"text": "Effective TB treatment is difficult, due to the unusual structure and chemical composition of the mycobacterial cell wall, which hinders the entry of drugs and makes many antibiotics ineffective."}, {"list": ["isoniazid", "rifampicin"], "text": "The two antibiotics most commonly used are isoniazid and rifampicin, and treatments can be prolonged, taking several months."}, {"list": ["antibiotic resistance"], "text": "Latent TB treatment usually employs a single antibiotic, while active TB disease is best treated with combinations of several antibiotics to reduce the risk of the bacteria developing antibiotic resistance."}, {"text": "People with latent infections are also treated to prevent them from progressing to active TB disease later in life."}, {"list": ["Directly observed therapy"], "text": "Directly observed therapy, i.e., having a health care provider watch the person take their medications, is recommended by the WHO in an effort to reduce the number of people not appropriately taking antibiotics."}, {"text": "The evidence to support this practice over people simply taking their medications independently is of poor quality."}, {"text": "There is no strong evidence indicating that directly observed therapy improves the number of people who were cured or the number of people who complete their medicine."}, {"text": "Moderate quality evidence suggests that there is also no difference if people are observed at home versus at a clinic, or by a family member versus a health care worker."}, {"text": "Methods to remind people of the importance of treatment and appointments may result in a small but important improvement."}, {"list": ["pyrazinamide", "ethambutol"], "text": "The recommended treatment of new-onset pulmonary tuberculosis, as of 2010, is six months of a combination of antibiotics containing rifampicin, isoniazid, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol for the first two months, and only rifampicin and isoniazid for the last four months."}, {"text": "Where resistance to isoniazid is high, ethambutol may be added for the last four months as an alternative."}, {"text": "If tuberculosis recurs, testing to determine which antibiotics it is sensitive to is important before determining treatment."}, {"list": ["multiple drug-resistant TB"], "text": "If multiple drug-resistant TB (MDR-TB) is detected, treatment with at least four effective antibiotics for 18 to 24 months is recommended."}, {"list": ["MTB"], "text": "Primary resistance occurs when a person becomes infected with a resistant strain of TB. A person with fully susceptible MTB may develop secondary (acquired) resistance during therapy because of inadequate treatment, not taking the prescribed regimen appropriately (lack of compliance), or using low-quality medication."}, {"text": "Drug-resistant TB is a serious public health issue in many developing countries, as its treatment is longer and requires more expensive drugs."}, {"text": "MDR-TB is defined as resistance to the two most effective first-line TB drugs: rifampicin and isoniazid."}, {"list": ["Extensively drug-resistant TB"], "text": "Extensively drug-resistant TB is also resistant to three or more of the six classes of second-line drugs."}, {"list": ["Totally drug-resistant TB"], "text": "Totally drug-resistant TB is resistant to all currently used drugs."}, {"text": "It was first observed in 2003 in Italy, but not widely reported until 2012, and has also been found in Iran and India."}, {"list": ["Bedaquiline"], "text": "Bedaquiline is tentatively supported for use in multiple drug-resistant TB. XDR-TB is a term sometimes used to define extensively resistant TB, and constitutes one in ten cases of MDR-TB."}, {"text": "Cases of XDR TB have been identified in more than 90% of countries."}, {"list": ["Age-standardized", "disability-adjusted life years", "latent infection"], "text": "Tuberculosis world map - DALY - WHO2004.svg disability-adjusted life years caused by tuberculosis per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004. Progression from TB infection to overt TB disease occurs when the bacilli overcome the immune system defenses and begin to multiply. In primary TB disease (some 1–5% of cases), this occurs soon after the initial infection. However, in the majority of cases, a latent infection occurs with no obvious symptoms. These dormant bacilli produce active tuberculosis in 5–10% of these latent cases, often many years after infection. The risk of reactivation increases with immunosuppression, such as that caused by infection with HIV. In people coinfected with M. tuberculosis and HIV, the risk of reactivation increases to 10% per year. Studies using DNA fingerprinting of M. tuberculosis strains have shown reinfection contributes more substantially to recurrent TB than previously thought, with estimates that it might account for more than 50% of reactivated cases in areas where TB is common. The chance of death from a case of tuberculosis is about 4% as of 2008, down from 8% in 1995."}, {"list": ["developing countries", "Swaziland", "aboriginal peoples", "Native Americans"], "text": "Tuberculosis world map-Deaths per million persons-WHO2012.svg. Of these 1.45 million deaths, about 0.35 million occur in those also infected with HIV. Tuberculosis is the second-most common cause of death from infectious disease (after those due to HIV/AIDS). The total number of tuberculosis cases has been decreasing since 2005, while new cases have decreased since 2002. China has achieved particularly dramatic progress, with about an 80% reduction in its TB mortality rate between 1990 and 2010. The number of new cases has declined by 17% between 2004 and 2014. Tuberculosis is more common in developing countries; about 80% of the population in many Asian and African countries test positive in tuberculin tests, while only 5–10% of the US population test positive. Hopes of totally controlling the disease have been dramatically dampened because of a number of factors, including the difficulty of developing an effective vaccine, the expensive and time-consuming diagnostic process, the necessity of many months of treatment, the increase in HIV-associated tuberculosis, and the emergence of drug-resistant cases in the 1980s. In 2007, the country with the highest estimated incidence rate of TB was Swaziland, with 1,200 cases per 100,000 people. India had the largest total incidence, with an estimated 2.0 million new cases. In developed countries, tuberculosis is less common and is found mainly in urban areas. Rates per 100,000 people in different areas of the world were: globally 178, Africa 332, the Americas 36, Eastern Mediterranean 173, Europe 63, Southeast Asia 278, and Western Pacific 139 in 2010. In Canada and Australia, tuberculosis is many times more common among the aboriginal peoples, especially in remote areas. In the United States Native Americans have a fivefold greater mortality from TB, and racial and ethnic minorities accounted for 84% of all reported TB cases. The rates of TB varies with age. In Africa, it primarily affects adolescents and young adults. However, in countries where incidence rates have declined dramatically (such as the United States), TB is mainly a disease of older people and the immunocompromised (risk factors are listed above). Worldwide, 22 \\"high-burden\\" states or countries together experience 80% of cases as well as 83% of deaths."}, {"list": ["antiquity"], "text": "Tuberculosis has been present in humans since antiquity."}, {"text": "The earliest unambiguous detection of \'\'M."}, {"text": "tuberculosis\'\' involves evidence of the disease in the remains of bison in Wyoming dated to around 17,000 years ago."}, {"text": "However, whether tuberculosis originated in bovines, then was transferred to humans, or whether it diverged from a common ancestor, is currently unclear."}, {"list": ["genes"], "text": "A comparison of the genes of \'\'M."}, {"text": "tuberculosis\'\' complex (MTBC) in humans to MTBC in animals suggests humans did not acquire MTBC from animals during animal domestication, as was previously believed."}, {"list": ["Neolithic Revolution"], "text": "Both strains of the tuberculosis bacteria share a common ancestor, which could have infected humans even before the Neolithic Revolution."}, {"list": ["BC", "Egyptian", "mummies", "the Americas", "Industrial Revolution", "vampires"], "text": "Skeletal remains show prehistoric humans (4000 BC) had TB, and researchers have found tubercular decay in the spines of Egyptian mummies dating from 3000–2400 BC. Genetic studies suggest TB was present in the Americas from about 100 AD. Before the Industrial Revolution, folklore often associated tuberculosis with vampires."}, {"text": "When one member of a family died from it, the other infected members would lose their health slowly."}, {"text": "People believed this was caused by the original person with TB draining the life from the other family members."}, {"list": ["tubercles", "Richard Morton"], "text": "Although the pulmonary form associated with tubercles was established as a pathology by Richard Morton in 1689, due to the variety of its symptoms, TB was not identified as a single disease until the 1820s."}, {"list": ["J. L. Schönlein"], "text": "It was not named \\"tuberculosis\\" until 1839, by J. L. Schönlein."}, {"list": ["Mammoth Cave"], "text": "During 1838–1845, Dr. John Croghan, the owner of Mammoth Cave, brought a number of people with tuberculosis into the cave in the hope of curing the disease with the constant temperature and purity of the cave air; they died within a year."}, {"list": ["sanatorium", "Sokołowsko", "Silesia"], "text": "Hermann Brehmer opened the first TB sanatorium in 1859 in Görbersdorf (now Sokołowsko), Silesia."}, {"text": "The bacillus causing tuberculosis, \'\'M."}, {"list": ["Robert Koch"], "text": "tuberculosis\'\', was identified and described on 24 March 1882 by Robert Koch."}, {"list": ["Nobel Prize in physiology or medicine"], "text": "He received the Nobel Prize in physiology or medicine in 1905 for this discovery."}, {"text": "Koch did not believe the bovine (cattle) and human tuberculosis diseases were similar, which delayed the recognition of infected milk as a source of infection."}, {"list": ["pasteurization"], "text": "Later, the risk of transmission from this source was dramatically reduced by the invention of the pasteurization process."}, {"list": ["glycerine"], "text": "Koch announced a glycerine extract of the tubercle bacilli as a \\"remedy\\" for tuberculosis in 1890, calling it \\"tuberculin\\"."}, {"text": "While it was not effective, it was later successfully adapted as a screening test for the presence of pre-symptomatic tuberculosis."}, {"list": ["World Tuberculosis Day"], "text": "The World Tuberculosis Day is marked on 24 March each year, the anniversary of Koch’s original scientific announcement."}, {"list": ["Albert Calmette", "Camille Guérin"], "text": "Albert Calmette and Camille Guérin achieved the first genuine success in immunization against tuberculosis in 1906, using attenuated bovine-strain tuberculosis."}, {"list": ["bacille Calmette–Guérin"], "text": "It was called bacille Calmette–Guérin (BCG)."}, {"text": "The BCG vaccine was first used on humans in 1921 in France, but received widespread acceptance in the US, Great Britain, and Germany only after World War II. Tuberculosis caused widespread public concern in the 19th and early 20th centuries as the disease became common among the urban poor."}, {"text": "In 1815, one in four deaths in England was due to \\"consumption\\"."}, {"list": ["notifiable disease", "sanatoria"], "text": "By 1918, one in six deaths in France was still caused by TB. After TB was determined to be contagious, in the 1880s, it was put on a notifiable disease list in Britain; campaigns were started to stop people from spitting in public places, and the infected poor were \\"encouraged\\" to enter sanatoria that resembled prisons (the sanatoria for the middle and upper classes offered excellent care and constant medical attention)."}, {"text": "Whatever the benefits of the \\"fresh air\\" and labor in the sanatoria, even under the best conditions, 50% of those who entered died within five years (c. 1916)."}, {"list": ["Medical Research Council"], "text": "When the Medical Research Council was formed in Britain in 1913, its initial focus was tuberculosis research."}, {"text": "In Europe, rates of tuberculosis began to rise in the early 1600s to a peak level in the 1800s, when it caused nearly 25% of all deaths."}, {"text": "By the 1950s, mortality in Europe had decreased about 90%."}, {"list": ["streptomycin"], "text": "Improvements in sanitation, vaccination, and other public health measures began significantly reducing rates of tuberculosis even before the arrival of streptomycin and other antibiotics, although the disease remained a significant threat."}, {"list": ["streptomycin"], "text": "In 1946, the development of the antibiotic streptomycin made effective treatment and cure of TB a reality."}, {"list": ["pneumothorax"], "text": "Prior to the introduction of this medication, the only treatment was surgical intervention, including the \\"pneumothorax technique\\", which involved collapsing an infected lung to \\"rest\\" it and allow tuberculous lesions to heal."}, {"text": "Because of the emergence of MDR-TB, surgery has been re-introduced for certain cases of TB infections."}, {"text": "It involves removal of infected chest cavities (\\"bullae\\") in the lungs to reduce the number of bacteria and to increase exposure of the remaining bacteria to antibiotics in the bloodstream."}, {"list": ["drug-resistant"], "text": "Hopes of completely eliminating TB were ended with the rise of drug-resistant strains in the 1980s."}, {"text": "The subsequent resurgence of tuberculosis resulted in the declaration of a global health emergency by the World Health Organization in 1993."}, {"text": "Tuberculosis has been known by many names from the technical to the familiar."}, {"list": ["Hippocrates"], "text": "Phthisis (Φθισις) is a Greek word for consumption, an old term for pulmonary tuberculosis; around 460 BCE, Hippocrates described phthisis as a disease of dry seasons."}, {"list": ["bacillus\'\'"], "text": "The abbreviation \\"TB\\" is short for tubercle bacillus."}, {"text": "\\"Consumption\\" was the most common nineteenth century English word for the disease."}, {"list": ["The Life and Death of Mr Badman\'\'", "John Bunyan"], "text": "The Latin root \\"con\\" meaning \\"completely\\" is linked to \\"sumere\\" meaning \\"to take up from under.\\" In The Life and Death of Mr Badman by John Bunyan, the author calls consumption \\"the captain of all these men of death.\\" \\"Great white plague\\" has also been used."}, {"list": ["poetic", "artistic"], "text": "Tuberculosis was for centuries associated with poetic and artistic qualities among those infected, and was also known as \\"the romantic disease\\"."}, {"list": ["John Keats", "Percy Bysshe Shelley", "Edgar Allan Poe", "Frederic Chopin", "Charlotte Brontë", "Fyodor Dostoevsky", "Thomas Mann", "W. Somerset Maugham", "Robert Louis Stevenson", "Alice Neel", "Jean-Antoine Watteau", "Elizabeth Siddal", "Marie Bashkirtseff", "Edvard Munch", "Aubrey Beardsley", "Amedeo Modigliani"], "text": "Major artistic figures such as the poets John Keats, Percy Bysshe Shelley, and Edgar Allan Poe, the composer Frederic Chopin, the novelists Charlotte Brontë, Fyodor Dostoevsky, Thomas Mann, W. Somerset Maugham, and Robert Louis Stevenson, and the artists Alice Neel, Jean-Antoine Watteau, Elizabeth Siddal, Marie Bashkirtseff, Edvard Munch, Aubrey Beardsley and Amedeo Modigliani either had the disease or were surrounded by people who did."}, {"text": "A widespread belief was that tuberculosis assisted artistic talent."}, {"text": "Physical mechanisms proposed for this effect included the slight fever and toxaemia that it caused, allegedly helping them to see life more clearly and to act decisively."}, {"list": ["literature", "Thomas Mann\'s", "The Magic Mountain\'\'", "sanatorium", "music", "Van Morrison\'s", "T.B. Sheets", "opera", "Puccini\'s", "La bohème\'\'", "Verdi\'s", "La Traviata\'\'", "art", "Monet\'s", "film", "The Bells of St. Mary\'s\'\'", "Ingrid Bergman"], "text": "Tuberculosis formed an often-reused theme in literature, as in Thomas Mann\'s The Magic Mountain, set in a sanatorium; in music, as in Van Morrison\'s song \\"T.B. Sheets\\"; in opera, as in Puccini\'s La bohème and Verdi\'s La Traviata; in art, as in Monet\'s painting of his first wife Camille on her deathbed; and in film, such as the 1945 \'\'The Bells of St. Mary\'s\'\' starring Ingrid Bergman as a nun with tuberculosis."}, {"list": ["World Health Organization", "Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation"], "text": "The World Health Organization, Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and US government are subsidizing a fast-acting diagnostic tuberculosis test for use in low- and middle-income countries."}, {"text": "In addition to being fast-acting, the test can determine if there is resistance to the antibiotic rifampicin which may indicate multi-drug resistant tuberculosis and is accurate in those who are also infected with HIV."}, {"text": "Many resource-poor places as of 2011 have access to only sputum microscopy."}, {"text": "India had the highest total number of TB cases worldwide in 2010, in part due to poor disease management within the private and public health care sector."}, {"list": ["Revised National Tuberculosis Control Program"], "text": "Programs such as the Revised National Tuberculosis Control Program are working to reduce TB levels amongst people receiving public health care."}, {"list": ["EIU"], "text": "A 2014 the EIU-healthcare report that the need to address apathy and urging for increased funding."}, {"text": "The report cites among others Lucica Ditui \\"[TB] is like an orphan. It has been neglected even in countries with a high burden and often forgotten by donors and those investing in health interventions.\\""}, {"list": ["Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria"], "text": "Slow progress has led to frustration, expressed by the executive director of the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria – Mark Dybul: \\"we have the tools to end TB as a pandemic and public health threat on the planet, but we are not doing it.\\" Several international organizations are pushing for more transparency in treatment, and more countries are implementing mandatory reporting of cases to the government, although adherence is often sketchy."}, {"text": "Commercial treatment providers may at times overprescribe second-line drugs as well as supplementary treatment, promoting demands for further regulations."}, {"text": "The government of Brazil provides universal TB-care, which reduces this problem."}, {"text": "Conversely, falling rates of TB-infection may not relate to the number of programs directed at reducing infection rates but may be tied to increased level of education, income, and health of the population."}, {"text": "Costs of the disease, as calculated by the World Bank in 2009 may exceed 150 billion USD per year in \\"high burden\\" countries."}, {"list": ["rural migrants in China"], "text": "Lack of progress eradicating the disease may also be due to lack of patient follow-up – as among the 250M rural migrants in China."}, {"list": ["stigma"], "text": "Slow progress in preventing the disease may in part be due to stigma associated with TB. Stigma may be due to the fear of transmission from affected individuals."}, {"list": ["Africa, AIDS"], "text": "This stigma may additionally arise due to links between TB and poverty, and in Africa, AIDS."}, {"text": "Such stigmatization may be both real and perceived; for example, in Ghana individuals with TB are banned from attending public gatherings."}, {"text": "Stigma towards TB may result in delays in seeking treatment, lower treatment compliance, and family members keeping cause of death secret – allowing the disease to spread further."}, {"text": "At odds is Russia, where stigma was associated with increased treatment compliance."}, {"text": "TB stigma also affects socially marginalized individuals to a greater degree and varies between regions."}, {"text": "One way to decrease stigma may be through the promotion of \\"TB clubs\\", where those infected may share experiences and offer support, or through counseling."}, {"text": "Some studies have shown TB education programs to be effective in decreasing stigma, and may thus be effective in increasing treatment adherence."}, {"text": "Despite this, studies on the relationship between reduced stigma and mortality are lacking as of 2010, and similar efforts to decrease stigma surrounding AIDS have been minimally effective."}, {"text": "Some have claimed the stigma to be worse than the disease, and healthcare providers may unintentionally reinforce stigma, as those with TB are often perceived as difficult or otherwise undesirable."}, {"text": "A greater understanding of the social and cultural dimensions of tuberculosis may also help with stigma reduction."}, {"text": "The BCG vaccine has limitations, and research to develop new TB vaccines is ongoing."}, {"list": ["phase I and II clinical trials"], "text": "A number of potential candidates are currently in phase I and II clinical trials."}, {"text": "Two main approaches are being used to attempt to improve the efficacy of available vaccines."}, {"text": "One approach involves adding a subunit vaccine to BCG, while the other strategy is attempting to create new and better live vaccines."}, {"list": ["MVA85A", "vaccinia"], "text": "MVA85A, an example of a subunit vaccine, currently in trials in South Africa, is based on a genetically modified vaccinia virus."}, {"text": "Vaccines are hoped to play a significant role in treatment of both latent and active disease."}, {"list": ["advance market commitments"], "text": "To encourage further discovery, researchers and policymakers are promoting new economic models of vaccine development, including prizes, tax incentives, and advance market commitments."}, {"list": ["Stop TB Partnership", "Aeras Global TB Vaccine Foundation"], "text": "A number of groups, including the Stop TB Partnership, the South African Tuberculosis Vaccine Initiative, and the Aeras Global TB Vaccine Foundation, are involved with research."}, {"list": ["Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation"], "text": "Among these, the Aeras Global TB Vaccine Foundation received a gift of more than $280 million (US) from the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation to develop and license an improved vaccine against tuberculosis for use in high burden countries."}, {"list": ["bedaquiline", "delamanid"], "text": "A number of medications are being studied for multidrug-resistant tuberculosis, including bedaquiline and delamanid."}, {"list": ["Food and Drug Administration"], "text": "Bedaquiline received U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approval in late 2012."}, {"text": "The safety and effectiveness of these new agents are still uncertain, because they are based on the results of relatively small studies."}, {"text": "However, existing data suggest that patients taking bedaquiline in addition to standard TB therapy are five times more likely to die than those without the new drug, which has resulted in medical journal articles raising health policy questions about why the FDA approved the drug and whether financial ties to the company making bedaquiline influenced physicians\' support for its use."}, {"text": "Mycobacteria infect many different animals, including birds, rodents, and reptiles."}, {"text": "The subspecies Mycobacterium tuberculosis, though, is rarely present in wild animals."}, {"list": ["Mycobacterium bovis\'\'", "New Zealand"], "text": "An effort to eradicate bovine tuberculosis caused by Mycobacterium bovis from the cattle and deer herds of New Zealand has been relatively successful."}, {"text": "Efforts in Great Britain have been less successful."}, {"list": ["elephants", "reverse zoonosis"], "text": ", tuberculosis appears to be widespread among captive elephants in the US. It is believed that the animals originally acquired the disease from humans, a process called reverse zoonosis."}, {"list": ["circuses", "zoos"], "text": "Because the disease can spread through the air to infect both humans and other animals, it is a public health concern affecting circuses and zoos."}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/Tuberculosis-x-ray-1.jpg", "file": "File:Tuberculosis-x-ray-1.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Tuberculosis-x-ray-1.jpg/300px-Tuberculosis-x-ray-1.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b8/Tuberculosis_video.webm", "file": "File:Tuberculosis video.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Tuberculosis_video.webm/300px-Tuberculosis_video.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2f/Tuberculosis_symptoms.svg", "file": "File:Tuberculosis symptoms.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Tuberculosis_symptoms.svg/300px-Tuberculosis_symptoms.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cb/Mycobacterium_tuberculosis.jpg", "file": "File:Mycobacterium tuberculosis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Mycobacterium_tuberculosis.jpg/300px-Mycobacterium_tuberculosis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8e/TB_poster.jpg", "file": "File:TB poster.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/TB_poster.jpg/300px-TB_poster.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8c/Tuberculous_epididymitis_Low_Power.jpg", "file": "File:Tuberculous epididymitis Low Power.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Tuberculous_epididymitis_Low_Power.jpg/300px-Tuberculous_epididymitis_Low_Power.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/03/Carswell-Tubercle.jpg", "file": "File:Carswell-Tubercle.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Carswell-Tubercle.jpg/300px-Carswell-Tubercle.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/27/TB_in_sputum.png", "file": "File:TB in sputum.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/TB_in_sputum.png/300px-TB_in_sputum.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fa/Mantoux_tuberculin_skin_test.jpg", "file": "File:Mantoux tuberculin skin test.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Mantoux_tuberculin_skin_test.jpg/300px-Mantoux_tuberculin_skin_test.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f4/3f05369r_(8435815214).jpg", "file": "File:3f05369r (8435815214).jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f4/3f05369r_(8435815214).jpg/300px-3f05369r_(8435815214).jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e1/Tuberculosis-prevalence-WHO-2009.svg", "file": "File:Tuberculosis-prevalence-WHO-2009.svg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Tuberculosis-prevalence-WHO-2009.svg/300px-Tuberculosis-prevalence-WHO-2009.svg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cc/Mummy_at_British_Museum.jpg", "file": "File:Mummy at British Museum.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/Mummy_at_British_Museum.jpg/300px-Mummy_at_British_Museum.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/07/RobertKoch.jpg", "file": "File:RobertKoch.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/RobertKoch.jpg/300px-RobertKoch.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c2/Munch_Det_Syke_Barn_1885-86.jpg", "file": "File:Munch Det Syke Barn 1885-86.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Munch_Det_Syke_Barn_1885-86.jpg/300px-Munch_Det_Syke_Barn_1885-86.jpg"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(33, 'urinary_tract_infection', 'Urinary%20tract%20infection', 'Multiple%20white%20cells%20seen%20in%20the%20urine%20of%20a%20person%20with%20a%20urinary%20tract%20infection%20using%20a%20microscopy', 'Infectious%20disease', '["Pain with urination", "frequent urination", "feeling the need to urinate despite having an empty bladder"]', '{"desc": "Based on symptoms, urine culture", "list": ["urine culture"]}', '{"desc": "Most often Escherichia coli", "list": ["Escherichia coli\'\'"]}', '[{"list": ["infection", "urinary tract"], "text": "A urinary tract infection (UTI) is an infection that affects part of the urinary tract."}, {"list": ["pyelonephritis"], "text": "When it affects the lower urinary tract it is known as a bladder infection (cystitis) and when it affects the upper urinary tract it is known as kidney infection (pyelonephritis)."}, {"list": ["urination"], "text": "Symptoms from a lower urinary tract include pain with urination, frequent urination, and feeling the need to urinate despite having an empty bladder."}, {"list": ["fever", "flank pain"], "text": "Symptoms of a kidney infection include fever and flank pain usually in addition to the symptoms of a lower UTI."}, {"list": ["bloody"], "text": "Rarely the urine may appear bloody."}, {"text": "In the very old and the very young, symptoms may be vague or non-specific."}, {"list": ["Escherichia coli\'\'", "fungi"], "text": "The most common cause of infection is Escherichia coli, though other bacteria or fungi may rarely be the cause."}, {"list": ["diabetes", "obesity"], "text": "Risk factors include female anatomy, sexual intercourse, diabetes, obesity, and family history."}, {"list": ["sexually transmitted infections"], "text": "Although sexual intercourse is a risk factor, UTIs are not classified as sexually transmitted infections (STIs)."}, {"list": ["blood-borne infection"], "text": "Kidney infection, if it occurs, usually follows a bladder infection but may also result from a blood-borne infection."}, {"text": "Diagnosis in young healthy women can be based on symptoms alone."}, {"text": "In those with vague symptoms, diagnosis can be difficult because bacteria may be present without there being an infection."}, {"list": ["urine culture"], "text": "In complicated cases or if treatment fails, a urine culture may be useful."}, {"list": ["antibiotics", "nitrofurantoin", "trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole"], "text": "In uncomplicated cases, UTIs are treated with a short course of antibiotics such as nitrofurantoin or trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole."}, {"list": ["Resistance"], "text": "Resistance to many of the antibiotics used to treat this condition is increasing."}, {"list": ["intravenous"], "text": "In complicated cases, a longer course or intravenous antibiotics may be needed."}, {"text": "If symptoms do not improve in two or three days, further diagnostic testing may be needed."}, {"list": ["Phenazopyridine"], "text": "Phenazopyridine may help with symptoms."}, {"text": "In those who have bacteria or white blood cells in their urine but have no symptoms, antibiotics are generally not needed, although during pregnancy is an exception."}, {"text": "In those with frequent infections, a short course of antibiotics may be taken as soon as symptoms begin or long-term antibiotics may be used as a preventative measure."}, {"text": "About 150 million people developed a urinary tract infection each year."}, {"text": "They are more common in women than men."}, {"text": "In women, they are the most common form of bacterial infection."}, {"text": "Up to 10% of women have a urinary tract infection in a given year and half of women having at least one infection at some point in their lives."}, {"text": "They occur most frequently between the ages of 16 and 35 years."}, {"text": "Recurrences are common."}, {"list": ["Ebers Papyrus"], "text": "Urinary tract infections have been described since ancient times with the first documented description in the Ebers Papyrus dated to c. 1550 BC."}, {"text": "Lower urinary tract infection is also referred to as a bladder infection."}, {"list": ["burning with urination", "vaginal discharge"], "text": "The most common symptoms are burning with urination and having to urinate frequently (or an urge to urinate) in the absence of vaginal discharge and significant pain."}, {"text": "These symptoms may vary from mild to severe and in healthy women last an average of six days."}, {"list": ["pubic bone", "lower back"], "text": "Some pain above the pubic bone or in the lower back may be present.<!"}, {"list": ["pyelonephritis", "flank pain", "fever", "vomiting"], "text": "--> People experiencing an upper urinary tract infection, or pyelonephritis, may experience flank pain, fever, or nausea and vomiting in addition to the classic symptoms of a lower urinary tract infection."}, {"list": ["bloody", "pus in the urine"], "text": "Rarely the urine may appear bloody or contain visible pus in the urine."}, {"list": ["jaundice", "urinary incontinence"], "text": "In young children, the only symptom of a urinary tract infection (UTI) may be a fever.<!-- -->  Because of the lack of more obvious symptoms, when females under the age of two or uncircumcised males less than a year exhibit a fever, a culture of the urine is recommended by many medical associations.<!--  --> Infants may feed poorly, vomit, sleep more, or show signs of jaundice.<!--  --> In older children, new onset urinary incontinence (loss of bladder control) may occur."}, {"list": ["elderly"], "text": "Urinary tract symptoms are frequently lacking in the elderly."}, {"list": ["change in mental status", "sepsis"], "text": "The presentations may be vague with incontinence, a change in mental status, or fatigue as the only symptoms, while some present to a health care provider with sepsis, an infection of the blood, as the first symptoms."}, {"list": ["dementia"], "text": "Diagnosis can be complicated by the fact that many elderly people have preexisting incontinence or dementia."}, {"list": ["dementia"], "text": "It is reasonable to obtain a urine culture in those with signs of systemic infection that may be unable to report urinary symptoms, such as when advanced dementia is present."}, {"list": ["fever", "increased white blood cell count"], "text": "Systemic signs of infection include a fever or increase in temperature of more than from usual, chills, and an increased white blood cell count."}, {"list": ["E. coli\'\'", "Staphylococcus saprophyticus\'\'"], "text": "Uropathogenic E. coli from the gut is the cause of 80–85% of community-acquired urinary tract infections, with Staphylococcus saprophyticus being the cause in 5–10%."}, {"list": ["viral", "fungal"], "text": "Rarely they may be due to viral or fungal infections."}, {"list": ["urinary catheterization"], "text": "Healthcare-associated urinary tract infections (mostly related to urinary catheterization) involve a much broader range of pathogens including: \'\'E."}, {"list": ["Klebsiella\'\'", "Pseudomonas\'\'", "Candida albicans\'\'", "Enterococcus\'\'"], "text": "coli (27%), Klebsiella (11%), Pseudomonas (11%), the fungal pathogen Candida albicans (9%), and Enterococcus\'\' (7%) among others."}, {"list": ["Staphylococcus aureus\'\'"], "text": "Urinary tract infections due to Staphylococcus aureus typically occur secondary to blood-borne infections."}, {"list": ["Chlamydia trachomatis\'\'", "Mycoplasma genitalium\'\'"], "text": "Chlamydia trachomatis and Mycoplasma genitalium can infect the urethra but not the bladder."}, {"list": ["urethritis"], "text": "These infections are usually classified as a urethritis rather than urinary tract infection."}, {"text": "In young sexually active women, sexual activity is the cause of 75–90% of bladder infections, with the risk of infection related to the frequency of sex."}, {"text": "The term \\"honeymoon cystitis\\" has been applied to this phenomenon of frequent UTIs during early marriage."}, {"list": ["post-menopausal", "Spermicide"], "text": "In post-menopausal women, sexual activity does not affect the risk of developing a UTI.<!-- --> Spermicide use, independent of sexual frequency, increases the risk of UTIs."}, {"list": ["Diaphragm"], "text": "Diaphragm use is also associated."}, {"list": ["birth control pills"], "text": "Condom use without spermicide or use of birth control pills does not increase the risk of uncomplicated urinary tract infection."}, {"list": ["urethra", "anus"], "text": "Women are more prone to UTIs than men because, in females, the urethra is much shorter and closer to the anus."}, {"list": ["menopause", "vaginal flora"], "text": "As a woman\'s estrogen levels decrease with menopause, her risk of urinary tract infections increases due to the loss of protective vaginal flora."}, {"list": ["vaginal atrophy"], "text": "Additionally, vaginal atrophy that can sometimes occur after menopause is associated with recurrent urinary tract infections."}, {"list": ["chronic prostatitis/chronic pelvic pain syndrome", "chronic bacterial prostatitis", "asymptomatic inflammatory prostatitis"], "text": "Chronic prostatitis in the forms of chronic prostatitis/chronic pelvic pain syndrome and chronic bacterial prostatitis (not acute bacterial prostatitis or asymptomatic inflammatory prostatitis) may cause recurrent urinary tract infections in males.<!-- --> Risk of infections increases as males age.<!-- --> While bacteria is commonly present in the urine of older males this does not appear to affect the risk of urinary tract infections."}, {"list": ["Urinary catheterization", "bacteriuria"], "text": "Urinary catheterization increases the risk for urinary tract infections.<!-- --> The risk of bacteriuria (bacteria in the urine) is between three and six percent per day and prophylactic antibiotics are not effective in decreasing symptomatic infections."}, {"list": ["aseptic technique"], "text": "The risk of an associated infection can be decreased by catheterizing only when necessary, using aseptic technique for insertion, and maintaining unobstructed closed drainage of the catheter."}, {"list": ["scuba divers", "condom catheters", "dry suits"], "text": "Male scuba divers using condom catheters and female divers using external catching devices for their dry suits are also susceptible to urinary tract infections."}, {"list": ["diabetes", "uncircumcised", "large prostate"], "text": "A predisposition for bladder infections may run in families.<!-- --> Other risk factors include diabetes, being uncircumcised, and having a large prostate."}, {"list": ["vesicoureteral reflux", "urine", "bladder", "ureters", "kidneys", "constipation"], "text": "In children UTIs are associated with vesicoureteral reflux (an abnormal movement of urine from the bladder into ureters or kidneys) and constipation."}, {"list": ["spinal cord injury", "voiding"], "text": "Persons with spinal cord injury are at increased risk for urinary tract infection in part because of chronic use of catheter, and in part because of voiding dysfunction."}, {"text": "It is the most common cause of infection in this population, as well as the most common cause of hospitalization."}, {"list": ["cranberry juice"], "text": "Additionally, use of cranberry juice or cranberry supplement appears to be ineffective in prevention and treatment in this population."}, {"list": ["bacteria"], "text": "The bacteria that cause urinary tract infections typically enter the bladder via the urethra."}, {"list": ["lymph"], "text": "However, infection may also occur via the blood or lymph.<!-- --> It is believed that the bacteria are usually transmitted to the urethra from the bowel, with females at greater risk due to their anatomy.<!-- --> After gaining entry to the bladder, \'\'E."}, {"list": ["biofilm"], "text": "Coli\'\' are able to attach to the bladder wall and form a biofilm that resists the body\'s immune response."}, {"text": "In straightforward cases, a diagnosis may be made and treatment given based on symptoms alone without further laboratory confirmation."}, {"list": ["urinalysis", "urinary nitrites", "white blood cells", "leukocyte esterase"], "text": "In complicated or questionable cases, it may be useful to confirm the diagnosis via urinalysis, looking for the presence of urinary nitrites, white blood cells (leukocytes), or leukocyte esterase."}, {"list": ["urine microscopy", "red blood cells", "culture", "colony-forming units"], "text": "Another test, urine microscopy, looks for the presence of red blood cells, white blood cells, or bacteria.<!-- --> Urine culture is deemed positive if it shows a bacterial colony count of greater than or equal to 10 3 colony-forming units per mL of a typical urinary tract organism.<!-- --> Antibiotic sensitivity can also be tested with these cultures, making them useful in the selection of antibiotic treatment.<!-- --> However, women with negative cultures may still improve with antibiotic treatment."}, {"text": "As symptoms can be vague and without reliable tests for urinary tract infections, diagnosis can be difficult in the elderly."}, {"text": "A urinary tract infection may involve only the lower urinary tract, in which case it is known as a bladder infection."}, {"list": ["asymptomatic bacteriuria"], "text": "Alternatively, it may involve the upper urinary tract, in which case it is known as pyelonephritis.<!-- --> If the urine contains significant bacteria but there are no symptoms, the condition is known as asymptomatic bacteriuria."}, {"list": ["diabetes mellitus", "immunocompromised"], "text": "If a urinary tract infection involves the upper tract, and the person has diabetes mellitus, is pregnant, is male, or immunocompromised, it is considered complicated."}, {"list": ["premenopausal"], "text": "Otherwise if a woman is healthy and premenopausal it is considered uncomplicated."}, {"text": "In children when a urinary tract infection is associated with a fever, it is deemed to be an upper urinary tract infection."}, {"list": ["suprapubic aspirations", "World Health Organization", "American Academy of Pediatrics", "renal ultrasound", "voiding cystourethrogram", "National Institute for Health and Care Excellence"], "text": "To make the diagnosis of a urinary tract infection in children, a positive urinary culture is required.<!-- --> Contamination poses a frequent challenge depending on the method of collection used, thus a cutoff of 10 5 CFU/mL is used for a \\"clean-catch\\" mid stream sample, 10 4 CFU/mL is used for catheter-obtained specimens, and 10 2 CFU/mL is used for suprapubic aspirations (a sample drawn directly from the bladder with a needle).<!-- --> The use of \\"urine bags\\" to collect samples is discouraged by the World Health Organization due to the high rate of contamination when cultured, and catheterization is preferred in those not toilet trained.<!-- --> Some, such as the American Academy of Pediatrics recommends renal ultrasound and voiding cystourethrogram (watching a person\'s urethra and urinary bladder with real time x-rays while they urinate) in all children less than two years old who have had a urinary tract infection.<!-- --> However, because there is a lack of effective treatment if problems are found, others such as the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence only recommends routine imaging in those less than six months old or who have unusual findings."}, {"list": ["cervicitis", "cervix", "vaginitis", "vagina", "Chlamydia trachomatis\'\'", "Neisseria gonorrheae\'\'"], "text": "In women with cervicitis (inflammation of the cervix) or vaginitis (inflammation of the vagina) and in young men with UTI symptoms, a Chlamydia trachomatis or Neisseria gonorrheae infection may be the cause."}, {"list": ["urethritis"], "text": "These infections are typically classified as a urethritis rather than a urinary tract infection."}, {"list": ["yeast infection"], "text": "Vaginitis may also be due to a yeast infection."}, {"list": ["Interstitial cystitis"], "text": "Interstitial cystitis (chronic pain in the bladder) may be considered for people who experience multiple episodes of UTI symptoms but urine cultures remain negative and not improved with antibiotics."}, {"list": ["Prostatitis", "prostate"], "text": "Prostatitis (inflammation of the prostate) may also be considered in the differential diagnosis."}, {"list": ["Hemorrhagic cystitis", "blood in the urine", "radiation therapy"], "text": "Hemorrhagic cystitis, characterized by blood in the urine, can occur secondary to a number of causes including: infections, radiation therapy, underlying cancer, medications and toxins."}, {"list": ["chemotherapeutic agent", "cyclophosphamide"], "text": "Medications that commonly cause this problem include the chemotherapeutic agent cyclophosphamide with rates of 2 to 40%."}, {"list": ["Eosinophilic cystitis", "eosinophiles"], "text": "Eosinophilic cystitis is a rare condition where eosinophiles are present in the bladder wall."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms are similar to a bladder infection."}, {"list": ["food allergies", "infections"], "text": "Its cause is not entirely clear; however, it may be linked to food allergies, infections, and medications among others."}, {"list": ["defecating"], "text": "A number of measures have not been confirmed to affect UTI frequency including: urinating immediately after intercourse, the type of underwear used, personal hygiene methods used after urinating or defecating, or whether a person typically bathes or showers."}, {"list": ["tampon", "douching"], "text": "There is similarly a lack of evidence surrounding the effect of holding one\'s urine, tampon use, and douching."}, {"list": ["spermicide", "diaphragm"], "text": "In those with frequent urinary tract infections who use spermicide or a diaphragm as a method of contraception, they are advised to use alternative methods."}, {"list": ["benign prostatic hyperplasia"], "text": "In those with benign prostatic hyperplasia urinating in a sitting position appears to improve bladder emptying which might decrease urinary tract infections in this group."}, {"text": "Using urinary catheters as little and as short of time as possible and appropriate care of the catheter when used prevents infections."}, {"text": "They should be inserted using sterile technique in hospital however non-sterile technique may be appropriate in those who self catheterize."}, {"text": "The urinary catheter set up should also be kept sealed."}, {"text": "Evidence does not support a significant decrease in risk when silver-alloy catheters are used."}, {"text": "For those with recurrent infections, taking a short course of antibiotics when each infection occurs is associated with the lowest antibiotic use."}, {"text": "A prolonged course of daily antibiotics is also effective."}, {"list": ["nitrofurantoin", "trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole"], "text": "Medications frequently used include nitrofurantoin and trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole (TMP/SMX)."}, {"list": ["Methenamine", "formaldehyde"], "text": "Methenamine is another agent used for this purpose as in the bladder where the acidity is low it produces formaldehyde to which resistance does not develop."}, {"list": ["antibiotic resistance"], "text": "Some recommend against prolonged use due to concerns of antibiotic resistance."}, {"text": "In cases where infections are related to intercourse, taking antibiotics afterwards may be useful."}, {"list": ["topical", "estrogen", "pessaries"], "text": "In post-menopausal women, topical vaginal estrogen has been found to reduce recurrence.<!-- --> As opposed to topical creams, the use of vaginal estrogen from pessaries has not been as useful as low dose antibiotics."}, {"text": "Antibiotics following short term urinary catheterization decreases the subsequent risk of a bladder infection."}, {"list": ["vaccines"], "text": "A number of vaccines are in development as of 2011."}, {"list": ["preventive"], "text": "The evidence that preventive antibiotics decrease urinary tract infections in children is poor."}, {"list": ["chronic kidney disease"], "text": "However recurrent UTIs are a rare cause of further kidney problems if there are no underlying abnormalities of the kidneys, resulting in less than a third of a percent (0.33%) of chronic kidney disease in adults."}, {"text": "Whether routine circumcisions prevents UTIs has not been well studied as of 2011."}, {"list": ["cranberry"], "text": "Some research suggests that cranberry (juice or capsules) may decrease the number of UTIs in those with frequent infections."}, {"list": ["Cochrane review"], "text": "A Cochrane review concluded that the benefit, if it exists, is small."}, {"text": "Long-term tolerance is also an issue with gastrointestinal upset occurring in more than 30%."}, {"text": "Cranberry juice is thus not currently recommended for this indication."}, {"list": ["probiotics"], "text": "As of 2015, probiotics require further study to determine if they are beneficial."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "The mainstay of treatment is antibiotics."}, {"list": ["Phenazopyridine"], "text": "Phenazopyridine is occasionally prescribed during the first few days in addition to antibiotics to help with the burning and urgency sometimes felt during a bladder infection."}, {"list": ["methemoglobinemia", "methemoglobin"], "text": "However, it is not routinely recommended due to safety concerns with its use, specifically an elevated risk of methemoglobinemia (higher than normal level of methemoglobin in the blood)."}, {"list": ["Acetaminophen"], "text": "Acetaminophen (paracetamol) may be used for fevers."}, {"text": "There is no good evidence for the use of cranberry products for treating current infections."}, {"text": "Those who have bacteria in the urine but no symptoms should not generally be treated with antibiotics."}, {"text": "This includes those who are old, those with spinal cord injuries, and those who have urinary catheters."}, {"text": "Pregnancy is an exception and it is recommended that women take 7 days of antibiotics."}, {"list": ["pyelonephritis", "low birth weight", "preterm birth"], "text": "If not treated it causes up to 30% of mothers to develop pyelonephritis and increases risk of low birth weight and preterm birth."}, {"list": ["diabetes mellitus"], "text": "Some also support treatment of those with diabetes mellitus and treatment before urinary tract procedures which will likely cause bleeding."}, {"text": "Uncomplicated infections can be diagnosed and treated based on symptoms alone."}, {"list": ["trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole", "nitrofurantoin", "fosfomycin"], "text": "Antibiotics taken by mouth such as trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole (TMP/SMX), nitrofurantoin, or fosfomycin are typically first line."}, {"list": ["Cephalosporins", "amoxicillin/clavulanic acid", "fluoroquinolone"], "text": "Cephalosporins, amoxicillin/clavulanic acid, or a fluoroquinolone may also be used."}, {"list": ["resistance"], "text": "However, resistance to fluoroquinolones among the bacterial that cause urinary infections has been increasing."}, {"text": "The FDA recommends against the use of fluoroquinolones when other options are available due to higher risks of serious side effects."}, {"text": "These medications substantially shorten the time to recovery with all being equally effective."}, {"text": "A three-day treatment with trimethoprim, TMP/SMX, or a fluoroquinolone is usually sufficient, whereas nitrofurantoin requires 5–7 days."}, {"text": "Fosfomycin may be used as a single dose but has been associated with lower rates of efficacy."}, {"text": "With treatment, symptoms should improve within 36 hours."}, {"text": "About 50% of people will recover without treatment within a few days or weeks."}, {"text": "Fluoroquinolones are not recommended as a first treatment."}, {"list": ["resistance"], "text": "The Infectious Diseases Society of America states this due to the concern of generating resistance to this class of medication."}, {"list": ["Amoxicillin-clavulanate"], "text": "Amoxicillin-clavulanate appears less effective than other options."}, {"text": "Despite this precaution, some resistance has developed to all of these medications related to their widespread use."}, {"list": ["Trimethoprim"], "text": "Trimethoprim alone is deemed to be equivalent to TMP/SMX in some countries."}, {"text": "For simple UTIs, children often respond to a three-day course of antibiotics."}, {"text": "Women with recurrent simple UTIs may benefit from self-treatment upon occurrence of symptoms with medical follow-up only if the initial treatment fails."}, {"text": "Complicated UTIs are more difficult to treat and usually requires more aggressive evaluation, treatment and follow-up."}, {"text": "It may require identifying and addressing the underlying complication."}, {"list": ["antibiotic resistance"], "text": "Increasing antibiotic resistance is causing concern about the future of treating those with complicated and recurrent UTI."}, {"list": ["Pyelonephritis", "intravenous"], "text": "Pyelonephritis is treated more aggressively than a simple bladder infection using either a longer course of oral antibiotics or intravenous antibiotics."}, {"list": ["ciprofloxacin", "ceftriaxone"], "text": "Seven days of the oral fluoroquinolone ciprofloxacin is typically used in areas where the resistance rate is less than 10%.<!-- --> If the local resistance rates are greater than 10%, a dose of intravenous ceftriaxone is often prescribed."}, {"list": ["amoxicillin/clavulanate"], "text": "Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole or amoxicillin/clavulanate orally for 14 days is another reasonable option."}, {"text": "In those who exhibit more severe symptoms, admission to a hospital for ongoing antibiotics may be needed."}, {"list": ["urinary obstruction", "kidney stone"], "text": "Complications such as urinary obstruction from a kidney stone may be considered if symptoms do not improve following two or three days of treatment."}, {"text": "Urinary tract infections are the most frequent bacterial infection in women."}, {"text": "They occur most frequently between the ages of 16 and 35 years, with 10% of women getting an infection yearly and more than 40–60% having an infection at some point in their lives."}, {"text": "Recurrences are common, with nearly half of people getting a second infection within a year.<!-- --> Urinary tract infections occur four times more frequently in females than males."}, {"text": "Pyelonephritis occurs between 20–30 times less frequently."}, {"list": ["hospital acquired infections"], "text": "They are the most common cause of hospital acquired infections accounting for approximately 40%."}, {"text": "Rates of asymptomatic bacteria in the urine increase with age from two to seven percent in women of child bearing age to as high as 50% in elderly women in care homes."}, {"text": "Rates of asymptomatic bacteria in the urine among men over 75 are between 7-10%."}, {"text": "Asymptomatic bacteria in the urine occurs in 2% to 10% of pregnancies."}, {"text": "Urinary tract infections may affect 10% of people during childhood."}, {"text": "Among children urinary tract infections are the most common in uncircumcised males less than three months of age, followed by females less than one year."}, {"text": "Estimates of frequency among children, however, vary widely."}, {"text": "In a group of children with a fever, ranging in age between birth and two years, two to 20% were diagnosed with a UTI."}, {"text": "In the United States, urinary tract infections account for nearly seven million office visits, a million emergency department visits, and one hundred thousand hospitalizations every year."}, {"text": "The cost of these infections is significant both in terms of lost time at work and costs of medical care.<!-- --> In the United States the direct cost of treatment is estimated at 1.6 billion USD yearly."}, {"list": ["Ebers Papyrus"], "text": "Urinary tract infections have been described since ancient times with the first documented description in the Ebers Papyrus dated to c. 1550 BC. It was described by the Egyptians as \\"sending forth heat from the bladder\\"."}, {"list": ["bloodletting"], "text": "Effective treatment did not occur until the development and availability of antibiotics in the 1930s before which time herbs, bloodletting and rest were recommended."}, {"list": ["pregnancy", "progesterone"], "text": "Urinary tract infections are more concerning in pregnancy due to the increased risk of kidney infections.<!-- --> During pregnancy, high progesterone levels elevate the risk of decreased muscle tone of the ureters and bladder, which leads to a greater likelihood of reflux, where urine flows back up the ureters and towards the kidneys.<!-- --> While pregnant women do not have an increased risk of asymptomatic bacteriuria, if bacteriuria is present they do have a 25–40% risk of a kidney infection."}, {"list": ["Cephalexin", "nitrofurantoin"], "text": "Thus if urine testing shows signs of an infection—even in the absence of symptoms—treatment is recommended.<!-- --> Cephalexin or nitrofurantoin are typically used because they are generally considered safe in pregnancy."}, {"list": ["premature birth", "pre-eclampsia", "high blood pressure", "seizures"], "text": "A kidney infection during pregnancy may result in premature birth or pre-eclampsia (a state of high blood pressure and kidney dysfunction during pregnancy that can lead to seizures)."}, {"text": "Some women have UTIs that keep coming back in pregnancy and currently there is not enough research on how to best treat these infections."}]', '{}', '{}', '{}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c4/Pyuria.JPG", "file": "File:Pyuria.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Pyuria.JPG/300px-Pyuria.JPG"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c5/Cystitis.webm", "file": "File:Cystitis.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Cystitis.webm/300px-Cystitis.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/29/Pyuria2011.JPG", "file": "File:Pyuria2011.JPG", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Pyuria2011.JPG/300px-Pyuria2011.JPG"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e5/Bladder_Infection.png", "file": "File:Bladder Infection.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Bladder_Infection.png/300px-Bladder_Infection.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9b/Bacteriuria_pyuria_4.jpg", "file": "Image:Bacteriuria pyuria 4.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Bacteriuria_pyuria_4.jpg/300px-Bacteriuria_pyuria_4.jpg"}]');
INSERT INTO `entity_data` (`id`, `entity`, `name`, `caption`, `type`, `symptoms`, `diagnosis`, `causes`, `parse_data`, `prevention`, `complications`, `medication`, `images`) VALUES
(34, 'whooping_cough', 'Pertussis', 'A%20young%20boy%20coughing%20due%20to%20pertussis.', 'Infectious%20disease', '["Runny nose", "fever", "cough"]', '{"desc": "Nasopharyngeal swab", "list": ["Nasopharyngeal swab"]}', '{"desc": "Bordetella pertussis (spread through the air)", "list": ["Bordetella pertussis\'\'", "spread through the air"]}', '[{"list": ["bacterial disease"], "text": "Pertussis (also known as whooping cough or 100-day cough) is a highly contagious bacterial disease."}, {"list": ["common cold", "runny nose", "fever", "cough"], "text": "Initially, symptoms are usually similar to those of the common cold with a runny nose, fever, and mild cough."}, {"text": "This is then followed by weeks of severe coughing fits."}, {"text": "Following a fit of coughing, a high-pitched whoop sound or gasp may occur as the person breathes in. The coughing may last for 10 or more weeks, hence the phrase \\"100-day cough\\"."}, {"list": ["break ribs", "very tired"], "text": "A person may cough so hard that they vomit, break ribs, or become very tired from the effort."}, {"list": ["periods where they do not breathe"], "text": "Children less than one year old may have little or no cough and instead have periods where they do not breathe."}, {"text": "The time between infection and the onset of symptoms is usually seven to ten days."}, {"text": "Disease may occur in those who have been vaccinated, but symptoms are typically milder."}, {"list": ["Bordetella pertussis\'\'"], "text": "Pertussis is caused by the bacterium Bordetella pertussis."}, {"list": ["airborne disease"], "text": "It is an airborne disease which spreads easily through the coughs and sneezes of an infected person."}, {"text": "People are infectious to others from the start of symptoms until about three weeks into the coughing fits."}, {"list": ["antibiotics"], "text": "Those treated with antibiotics are no longer infectious after five days."}, {"list": ["sample from the back of the nose and throat"], "text": "Diagnosis is by collecting a sample from the back of the nose and throat."}, {"list": ["culture", "polymerase chain reaction"], "text": "This sample can then be tested by either culture or by polymerase chain reaction."}, {"list": ["vaccination", "pertussis vaccine"], "text": "Prevention is mainly by vaccination with the pertussis vaccine."}, {"text": "Initial immunization is recommended between six and eight weeks of age, with four doses to be given in the first two years of life."}, {"text": "The vaccine becomes less effective over time, with additional doses often recommended for older children and adults."}, {"text": "Antibiotics may be used to prevent the disease in those who have been exposed and are at risk of severe disease."}, {"text": "In those with the disease, antibiotics are useful if started within three weeks of the initial symptoms, but otherwise have little effect in most people."}, {"text": "In children less than one year old and among those who are pregnant, they are recommended within six weeks of symptom onset."}, {"list": ["erythromycin", "azithromycin", "clarithromycin", "trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole"], "text": "Antibiotics used include erythromycin, azithromycin, clarithromycin, or trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole."}, {"text": "Evidence to support interventions, other than antibiotics, for the cough is poor."}, {"text": "Many children less than a year of age require hospitalization."}, {"text": "An estimated 16.3 million people worldwide were infected in 2015."}, {"list": ["developing world"], "text": "Most cases occur in the developing world, and people of all ages may be affected."}, {"text": "In 2015, it resulted in 58,700 deaths – down from 138,000 deaths in 1990."}, {"text": "Nearly 0.5% of infected children less than one year of age die."}, {"text": "Outbreaks of the disease were first described in the 16th century."}, {"text": "The bacterium that causes the infection was discovered in 1906."}, {"text": "The pertussis vaccine became available in the 1940s."}, {"list": ["paroxysmal", "fainting", "vomiting"], "text": "The classic symptoms of pertussis are a paroxysmal cough, inspiratory whoop, and fainting, or vomiting after coughing."}, {"list": ["subconjunctival hemorrhages", "rib fractures", "urinary incontinence", "hernias", "vertebral artery dissection"], "text": "The cough from pertussis has been documented to cause subconjunctival hemorrhages, rib fractures, urinary incontinence, hernias, and vertebral artery dissection."}, {"list": ["pleura", "pneumothorax"], "text": "Violent coughing can cause the pleura to rupture, leading to a pneumothorax."}, {"text": "Vomiting after a coughing spell or an inspiratory whooping sound on coughing, almost doubles the likelihood that the illness is pertussis."}, {"list": ["emesis"], "text": "The absence of a paroxysmal cough or posttussive emesis, though, makes it almost half as likely."}, {"list": ["runny nose"], "text": "The illness usually starts with mild respiratory symptoms include mild coughing, sneezing, or a runny nose."}, {"list": ["catarrhal"], "text": "This is known as the catarrhal stage."}, {"list": ["paroxysmal"], "text": "After one to two weeks, the coughing classically develops into uncontrollable fits, each with five to ten forceful coughs, followed by a high-pitched \\"whoop\\" sound in younger children, or a gasping sound in older children, as the person tries to inhale (paroxysmal stage)."}, {"text": "Coughing fits can occur on their own or can be triggered by yawning, stretching, laughing, eating, or yelling; they usually occur in groups, with multiple episodes on an hourly basis throughout the day."}, {"text": "This stage usually lasts two to eight weeks, or sometimes longer."}, {"text": "A gradual transition then occurs to the convalescent stage, which usually lasts one to four weeks."}, {"text": "This stage is marked by a decrease in paroxysms of coughing, both in frequency and severity, and a cessation of vomiting."}, {"text": "A tendency to produce the \\"whooping\\" sound after coughing may remain for a considerable period after the disease itself has cleared up."}, {"list": ["time between exposure and the development of symptoms"], "text": "The time between exposure and the development of symptoms is on average 7–14 days (range 6–20 days), rarely as long as 42 days."}, {"list": ["Bordetella pertussis\'\'"], "text": "Pertussis is caused by the bacterium Bordetella pertussis.<!"}, {"list": ["airborne disease"], "text": "--> It is an airborne disease that spreads easily through the coughs and sneezes of an infected person."}, {"text": "Uncertainties have existed of \'\'B."}, {"list": ["zoonotic disease", "virulent", "agar"], "text": "pertussis\'\' and whooping cough as a zoonotic disease since around 1910 but in the 1930s, knowledge was gained that the bacteria lost their virulent power when repeatedly spread on agar media."}, {"text": "This explained the difficulties to reproduce results from different studies as the pre-inoculating handlings of the bacteria were not standardized among scientists."}, {"list": ["primate"], "text": "Today it is established that at least some primate species are highly susceptible to \'\'B."}, {"list": ["incidence"], "text": "pertussis\'\' and develop clinical whooping cough in high incidence when exposed to low inoculation doses."}, {"list": ["gorillas"], "text": "The bacteria may be present in wild animal populations, but this is not confirmed by laboratory diagnosis, although whooping cough is known among wild gorillas."}, {"list": ["zoos"], "text": "Several zoos also have a long-standing custom of vaccinating their primates against whooping cough."}, {"text": "It acts primarily via its pertussis toxin but also via invasion of tissues and alveolar macrophages."}, {"text": "B. pertussis attaches to the cilia of respiratory epithelial cells, where it produces cilia-paralyzing toxins, and causes inflammation of the respiratory tract, thereby interfering with the \\"mucociliary escalator\\" by which pulmonary secretions (i.e., mucus) are cleared."}, {"text": "A physician\'s overall impression is most effective in initially making the diagnosis."}, {"text": "Single factors are much less useful."}, {"list": ["culturing", "Bordet-Gengou medium", "polymerase chain reaction", "direct fluorescent antibody", "serological", "complement fixation test"], "text": "Methods used in laboratory diagnosis include culturing of nasopharyngeal swabs on a nutrient medium (Bordet-Gengou medium), polymerase chain reaction (PCR), direct fluorescent antibody (DFA), and serological methods (e.g. complement fixation test)."}, {"text": "The bacteria can be recovered from the person only during the first three weeks of illness, rendering culturing and DFA useless after this period, although PCR may have some limited usefulness for an additional three weeks."}, {"list": ["pertussis toxin"], "text": "Serology may be used for adults and adolescents who have already been infected for several weeks to determine whether antibody against pertussis toxin or another virulence factor of \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\' is present at high levels in the blood of the person."}, {"text": "By this stage, they have been contagious for some weeks and may have spread the infection to many people."}, {"text": "Because of this, adults, who are not in great danger from pertussis, are increasingly being encouraged to be vaccinated."}, {"list": ["B. parapertussis\'\'"], "text": "A similar, milder disease is caused by B. parapertussis."}, {"list": ["vaccination"], "text": "The primary method of prevention for pertussis is vaccination."}, {"text": "Evidence is insufficient to determine the effectiveness of antibiotics in those who have been exposed, but are without symptoms."}, {"text": "Preventive antibiotics, however, are still frequently used in those who have been exposed and are at high risk of severe disease (such as infants)."}, {"list": ["Pertussis vaccines", "World Health Organization", "Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"], "text": "Pertussis vaccines are effective at preventing illness and are recommended for routine use by the World Health Organization and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention."}, {"text": "The vaccine saved an estimated half a million lives in 2002."}, {"list": ["acellular"], "text": "The multicomponent acellular pertussis vaccine is 71–85% effective, with greater effectiveness for more severe strains."}, {"text": "Despite widespread vaccination, however, pertussis has persisted in vaccinated populations and is today \\"one of the most common vaccine-preventable diseases in Western countries\\"."}, {"text": "The 21st-century resurgences in pertussis infections are attributed to a combination of waning immunity and bacterial mutations that elude vaccines."}, {"text": "Immunization does not confer lifelong immunity; a 2011 CDC study indicated that protection may only last three to six years."}, {"text": "This covers childhood, which is the time of greatest exposure and greatest risk of death from pertussis."}, {"text": "An effect of widespread immunization on society has been the shift of reported infections from children aged 1–9 years to infants, adolescents, and adults, with adolescents and adults acting as reservoirs for \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\' and infecting infants with fewer than three doses of vaccine."}, {"list": ["natural immunity"], "text": "Infection induces incomplete natural immunity that wanes over time."}, {"text": "A 2005 study said estimates of the duration of infection-acquired immunity range from 7 to 20 years and the different results could be the result of differences in levels of circulating \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\', surveillance systems, and case definitions used."}, {"text": "The study said protective immunity after vaccination wanes after 4–12 years."}, {"text": "Vaccination exemption laws appear to increase cases."}, {"text": "Both WHO and the CDC found that the acellular pertussis vaccines were effective at prevention of the disease, but had a limited impact on infection and transmission, meaning that vaccinated people could act as asymptomatic reservoirs of infection."}, {"list": ["erythromycin", "clarithromycin", "azithromycin"], "text": "The antibiotics erythromycin, clarithromycin, or azithromycin are typically the recommended treatment."}, {"list": ["macrolides"], "text": "Newer macrolides are frequently recommended due to lower rates of side effects."}, {"list": ["Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole", "pyloric stenosis"], "text": "Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (TMP/SMX) may be used in those with allergies to first-line agents or in infants who have a risk of pyloric stenosis from macrolides."}, {"text": "A reasonable guideline is to treat people age >1 year within 3 weeks of cough onset and infants age <1 year and pregnant women within 6 weeks of cough onset."}, {"text": "If the person is diagnosed late, antibiotics will not alter the course of the illness, and even without antibiotics, they should no longer be spreading pertussis."}, {"text": "Antibiotics when used early decrease the duration of infectiousness, and thus prevent spread."}, {"text": "Short-term antibiotics (azithromycin for 3–5 days) are as effective as long-term treatment (erythromycin 10–14 days) in eliminating \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\' with fewer and less severe side effects."}, {"text": "People with pertussis are infectious from the beginning of the catarrhal stage (a runny nose, sneezing, low-grade fever, symptoms of the common cold) through the third week after the onset of paroxysms (multiple, rapid coughs) or until 5 days after the start of effective antimicrobial treatment."}, {"list": ["cough"], "text": "Effective treatments of the cough associated with this condition have not been developed."}, {"list": ["Disability-adjusted life year", "pneumonia", "bronchitis", "encephalopathy", "earache", "seizures", "immune system", "apneas"], "text": "[[File:Pertussis world map - DALY - WHO2004.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Disability-adjusted life year for pertussis per 100,000 inhabitants as of 2004.Common complications include pneumonia, bronchitis, encephalopathy, earache, and seizures. Most healthy older children and adults fully recover, but those with comorbid conditions have a higher risk of morbidity and mortality.Infection in newborns is particularly severe. Pertussis is fatal in an estimated 1.6% of hospitalized US infants under one year of age. First-year infants are also more likely to develop complications, such as: pneumonia (20%), encephalopathy (0.3%), seizures (1%), failure to thrive, and death (1%) —perhaps due to the ability of the bacterium to suppress the immune system. Pertussis can cause severe paroxysm-induced cerebral hypoxia, and 50% of infants admitted to hospital suffer apneas. Reported fatalities from pertussis in infants increased substantially from 1990 to 2010."}, {"list": ["DTaP", "incidence", "Canada", "Toronto", "Australia"], "text": "Whooping cough world map-Deaths per million persons-WHO2012.svg was likely much higher. After vaccinations were introduced in the 1940s, pertussis incidence fell dramatically to approximately 1,000 by 1976. Incidence rates have increased since 1980. In 2015, rates in the United States were 20,762 people. Pertussis is the only vaccine-preventable disease that is associated with increasing deaths in the U.S. The number of deaths increased from four in 1996 to 17 in 2001, almost all of which were infants under one year. In Canada, the number of pertussis infections has varied between 2,000 and 10,000 reported cases each year over the last ten years, and it is the most common vaccine-preventable illness in Toronto. In 2009 Australia reported an average of 10,000 cases a year, and the number of cases had increased. In the U.S. pertussis in adults has increased significantly since about 2004."}, {"text": "In 2010 ten infants in California died, and health authorities declared an epidemic encompassing 9,120 cases."}, {"text": "They found that doctors had failed to correctly diagnose the infants\' condition during several visits."}, {"text": "Statistical analysis identified significant overlap in communities with a cluster of nonmedical child exemptions and cases."}, {"text": "The number of exemptions varied widely among communities, but tended to be highly clustered."}, {"text": "In some schools, more than three-fourths of parents filed for vaccination exemptions."}, {"text": "The data suggest vaccine refusal based on nonmedical reasons and personal belief exacerbated the outbreak."}, {"text": "Other factors included reduced duration of the current vaccine and that most vaccinated adults and older children had not received a booster shot."}, {"text": "In April and May 2012 pertussis was declared to be at epidemic levels in Washington, with 3,308 cases."}, {"text": "In December 2012 Vermont declared an epidemic of 522 cases."}, {"text": "Wisconsin had the highest incidence rate, with 3,877 cases, although it did not make an official epidemic declaration."}, {"list": ["Jules Bordet", "Octave Gengou"], "text": "B. pertussis was discovered in 1906 by Jules Bordet and Octave Gengou, who also developed the first serology and vaccine."}, {"text": "Efforts to develop an inactivated whole-cell vaccine began soon after \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\' was cultured that year."}, {"list": ["Louis W. Sauer", "Evanston Hospital"], "text": "In the 1920s, Louis W. Sauer developed a weak vaccine for whooping cough at Evanston Hospital (Evanston, IL)."}, {"text": "In 1925 Danish physician Thorvald Madsen was the first to test a whole-cell vaccine on a wide scale."}, {"list": ["Faroe Islands"], "text": "Madsen used the vaccine to control outbreaks in the Faroe Islands in the North Sea."}, {"list": ["Atlanta, Georgia,", "Leila Denmark"], "text": "In 1932 an outbreak of whooping cough hit Atlanta, Georgia, prompting pediatrician Leila Denmark to begin her study of the disease."}, {"list": ["Journal of the American Medical Association", "Emory University", "Eli Lilly & Company"], "text": "Over the next six years her work was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association, and in partnership with Emory University and Eli Lilly & Company, she developed the first pertussis vaccine."}, {"list": ["Grace Eldering", "Loney Gordon", "Pearl Kendrick", "diphtheria", "tetanus"], "text": "In 1942 American scientists Grace Eldering, Loney Gordon, and Pearl Kendrick combined the whole-cell pertussis vaccine with diphtheria and tetanus toxoids to generate the first DTP combination vaccine."}, {"list": ["strep throat", "leukocytosis"], "text": "To minimize the frequent side effects caused by the pertussis component, Japanese scientist Yuji Sato developed an acellular vaccine consisting of purified haemagglutinins (HAs: filamentous strep throat and leukocytosis-promoting-factor HA), which are secreted by \'\'B."}, {"text": "pertussis\'\'."}, {"text": "Sato\'s acellular pertussis vaccine was used in Japan starting in 1981."}, {"text": "Later versions of the acellular vaccine in other countries consisted of additional defined components of \'\'B."}, {"list": ["DTaP"], "text": "pertussis\'\' and were often part of the DTaP combination vaccine."}, {"list": ["encephalopathy"], "text": "During the 1970s and 1980s, a controversy erupted related to the question of whether the whole-cell pertussis component caused permanent brain injury in rare cases, called pertussis vaccine encephalopathy."}, {"text": "Despite this allegation, doctors recommended the vaccine due to the overwhelming public health benefit, because the claimed rate was very low (one case per 310,000 immunizations, or about 50 cases out of the 15 million immunizations each year in the United States), and the risk of death from the disease was high (pertussis killed thousands of Americans each year before the vaccine was introduced)."}, {"text": "No studies showed a causal connection, and later studies showed no connection of any type between the DPT vaccine and permanent brain injury."}, {"list": ["epilepsy"], "text": "The alleged vaccine-induced brain damage proved to be an unrelated condition, infantile epilepsy."}, {"list": ["Journal of the American Medical Association\'\'"], "text": "In 1990, the Journal of the American Medical Association called the connection a \\"myth\\" and \\"nonsense\\"."}, {"list": ["anecdotal reports"], "text": "However, before that point, criticism of the studies showing no connection and a few well-publicized anecdotal reports of permanent disability that were blamed on the DPT vaccine gave rise to 1970s anti-DPT movements."}, {"text": "Negative publicity and fear-mongering caused the immunization rate to fall in several countries, including the UK, Sweden, and Japan."}, {"text": "A dramatic increase in the incidence of pertussis followed."}, {"text": "In the United States, low profit margins and an increase in vaccine-related lawsuits led many manufacturers to stop producing the DPT vaccine by the early 1980s."}, {"list": ["Lea Thompson"], "text": "In 1982, the television documentary DPT: Vaccine Roulette depicted the lives of children whose severe disabilities were incorrectly blamed on the DPT vaccine by reporter Lea Thompson."}, {"list": ["lawsuits"], "text": "The ensuing negative publicity led to many lawsuits against vaccine manufacturers."}, {"list": ["liability insurance"], "text": "By 1985, vaccine manufacturers had difficulty obtaining liability insurance."}, {"text": "The price of DPT vaccine skyrocketed, leading providers to curtail purchases, limiting availability."}, {"text": "Only one manufacturer remained in the US by the end of 1985."}, {"list": ["National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act", "no-fault"], "text": "To correct the situation, Congress in 1986 passed the National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act (NCVIA), which established a federal no-fault system to compensate victims of injury caused by mandated vaccines."}, {"text": "The majority of claims that have been filed through the NCVIA have been related to injuries allegedly caused by the whole-cell DPT vaccine."}, {"text": "The concerns about side effects led Sato to introduce an even safer acellular vaccine for Japan in 1981 that was approved in the US in 1992 for use in the combination DTaP vaccine."}, {"list": ["tetanus", "diphtheria"], "text": "The acellular vaccine has a rate of adverse events similar to that of a Td vaccine (a tetanus-diphtheria vaccine containing no pertussis vaccine)."}]', '{"list": ["Pertussis vaccine"], "conditions": ["Pertussis vaccine"]}', '{"list": ["Vomiting", " broken ribs", " very tired"], "conditions": ["broken ribs", "very tired"]}', '{}', 'null'),
(35, 'yeast_infection', 'Candidiasis', 'Oral%20candidiasis%20%28thrush%29', 'Infectious%20disease', '["White patches or vaginal discharge", "itchy"]', '{}', '{"desc": "Candida (a type of yeast)", "list": ["Candida\'\'", "yeast"]}', '[{"list": ["fungal infection", "Candida\'\'", "yeast"], "text": "Candidiasis is a fungal infection due to any type of Candida (a type of yeast)."}, {"list": ["affects the mouth"], "text": "When it affects the mouth, it is commonly called thrush."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms include white patches on the tongue or other areas of the mouth and throat."}, {"text": "Other symptoms may include soreness and problems swallowing."}, {"list": ["affects the vagina"], "text": "When it affects the vagina, it is commonly called a yeast infection."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms include genital itching, burning, and sometimes a white \\"cottage cheese-like\\" discharge from the vagina."}, {"text": "Less commonly the penis may be affected, resulting in itchiness."}, {"text": "Very rarely, the infection may become invasive, spreading to other parts of the body."}, {"list": ["fevers"], "text": "This may result in fevers along with other symptoms depending on the parts involved."}, {"list": ["Candida albicans\'\'"], "text": "More than 20 types of Candida can cause infection with Candida albicans being the most common."}, {"list": ["weak immune systems"], "text": "Infections of the mouth are most common among children less than one month old, the elderly, and those with weak immune systems."}, {"list": ["HIV/AIDS", "organ transplantation", "diabetes", "corticosteroids"], "text": "Conditions that result in a weak immune system include HIV/AIDS, the medications used after organ transplantation, diabetes, and the use of corticosteroids."}, {"list": ["dentures", "antibiotic"], "text": "Other risks include dentures and following antibiotic therapy."}, {"list": ["pregnancy"], "text": "Vaginal infections occur more commonly during pregnancy, in those with weak immune systems, and following antibiotic use."}, {"list": ["invasive candidiasis", "intensive care unit", "low birth weight infants"], "text": "Risk factors for invasive candidiasis include being in an intensive care unit, following surgery, low birth weight infants, and those with weak immune systems."}, {"list": ["chlorhexidine"], "text": "Efforts to prevent infections of the mouth include the use of chlorhexidine mouth wash in those with poor immune function and washing out the mouth following the use of inhaled steroids."}, {"list": ["probiotics"], "text": "Little evidence supports probiotics for either prevention or treatment even among those with frequent vaginal infections."}, {"list": ["topical", "clotrimazole", "nystatin"], "text": "For infections of the mouth, treatment with topical clotrimazole or nystatin is usually effective."}, {"list": ["fluconazole", "itraconazole", "amphotericin B"], "text": "By mouth or intravenous fluconazole, itraconazole, or amphotericin B may be used if these do not work."}, {"text": "A number of topical antifungal medications may be used for vaginal infections including clotrimazole."}, {"list": ["echinocandin", "caspofungin", "micafungin"], "text": "In those with widespread disease, an echinocandin such as caspofungin or micafungin is used."}, {"text": "A number of weeks of intravenous amphotericin B may be used as an alternative."}, {"text": "In certain groups at very high risk, antifungal medications may be used preventatively."}, {"text": "Infections of the mouth occur in about 6% of babies less than a month old."}, {"list": ["chemotherapy", "AIDS"], "text": "About 20% of those receiving chemotherapy for cancer and 20% of those with AIDS also develop the disease."}, {"text": "About three-quarters of women have at least one yeast infection at some time during their lives."}, {"text": "Widespread disease is rare except in those who have risk factors."}, {"text": "Signs and symptoms of candidiasis vary depending on the area affected."}, {"text": "Most candidal infections result in minimal complications such as redness, itching, and discomfort, though complications may be severe or even fatal if left untreated in certain populations."}, {"list": ["immunocompetent", "oral cavity", "pharynx", "thrush", "esophagus", "vagina", "penis", "gastrointestinal tract", "urinary tract", "respiratory tract"], "text": "In healthy (immunocompetent) persons, candidiasis is usually a localized infection of the skin, fingernails or toenails (onychomycosis), or mucosal membranes, including the oral cavity and pharynx (thrush), esophagus, and the genitalia (vagina, penis, etc.); less commonly in healthy individuals, the gastrointestinal tract, <ref name=\\"pmid24612332\\"> <ref name=\\"SIFO\\"> urinary tract, and respiratory tract are sites of candida infection."}, {"list": ["esophagus", "systemic", "fungemia"], "text": "In immunocompromised individuals, Candida infections in the esophagus occur more frequently than in healthy individuals and have a higher potential of becoming systemic, causing a much more serious condition, a fungemia called candidemia."}, {"list": ["difficulty swallowing", "painful swallowing"], "text": "Symptoms of esophageal candidiasis include difficulty swallowing, painful swallowing, abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting."}, {"text": "Thrush is commonly seen in infants."}, {"text": "It is not considered abnormal in infants unless it lasts longer than a few weeks."}, {"list": ["vulva", "cottage cheese"], "text": "Infection of the vagina or vulva may cause severe itching, burning, soreness, irritation, and a whitish or whitish-gray cottage cheese-like discharge."}, {"list": ["phimosis"], "text": "Symptoms of infection of the male genitalia (balanitis thrush) include red skin around the head of the penis, swelling, irritation, itchiness and soreness of the head of the penis, thick, lumpy discharge under the foreskin, unpleasant odour, difficulty retracting the foreskin (phimosis), and pain when passing urine or during sex."}, {"list": ["anal itching", "gastric ulcers"], "text": "Common symptoms of gastrointestinal candidiasis in healthy individuals are anal itching, belching, bloating, indigestion, nausea, diarrhea, gas, intestinal cramps, vomiting, and gastric ulcers."}, {"list": ["sexually transmissible disease"], "text": "Perianal candidiasis can cause anal itching; the lesion can be erythematous, papular, or ulcerative in appearance, and it is not considered to be a sexually transmissible disease."}, {"list": ["dysbiosis"], "text": "Abnormal proliferation of the candida in the gut may lead to dysbiosis."}, {"list": ["irritable bowel syndrome"], "text": "While it is not yet clear, this alteration may be the source of symptoms generally described as the irritable bowel syndrome, and other gastrointestinal diseases."}, {"list": ["immune system", "microorganisms"], "text": "Candida yeasts are generally present in healthy humans, frequently part of the human body\'s normal oral and intestinal flora, and particularly on the skin; however, their growth is normally limited by the human immune system and by competition of other microorganisms, such as bacteria occupying the same locations in the human body."}, {"text": "Candida requires moisture for growth, notably on the skin."}, {"text": "For example, wearing wet swimwear for long periods of time is believed to be a risk factor."}, {"text": "In extreme cases, superficial infections of the skin or mucous membranes may enter into the bloodstream and cause systemic Candida infections."}, {"list": ["HIV", "AIDS", "mononucleosis", "cancer", "steroids", "stress"], "text": "Factors that increase the risk of candidiasis include HIV/AIDS, mononucleosis, cancer treatments, steroids, stress, antibiotic usage, diabetes, and nutrient deficiency."}, {"list": ["Hormone replacement therapy"], "text": "Hormone replacement therapy and infertility treatments may also be predisposing factors."}, {"text": "Treatment with antibiotics can lead to eliminating the yeast\'s natural competitors for resources in the oral and intestinal flora; thereby increasing the severity of the condition."}, {"text": "A weakened or undeveloped immune system or metabolic illnesses are significant predisposing factors of candidiasis."}, {"text": "Almost 15% of people with weakened immune systems develop a systemic illness caused by Candida species."}, {"list": ["carbohydrates"], "text": "Diets high in simple carbohydrates have been found to affect rates of oral candidiases."}, {"text": "C. albicans was isolated from the vaginas of 19% of apparently healthy women, i.e., those who experienced few or no symptoms of infection."}, {"list": ["douches", "perturb", "vaginal flora", "lactic acid bacteria", "lactobacilli", "inflammation"], "text": "External use of detergents or douches or internal disturbances (hormonal or physiological) can perturb the normal vaginal flora, consisting of lactic acid bacteria, such as lactobacilli, and result in an overgrowth of Candida cells, causing symptoms of infection, such as local inflammation."}, {"text": "Pregnancy and the use of oral contraceptives have been reported as risk factors."}, {"list": ["Diabetes mellitus", "antibiotics"], "text": "Diabetes mellitus and the use of antibiotics are also linked to increased rates of yeast infections."}, {"text": "In penile candidiasis, the causes include sexual intercourse with an infected individual, low immunity, antibiotics, and diabetes."}, {"text": "Male genital yeast infections are less common, but a yeast infection on the penis caused from direct contact via sexual intercourse with an infected partner is not uncommon."}, {"list": ["bacterial vaginosis"], "text": "Symptoms of vaginal candidiasis are also present in the more common bacterial vaginosis; aerobic vaginitis is distinct and should be excluded in the differential diagnosis."}, {"text": "In a 2002 study, only 33% of women who were self-treating for a yeast infection actually had such an infection, while most had either bacterial vaginosis or a mixed-type infection."}, {"text": "Diagnosis of a yeast infection is done either via microscopic examination or culturing."}, {"list": ["microscope slide"], "text": "For identification by light microscopy, a scraping or swab of the affected area is placed on a microscope slide."}, {"list": ["potassium hydroxide"], "text": "A single drop of 10% potassium hydroxide (KOH) solution is then added to the specimen."}, {"list": ["pseudohyphae", "yeast cells"], "text": "The KOH dissolves the skin cells, but leaves the Candida cells intact, permitting visualization of pseudohyphae and budding yeast cells typical of many Candida species."}, {"text": "For the culturing method, a sterile swab is rubbed on the infected skin surface."}, {"text": "The swab is then streaked on a culture medium."}, {"text": "The culture is incubated at 37 °C (98.6 °F) for several days, to allow development of yeast or bacterial colonies."}, {"text": "The characteristics (such as morphology and colour) of the colonies may allow initial diagnosis of the organism causing disease symptoms."}, {"list": ["endoscopy"], "text": "Respiratory, gastrointestinal, and esophageal candidiasis require an endoscopy to diagnose."}, {"list": ["duodenum", "fungal culture"], "text": "For gastrointestinal candidiasis, it is necessary to obtain a 3–5 milliliter sample of fluid from the duodenum for fungal culture."}, {"list": ["colony-forming units"], "text": "The diagnosis of gastrointestinal candidiasis is based upon the culture containing in excess of 1,000 colony-forming units per milliliter."}, {"text": "Candidiasis may be divided into these types:"}, {"text": "A diet that supports the immune system and is not high in simple carbohydrates contributes to a healthy balance of the oral and intestinal flora."}, {"text": "While yeast infections are associated with diabetes, the level of blood sugar control may not affect the risk."}, {"text": "Wearing cotton underwear may help to reduce the risk of developing skin and vaginal yeast infections, along with not wearing wet clothes for long periods of time."}, {"text": "Oral hygiene can help prevent oral candidiasis when people have a weakened immune system."}, {"text": "For people undergoing cancer treatment, chlorhexidine mouthwash can prevent or reduce thrush."}, {"text": "People who use inhaled corticosteroids can reduce the risk of developing oral candidiasis by rinsing the mouth with water or mouthwash after using the inhaler."}, {"text": "For women who experience recurrent yeast infections, there is limited evidence that oral or intravaginal probiotics help to prevent future infections."}, {"text": "This includes either as pills or as yogurt."}, {"list": ["antifungal medications", "clotrimazole", "nystatin", "fluconazole", "voriconazole", "amphotericin B", "echinocandins"], "text": "Candidiasis is treated with antifungal medications; these include clotrimazole, nystatin, fluconazole, voriconazole, amphotericin B, and echinocandins."}, {"list": ["caspofungin"], "text": "Intravenous fluconazole or an intravenous echinocandin such as caspofungin are commonly used to treat immunocompromised or critically ill individuals."}, {"list": ["clinical practice guideline"], "text": "The 2016 revision of the clinical practice guideline for the management of candidiasis lists a large number of specific treatment regimens for Candida infections that involve different Candida species, forms of antifungal drug resistance, immune statuses, and infection localization and severity."}, {"text": "Gastrointestinal candidiasis in immunocompetent individuals is treated with 100–200 mg fluconazole per day for 2–3 weeks."}, {"text": "Mouth and throat candidiasis are treated with antifungal medication."}, {"text": "Oral candidiasis usually responds to topical treatments; otherwise, systemic antifungal medication may be needed for oral infections."}, {"list": ["in the skin folds (candidal intertrigo)", "nystatin", "miconazole"], "text": "Candidal skin infections in the skin folds (candidal intertrigo) typically respond well to topical antifungal treatments (e.g., nystatin or miconazole)."}, {"text": "Systemic treatment with antifungals by mouth is reserved for severe cases or if treatment with topical therapy is unsuccessful."}, {"text": "Candida esophagitis may be treated orally or intravenously; for severe or azole-resistant esophageal candidiasis, treatment with amphotericin B may be necessary."}, {"text": "Vaginal yeast infections are typically treated with topical antifungal agents."}, {"text": "A one-time dose of fluconazole is 90% effective in treating a vaginal yeast infection."}, {"text": "For severe nonrecurring cases, several doses of fluconazole is recommended."}, {"list": ["suppositories", "douches"], "text": "Local treatment may include vaginal suppositories or medicated douches."}, {"text": "Other types of yeast infections require different dosing."}, {"list": ["Gentian violet", "breastfeeding"], "text": "Gentian violet can be used for thrush in breastfeeding babies."}, {"text": "C. albicans can develop resistance to fluconazole, this being more of an issue in those with HIV/AIDS who are often treated with multiple courses of fluconazole for recurrent oral infections."}, {"list": ["pregnancy", "imidazole", "triazole"], "text": "For vaginal yeast infection in pregnancy, topical imidazole or triazole antifungals are considered the therapy of choice owing to available safety data."}, {"list": ["transplacental"], "text": "Systemic absorption of these topical formulations is minimal, posing little risk of transplacental transfer."}, {"text": "In vaginal yeast infection in pregnancy, treatment with topical azole antifungals is recommended for 7 days instead of a shorter duration."}, {"text": "No benefit from probiotics has been found for active infections."}, {"list": ["central nervous system"], "text": "Systemic candidiasis occurs when Candida yeast enters the bloodstream and may spread (becoming disseminated candidiasis) to other organs, including the central nervous system, kidneys, liver, bones, muscles, joints, spleen, or eyes."}, {"list": ["intravenous"], "text": "Treatment typically consists of oral or intravenous antifungal medications."}, {"list": ["echinocandin", "caspofungin"], "text": "In candidal infections of the blood, intravenous fluconazole or an echinocandin such as caspofungin may be used."}, {"list": ["Amphotericin B"], "text": "Amphotericin B is another option."}, {"list": ["intensive care units", "mortality rate"], "text": "Among individuals being treated in intensive care units, the mortality rate is about 30–50% when systemic candidiasis develops."}, {"text": "Oral candidiasis is the most common fungal infection of the mouth, and it also represents the most common opportunistic oral infection in humans."}, {"text": "In the Western Hemisphere, about 75% of females are affected at some time in their lives with a vaginal yeast infection."}, {"text": "Esophageal candidiasis is the most common esophageal infection in persons with AIDS and accounts for about 50% of all esophageal infections, often coexisting with other esophageal diseases."}, {"text": "About two-thirds of people with AIDS and esophageal candidiasis also have oral candidiasis."}, {"list": ["sepsis"], "text": "Candidal sepsis is rare."}, {"text": "Candida is the fourth most common cause of bloodstream infections among hospital patients in the United States."}, {"list": ["Hippocrates"], "text": "Descriptions of what sounds like oral thrush go back to the time of Hippocrates circa 460–370 BCE."}, {"text": "Vulvovaginal candidiasis was first described in 1849 by Wilkinson."}, {"text": "In 1875, Haussmann demonstrated the causative organism in both vulvovaginal and oral candidiasis is the same."}, {"text": "With the advent of antibiotics following World War II, the rates of candidiasis increased."}, {"list": ["nystatin"], "text": "The rates then decreased in the 1950s following the development of nystatin."}, {"list": ["bird of the same name"], "text": "The colloquial term \\"thrush\\" refers to the resemblance of the white flecks present in some forms of candidiasis (e.g. pseudomembranous candidiasis) with the breast of the bird of the same name."}, {"text": "The term candidosis is largely used in British English, and candidiasis in American English."}, {"text": "Candida is also pronounced differently; in American English, the stress is on the \\"i\\", whereas in British English the stress is on the first syllable."}, {"list": ["genus", "species"], "text": "The genus Candida and species \'\'C."}, {"list": ["Christine Marie Berkhout", "University of Utrecht"], "text": "albicans\'\' were described by botanist Christine Marie Berkhout in her doctoral thesis at the University of Utrecht in 1923."}, {"text": "Over the years, the classification of the genera and species has evolved."}, {"text": "Obsolete names for this genus include Mycotorula and Torulopsis."}, {"text": "The species has also been known in the past as Monilia albicans and Oidium albicans."}, {"list": ["nomen conservandum\'\'"], "text": "The current classification is nomen conservandum, which means the name is authorized for use by the International Botanical Congress (IBC)."}, {"text": "The genus Candida includes about 150 different species; however, only a few are known to cause human infections."}, {"list": ["pathogenic"], "text": "C. albicans is the most significant pathogenic species."}, {"text": "Other species pathogenic in humans include \'\'C."}, {"text": "tropicalis, C."}, {"text": "glabrata, C."}, {"text": "krusei, C."}, {"text": "parapsilosis, C."}, {"text": "dubliniensis, and C."}, {"text": "lusitaniae\'\'."}, {"text": "The name Candida was proposed by Berkhout."}, {"list": ["toga"], "text": "It is from the Latin word toga candida, referring to the white toga (robe) worn by candidates for the Senate of the ancient Roman republic."}, {"text": "The specific epithet albicans also comes from Latin, albicare meaning \\"to whiten\\"."}, {"text": "These names refer to the generally white appearance of Candida species when cultured."}, {"list": ["pseudoscientific"], "text": "A 2005 publication noted that \\"a large pseudoscientific cult\\" has developed around the topic of Candida, with claims up to one in three people are affected by yeast-related illness, particularly a condition called \\"Candidiasis hypersensitivity\\"."}, {"text": "Some practitioners of alternative medicine have promoted these purported conditions and sold dietary supplements as supposed cures; a number of them have been prosecuted."}, {"list": ["National Institutes of Health"], "text": "In 1990, alternative health vendor Nature\'s Way signed an FTC consent agreement not to misrepresent in advertising any self-diagnostic test concerning yeast conditions or to make any unsubstantiated representation concerning any food or supplement\'s ability to control yeast conditions, with a fine of $30,000 payable to the National Institutes of Health for research in genuine candidiasis."}]', '{}', '{}', '{"desc": "Clotrimazole, nystatin, fluconazole", "list": ["Clotrimazole", "nystatin", "fluconazole"]}', '[{"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Human_tongue_infected_with_oral_candidiasis.jpg", "file": "File:Human tongue infected with oral candidiasis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Human_tongue_infected_with_oral_candidiasis.jpg/300px-Human_tongue_infected_with_oral_candidiasis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3d/Candidal_infections.webm", "file": "File:Candidal infections.webm", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Candidal_infections.webm/300px-Candidal_infections.webm"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/Derm-57.jpg", "file": "File:Derm-57.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Derm-57.jpg/300px-Derm-57.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2c/Toefungus.jpg", "file": "File:Toefungus.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Toefungus.jpg/300px-Toefungus.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/84/Yeast_Infection.png", "file": "File:Yeast Infection.png", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Yeast_Infection.png/300px-Yeast_Infection.png"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/da/Candida_albicans_PHIL_3192_lores.jpg", "file": "File:Candida albicans PHIL 3192 lores.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Candida_albicans_PHIL_3192_lores.jpg/300px-Candida_albicans_PHIL_3192_lores.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/38/Vaginal_wet_mount_of_candidal_vulvovaginitis.jpg", "file": "File:Vaginal wet mount of candidal vulvovaginitis.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Vaginal_wet_mount_of_candidal_vulvovaginitis.jpg/300px-Vaginal_wet_mount_of_candidal_vulvovaginitis.jpg"}, {"url": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d5/Esophageal_candidiasis_(2)_PAS_stain.jpg", "file": "Image:Esophageal candidiasis (2) PAS stain.jpg", "thumb": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Esophageal_candidiasis_(2)_PAS_stain.jpg/300px-Esophageal_candidiasis_(2)_PAS_stain.jpg"}]');

